insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-39-1','10','57','Song, dance, and clothing were used by African slaves to convey messages, and the song and dance of present-day African-Americans is very similar.  The dancing, storytelling, and music of the Inshangi family for schoolkids is used to show how such traditions of Africans can be conveyed to present-day African Americans.  Lessons were taught in this performance, such as the importance of watching what you say, and proverbs were also told, as well as the use of dancing and humor to convey important traditions and messages.  After the performance, Russell states the three things that prevail throughout: family, hospitality, & worship.\r\nThey also talk with Katherine Blackwell about present-day children, and she emphasizes the notion that children all over the world are the same and are affected in similar ways by storytelling.  Blackwell works with African-American schoolchildren to connect them to their African roots and get them to be more informed about their ancestry.  The episode finishes with Russell emphasizing the importance of the exchange between African-Americans and indigenous Africans, and that these exchanges will unify both groups.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-39-2','10','57','Darryl Wood interviews John Conyers about such questions as whether civil rights policies now overlook the needs of African-Americans & whether the greater focus on women and homosexuals dilutes the cause of blacks.  He asks him such questions as whether we really need to continue to fight for enforcement of civil rights, how we can look at changing peoplesâ€™ present-day perceptions, issues of concern about where the funding for civil rights is going, and how we can maintain progressive action for black Americans.  Conyers responds to such questions by conveying his belief that we must recognize that we are moving into an era of human rights rather than just civil rights, and that even though other aspects of the civil rights struggle are obscuring African-American causes, blacks still are predominant in most of the groups that are being fought for.  In addition, he discusses what we should be doing to maintain progressive action and how such controversial and confusing issues such as reparations should be approached.');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-39-3','10','57','There is the problem of young people bringing guns to school (esp. in response to death of student Chester Jackson, Jr. in a Detroit school).  Because of this tragic event, assemblies were held in several schools to get staff/students/parents together in discussion about this problem & how to enforce safety & security.  Questions raised were: What can parents do?  How can they get more involved?  The interviewees stress that they should talk to their children & prevent them from carrying weapons to school, and at the assembly they also had to sign the â€œParent Commitment Pledge.â€  In addition, the school will get more involved in getting those parents and students who werenâ€™t in attendance at the assemblies to help.  \r\nOther questions raised in the discussion had to do with policies regarding students with weapons.  Are sweeps and metal detectors constitutional?  Should separate facilities be arranged for â€œproblem studentsâ€ who have had to be removed from their schools?  Should any of these policies be changed?  These were the overall issues of discussion.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-39-4','10','57','Darryl Wood interviews the jazz musician Wynton Marsalis about his achievements, awards, accolades, etc.  Marsalis first addresses the question of how he has been able to handle all of the public response and hype surrounding his career, stating that he tries not to focus too much on the press and the media.  He emphasizes that one of the biggest changes that results from fame is a personâ€™s relationship with their peers.  Wood follows this by asking the question of how one should act as they rise to the top of jazz musicianship and become a star.  Marsalis believes that publicity isnâ€™t necessarily based on achievement, so the way a person acts outside of their musicianship is often focused on much more than their playing itself.  Therefore, there is no one certain way that a young musician can be told to act.\r\n	Wood goes on to ask the question of what Marsalis thinks his music achieves, both musically and socially.  Marsalis states that the main goal of his and his fellow musiciansâ€™ music is to encompass and convey the American experience, bringing all eras of people and music together.  He also stresses that music that he writes develops even more if he can become familiar with the players who will perform it first.  He often tailors his compositions and must have the players work together because each is different.  Woodâ€™s most difficult question for Marsalis has to do with what message he believes his own music is conveying to the public in this time.  Marsalis states that he tries to get across a sense of what he has struggled through in his life and the obstacles he has had to overcome.  The two also discuss the importance of preserving jazz music in order to preserve its messages of humanity, history, and personal experience, which is more important than simply oneâ€™s race, and relate this to Marsalisâ€™ inspiration for his composition Blood on the Fields.  They finish by discussing the â€œjazz geniuses,â€ such as Louis Armstrong and Coltrain.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-39-5','10','57','In this installment of Detroit Black Journal, host Ed Gordon interviews the Mayor of Detroit, Coleman Young.  The two first discuss the controversy surrounding the renovation of the Detroit Airport, in which, during construction, bodies were disinterred from a nearby cemetery and moved.  Issues dealing with this interment had to do with Southwestern Airlines\' desire to lengthen a runway and also dealt with the problem of revenue versus expense for the city, as well as possible ramifications for taxpayers.\r\n	Moving on from this issue, Gordon brings up the topic of the upcoming presidential election, citing the mayor\'s statement that he couldn\'t support Jesse Jackson wholeheartedly because he doesn\'t believe the nation is ready for a black president.  He asks Young to discuss this issue and his viewpoints on Michael Dukakis, questioning why Young couldn\'t just state that he believed that Dukakis would make a better president and leave it at that.  They discuss how the possible presidential candidates approach the problem of improving conditions for blacks that had been worsened, in Young\'s opinion, during Reagan\'s term.  Following this, the show is opened to questions from callers.\r\n	Some of the questions brought up by callers and discussed include how casino gambling will affect Detroit and how Young can contribute to help solve problems facing the youth of Detroit, mainly those having to do with the job market and getting a good education.  Young also presents his plans for establishing a more equitable distribution of wealth and what he thinks should result from companies going overseas.  The next caller broaches the issue of city expansion, development, and renewal projects, including the possibility of a downtown shopping center along Monroe Block and a people mover rail system.  \r\n	The next big issue that is discussed is the drug problem in the city, especially the new \"crack down\" policy that the mayor has implemented, which some people are very happy with and others are particularly opposed to.  Young stresses the desperate need that the city has for rehabilitation facilities, especially because most of the city\'s crime is committed by people who are somehow in contact with drugs, and getting them help is extremely important.  Another caller asks about the Brewster Douglass Projects, and what the mayor\'s plans are for improving that area.  He discusses how he has attempted to provide new or renovated units for habitation.  The last caller asks him what his future political plans are, and he says that he plans to run for reelection.  Gordon asks whether he will \"groom a successor\" for if he chooses to step down at some time, and Young replies that it is not so much about \"grooming\" a successor, but about preparing the younger generation for what to expect and how to approach politics if they do decide to go into that field.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-39-6','10','57','The show opens with performances rom Hal McKinney and The Brothers of Music, who perform \"Cornerstone.\"  It then moves on to a segment of the show called \"Grapevine.\"  In it, Sandy Lawrence starts by covering community announcements and details, upcoming events, and entertainment news.  She covers news about Florence Ballard, the former member of the Supremes, Kim Westin, an actress performing in \"Halleluiah Baby,\" and highlights a book by Elsie Archer, \"Let\'s Face It.\"  She then names the Together Sister of the Week Roslyn Russell, a medical secretary.\r\n	Following Lawrence\'s segment, the show moves to Tony Brown, who presents Part Two on the Olympic Revolt.  Part Two covers how black athletes Tommie Smith and John Carlos decided to make a political statement at the 1968 Olympic games in Mexico City in order to bring attention to the racial injustices occurring in the United States. As the American flag was raised and national anthem played, the athletes bowed their heads and raised their black-gloved fist to a Black power salute. Their actions supported the larger movement of the Olympic Project for Human Rights (OPHR) committee who had originally wanted Black athletes to boycott the game. The OPHR had encouraged a boycott to demonstrate their unhappiness with the inequality and injustices that Black American were experiencing, in hope of exposing the hypocrisy of a government that expounded democracy yet treated Black Americans as second class citizens. The following clip with host Tony Brown was taped at the when the boycott was in full swing. Brown interviews Harry Edwards the boycott organizer, former Black Olympic champions, and men and women on the street to gage their support for the boycott. \r\n	One of the creative aspects of the show is the incorporation of \"Public Service Announcements\" that take a satirical look at black identity.  The \"Free Your Mind\" clip that follows Brown\'s segment explores the complexity of integrating ones public and private identities. Essentially, at the heart of the message is the idea that Black Americans may feel that in order to succeed in the corporate America they must assimilate and either imitate or adapt Eurocentric characteristics.  It is only in private, among family and friends, that the ethic identity can be fully embraced. The clip challenges viewers to question if the two selves can ever be fully reconciled and brought together. Thus achieving professional success while still being true to oneâ€™s ethic identity.\r\n	After the \"Free Your Mind\" clip, the Brothers of Soul play a musical selection, and this ends Part 1 of the program.  Following the break, the show returns with its \"People and Places\" segment, which covers local and national news.  In this day\'s program, the topics covered consist of the lack of black appointees at city agencies, Nixon\'s election, the formation of the National Afro-American Police League, the International Conference of Black Writers (with authors C.L.R. James and Stokely Carmichael are keynote speakers), and O.J. Simpson\'s weekend football victory.  Following this segment of the show, the next musical guest, Bill Davis, gives performances of both \"Quiet Nights\" and \"The Trolley I\'d Like to Ride.\"\r\n	After this musical performance, the show welcomes its second special guest, who is interviewed by Tony Brown.  She is named Martha Jean Steinberg, known better by community members as Martha Jean the Queen, discusses her organization, â€œThe Forgotten People.â€ Her organization is geared at blue-collar workers and focuses on self-sufficiency, positive thinking and building self-esteem.  After this interview, another musical selection is performed, this time by the Inkster Community Choir.\r\n	To finish the program, the CPT Players give a performance of a scene from Langston Hughes\' The Life of Jesse B. Semple.  Langston Hughes, often associated with the Harlem Renaissance, was known for his thought provoking and rich portrayals of Black life in America. He wrote novels, short stories and plays, as well as poetry. His most famous fictional character is Jesse B. Semple, nicknamed Simple. The Simple character used humor and satire to comment on inequality and injustice occurring throughout the nation. In the following clip, the â€œCPT Players,â€ act out one of the simple stories, which is set in a boarding house.  Sempleâ€™s friend tries to correct his â€˜broken Englishâ€™ and his meddling landlady sets out to reforms his â€˜immoralâ€™ behavior. \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-39-7','10','57','The setting for the show, in which Charlayne Hunter-Gault interviews Bishop Desmond Tutu, is a town hall meeting where the audience and individuals who phone in have an opportunity to participate in the discussion. Given the nature of the show\'s format many topics are interwoven into the conversation, sometimes being addressed more than once in the show. The following is an outline of some of the main issues covered in the order in which they are discussed on the show.\r\nShell Oil \r\nIn the first segment Tutu talks about the American protest that are occurring against Shell Oil Company. He says, â€œThese protests in America are extremely important for two reasons. It boosts the morale of the victims of apartheid by letting them know that people all over the planet care. Also it undermines the image of Shell Oil. International opinion is more important to them than they would like you to believe. This is why they have banned TV from showing what is going on. The government keeps looking for scapegoats on the unrest in South Africa. But they are avoiding the main issue, we have warned them that until apartheid is gone, anything they do will be peripheral to the real problem.â€	\r\nThe Complexity of Apartheid \r\nHe then addresses the struggle against apartheid by noting, We inhabit two worlds. They have a different perception and live in a different world. I think the gap has widened. They are adept at semantic games, and telling you about all the things they intend to do.â€ â€œWe need a total dismantling of apartheid, we need an end to the state of emergency, we need troops pulled out, exiles and political prisoners returned to their homes. They will not do it of their own accord, I have never heard of any people willing to share power. On the issue of violence, if I were younger I would\'ve rejected Bishop Tutu long ago. A small boy told me one time: Bishop Tutu, show me what you have gained for us with all of your eloquent talk on peace, and I will show you what we have accomplished with a few stones.â€	\r\nUnited States Intervention\r\nIn his fight against apartheid Tutu maintained that sanctions imposed by international business and governments was vital to dismantling the system. He states, â€œReagan has set sanctions on Libya , Nicaragua , etc. But when it comes to South Africa Reagan claims that the sanctions will hurt those who they intend to help. Why is this so? This was not an issue with any other countries he has applied sanctions to, why South Africa ? International intervention is necessary to prevent a catastrophe in South Africa .â€ He brings this issue up again at the end of part II stating, â€œ70% of blacks in South Africa are asking that sanctions be imposed. I think there are similarities between all people who are denied basic rights. The Palestinians are seeking territory, so there are similarities.â€ â€œIf your government would apply the same policies it applies to Nicaragua , then there would be no apartheid in South Africa .â€	\r\nMandela\r\nTutu speaks on the significance of Mandela as a symbol: â€œHe is a Martin Luther King for us, every struggle needs a leader who is charismatic and truly dedicated to the struggle. Nelson Mandela is head and shoulders into South Africa more than anybody I know. The government\'s only predictability is in how unpredictable they are. The way they are dealing with Winnie Mandela. Nelson Mandela is not free, and you would figure the government would worry about him dying in prison. Some say that the South African government is like a centipede that is trying to shoot itself in every foot.â€	\r\nTribalism\r\nTutu speaks on tribalism: â€œWe are de-tribalized, my mother is of one tribe and my father is of another. The governments of the world like to use tribalism to mean strife. Problems are not synonymous with tribalism, there are no tribes in Northern Ireland .â€	\r\n	\r\nComparisons to the Civil Rights Movement \r\nTutu addresses the difference between the Civil Rights movement in the U.S. and the struggle against apartheid in South Africa: â€œThe difference between the civil rights movement and our struggle in South Africa, here there was a Constitution that guaranteed rights and the law was theoretically on their side. In South Africa, the constitution is against us.â€	\r\nReligion\r\nTutu discusses his religious teachings: â€œI am now Bishop of Johannesburg. I talk to white audiences in a spiritual way and they realized I do not have horns and a tail, and do know a thing or two about the bible. There are a lot of white people that have so much lose but want to see change very badly. Donâ€™t think that white people in South Africa are all demons because they are not. They are simply human beings, and many of them very scared human beings.â€	\r\nTension in South Africa\r\nTutu addresses the increased tension in South Africa: â€œThere is an increase in South African blacks that are willing to choose violence over negotiating, now that negotiations are proving themselves to be unfruitful. The children put us adults to shame when it comes to bravery. Confronting the police and troops, they are dodging bullets.â€	\r\n');
