insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-1','119','59','Song, dance, and clothing were used by African slaves to convey messages, and the song and dance of present-day African-Americans is very similar.  The dancing, storytelling, and music of the Inshangi family is used to show how such traditions of Africans can be conveyed to present-day African Americans.  Lessons taught in this performance include the importance of watching what you say.  Dancing and humor is used to convey important traditions and messages.  After the performance, Russell states the three things that prevail throughout: family, hospitality, and worship.\r\nThey also talk with Katherine Blackwell about present-day children, and she emphasizes the notion that children all over the world are the same and are affected in similar ways by storytelling.  Blackwell works with African-American schoolchildren to connect them to their African roots and get them to be more informed about their ancestry.  The episode finishes with Russell emphasizing the importance of the exchange between African-Americans and indigenous Africans, and that these exchanges will unify both groups.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-2','119','59','Darryl Wood is joined by Motown Records founder Berry Gordy, and they start out talking about Gordy\'s autobiography \"To Be Loved,\" with Wood asking why it took so long for him to share anything about Motown in intimate detail.  Gordy says that he wants to share his experience with young people who share his life of struggle, and show them how he managed to build such a company and show them that it is possible.  He wants people to understand clearly how a company such as Motown was developed, mainly through competition, and he doesn\'t want inner-city young people to give up their dream, so he wants them to understand the work that was put into building up the organization.  Gordy also wrote the book to discuss the history and the legacy of Motown, and wants to make sure that people understand that the book was written for a variety of reasons.\r\n	Wood then addresses how it didn\'t always look to Gordy like he would \"make it,\" and how he faced adversity and doubt at a young age when he was starting out.  Gordy was a songwriter and a dreamer, so he was often looked at as though he wasn\'t doing much with his life.  Starting out, Gordy\'s family gave him a loan to cut a record and get the organization going. They treated it as a professional loan, and Gordy signed a contract and promised to pay it back.  This led to Gordy having to pay good attention to the financial aspects of the label, which contributed to his strong work ethic and sense of responsibility.  His sister was in charge of watching his money as it grew, and then Motown developed into a family affair, because they had such a strong involvement in it.  \r\n	Wood then talks about how Gordy addresses extremely personal issues in his book and opens up old wounds for the world to see, and he asks Gordy why he chose to do that.  Gordy responds by saying that he has to take full responsibility for his life, and that many of his personal experiences are shared by other citizens and people who are reading the book.  He wants to make clear that he is proud that he was a normal person who was forced to overcome his own problems.  He believes that, on a basic level, everyone is the same and wants the same things, and everyone should share the ideas that they come up with.  He believes that people do not fulfill their potential because they are afraid to speak their mind and just want to be safe.  \r\n	Wood talks about the chronological nature of the book, following from the start of the Gordy clan all the way up through to Barry\'s life at present.  One of the points in this chronology is when Gordy was forced to work for his father, even though he hated it, because his father wanted him to learn the principles of a good day\'s work.  Gordy\'s relationship with his father also taught him that finding god doesn\'t necessarily come from going to church, but rather from one\'s actions.  This gave Gordy the belief that one can never be truly happy unless they are proud of themselves.  He also believes that communication and spreading of one\'s learning is extremely important.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-3','119','59','The show opens with a recording of one of Bobby Seale\'s speeches in Oakland in the 1960s about what blacks want, need, and are entitled to in the world.  Seale is then introduced as a guest on the show and the interview begins.  Seale starts by discussing the changes that have occurred in the struggle and the movement, one change being that activists in the struggle have stopped attacking the system and found better ways to promote change.  He discusses the Black Panther Party, and talks about how the civil and human rights aspect of the struggle did not leave blacks with a \"practical, ideological goal objective.\" The result has been that many present-day blacks are not aware of what was done in the \'60s nor are they familiar with the people involved and events that took place in that struggle.  \r\n	The host, Ron Scott, then goes on to ask Seale about what led  to him becoming Revolutionary Chairman of the Black Panther Party.  Seale says that he started out in the struggle simply because of anger and frustration at racist society, but without a great deal of education and knowledge.  Following his service in the Air Force, attending college, and his work as a comedian, he developed more of a consciousness about what was occurring, but he still \"stumbled into the struggle.\"  After the creation of smaller organizations and activist groups, Seale and his comrades eventually founded the Black Panther Party.  \r\n	Scott then goes on to introduce \"The Lonely Range,\" which Seale describes as his autobiography.  Many people have said that in the book Seale doesn\'t lay out an exact pattern for liberation, but Seale says this is because one cannot recreate in the \'80s exactly what the \'60s was like; things change.  He also talks about his love for author Richard Wright, and his adoption of his style in his own writings.   \r\n	They move on to talk about how black males often suffer violent upbringings, suffering things such as whippings from their fathers. Seale believes that this is one of the reasons that people grow up to be violent as adults.  \r\n	Scott then asks Seale why he decided to leave the Black Panther Party.  Seale talks about knowing that they weren\'t going to be doing the same things in the future as they had done in the past, wanting to get into something else, wanting to rest, his desire to write his autobiography, and his knowledge that they were in a \"down period,\" where not much was occurring.  He wanted to move on to new things, and didn\'t want to stand and \"toll the bell on something that was dwindling.\"\r\n	Questions are then taken from the audience.  The first man asks Seale about his plans for the future, given that most of the leaders of the \'60s are all gone, and does he feel like the struggle was worth it.  Seale believes that it was, and describes the organization that he has put together, \"Advocates Seen.\"  He believes that the \'80s have to be about political organizing at the city level, which he believes this program will help. He also wants to earn his law degree and pass on the activism to the younger generation.  The next audience member addresses the issue of the inherent problems of black men and women that were brought up earlier (e.g. that of violence), and asks how they can address these problems of the \"apathetic\" people so that they can be ready to take over the struggle and organizations such as Advocates Seen.  Seale says that he believes people were actually more apathetic in the \'60s, and that he thinks it is possible to reach blacks through the work of many people.  He has hope for the future of the struggle, and he doesn\'t believe that everything is dead.  A third audience member asks if Seale has some constructive ideas that can be implemented on the community level to continue the education of the younger generation and communication.  Seale believes it\'s important that organizations are taught how to put periodicals together, and that schools are given guidance as to proper curriculum.  \r\n	Scott asks if it is truly possible for blacks to take over any communications apparatus, such as TV and mass media, as he suggested was necessary for proper education.  Seale says that many blacks do not recognize the large amount of talent that exists in the black communities across the country.  He thinks that blacks must understand that attending college and getting a proper education is imperative no matter what they want to do, whether it is to get a good job or be a member of the struggle.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-4','119','59','Russell is joined by Ernest C. Dillard, Jr., a local historian and projects manager with the United Auto Workers.  He is the author of Civil Rights in the 1990s: Race at the Crossroads, and Russell starts by posing the question to him of what he means by \"crossroads.\"  Dillard believes that they are at a stage where there is the opportunity for potentially great progress, but only if they choose to do the right thing.  In his book, Dillard says that blacks are on equal footing with whites legally, in terms of things such as voting rights, but there are new issues that need to be addressed.  These legal rights were the result of actions such as Martin Luther King.  \r\n	Russell asks where they should now be focusing their attention, if it is no longer necessary in the legal and political arenas.  Dillard believes that economic rights should be a strong focus, arguing that there is a \"black condition,\" where unemployment and crime are common in the black community.  He goes on to talk about what they should be doing to address these problems. He brings up Affirmative Action, which he states he is a believer in but says he thinks has stark limitations.  Dillard highlights that blacks are not alone when it comes to economic strife, and there are a great deal of whites facing those problems as well.  He thinks that blacks and laborers and liberals should \"hook up\" on issues such as economics and education, where they tend to share common perspectives.  He believes in working together to solve such problems, mainly because the majority of the population, whites, have the most influence when it comes to voting on issues and creating change, and also because they share the economic problems of the blacks.  \r\n	They then go on to show interviews with citizens, as well as David Duke, a losing candidate for Louisiana governor\'s, public presentation, about their reflections on the civil rights movement and how they feel about present-day circumstances.  \r\n	Russell asks Dillard what makes him think that blacks and whites can come together, and he also wants to know his perspective on David Duke.  He believes that he is an \"opportunistic white politician who gets elected by misleading white people.\"  He also thinks that, in order to bring whites and blacks together, there needs to be an expose of how politicians such as Duke use the race question, and there needs to be political education of the people.  Whites and blacks need to understand that both whites and blacks share the same economic problems, and that whites have the majority of it, but that it is a shared struggle as well.  He believes that many whites have been fooled into thinking that blacks are at the root of their problem when it is really the result of something else.  \r\n	Russell also asks what blacks should be doing for themselves, and whether there is a role for self-determination.  Dillard says that yes, blacks should help blacks, but he stresses that the area he\'s talking about is the political.  He also thinks that one of the reasons racist white politicians can get away with working the race question is that liberal whites are uncomfortable taking them on, because they think theyâ€™ll be seen as \"lovers of blacks.\"  He thinks the big lie that blacks and whites have been operating under for many years is that blacks are the problem.  \r\n	To finish, Russell tells the audience that there is a video library called Eyes on the Prize that they can use to teach their heritage to their children.  Then, they show a clip from Martin Luther King at the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-5','119','59','Darryl Wood is joined by scholar, author, and lecturer Dr. Cornell West, who is there to discuss his new book.  West has been called many things, including an \"endangered species,\" and Wood begins by asking his guest what he thinks that means.  West replies that it could mean any black man with self-love and self-respect in modern-day life is a dying species, or that people who are seriously connected to a political struggle are a dying breed.  West has been quoted as saying that \"our capitalist civilization is killing our minds, bodies, and souls in the name of the American Dream.\" Wood asks him to explain this comment.  West believes that the system allowed the market to \"run amok\" in the past, which created a market culture and market mentality.  He says that historically, people are bombarded with this market culture. When things that are not involved in the market, such as parenting, take on this mentality, the result is \"gangsterized\" culture and politics.  \r\n	Wood then asks whether, as people move through capitalist society, West\'s goal is to create a more \"humane form\" of a capitalist society, or whether it is to change capitalist mentality to something else.  West says that it is both short-term and long-term: it is partly about keeping poor working people alive and active, and also providing access to politics and opportunities.  He fears that radical Democratic policies are waning, and that they have been left with a global capitalism.  He says that there have to be countervailing forces against the market mentality and global capitalism, and that this would involve democratization.   \r\n	Wood moves on to discuss the new movement, or \"obsidian society,\" in which West finds himself partnering to create.  West describes such as society as a foundation that would generate funds to reinvest in the black community, mainly in black young people.  He says is it would give out genius awards to inner-city youth, funding their outstanding intellectual, academic, and artistic pursuits, and he describes it as a kind of \"philanthropic endeavor\" that involves a \"re-channeling of resources into communities that are in need of investment.\"  He also says that it would involve black celebrities using their public stature to make a difference in society, and Wood asks him what he thinks could make this possible.  West gives the names of some black celebrities, such as Harry Belafonte, who have used their leverage to promote strong movements within the black community.    \r\n	Wood then addresses the issue that blacks are always seen as acting as a group, and questions whether they need to get out of their situation and support new economies and institutions that West proposes.  West says that transforming the larger society would have to involve multi-racial coalition and alliance, but these would be stronger if black solidarity was stronger, and he doesn\'t think there is a way around this solidarity.  Woods expands on this idea of multi-racialism to say that other races\' concerns all tend to get lumped in with black concerns and the black community.  He asked whether, with the net effect of diluting black solution, a coalition can truly be put together with that dynamic existing.  West says that blacks signify a certain kind of suffering that has been experienced in America, and there is no way they can separate any form of suffering from any other forms.  Their challenge is to make sure that their mission and message is not diluted, but they must also keep it broad enough that it encompasses all forms of suffering so that they don\'t get the worst of mainstream society.  He says that the black freedom struggle has never been solely about black interests, and that it\'s in the interests of all peoples\' freedom and equality.  \r\n	Wood moves on to discussing West\'s latest book, Restoring Hope: Conversations on the Future of Black America, which has a lot to do with internal qualities, such as integrity and sacrifice.  He asks what the place is of all these qualities in restoring hope, and West says that they serve to remind us of all those who came before and transmit to present-day blacks the terms of struggle and to focus on the terms of sacrifice and institution-building that came before them.  West describes how they are living in a large generation gap, where people are so shaped by market culture that their relation to their past is increasingly distant.  \r\n	West discusses the principles and ideas of Harry Belafonte at length in his book, and Wood asks West whether this was his favorite interview in the making of the book.  West says that his interview was mind-blowing, because he provides so much insight and information on so many ideas and topics.  He is also a strong believer in Belafonte\'s vision and message.  Wood also talks about West\'s interview with Charlayne Hunter-Gault, who talks about having to \"insulate herself\" in society and pass hope on to others.  West talks about having to be able to push aside the oppressive views and natures of society and having to have self-respect and dignity in order to remain strong and influential.  \r\n	Wood then jumps to the end of the book, where Maya Angelou equates hope with love, and he asks who West thinks will help black America love itself again.  West believes that it\'s the artists, the great singers, painters, writers, etc., that can help spread the message of the importance of self-love and hope.  \r\n\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-6','119','59','Cliff Russell sits down with leading Metro-Detroit black auto dealership owners and discusses their perspectives on minorities and the automobile industry.\r\n\r\nSummary: The episode opens with a remote report from Diana Craig discussing the upcoming plans for the Big Three for the automotive year.  \r\nCliff Russell begins by expressing the difficulties of owing a car dealership in Detroit, and introduces his four guests: Mel Farr, Charles Harrell, Theresa Jones and Nathan Conyers.\r\nRussell begins by expressing amazement that he is joined by four black car dealers who are still in business, however Farr downplays this notion, saying that the worst has passed economically.  Conyers claims that 16 black owned dealerships in the State of Michigan is significant, and predicts that the number is bound to go up.  \r\n	Russell asks the group what it will take to increase the number of African Americans in the car dealership business, and Harrell says that the success of current black dealers will persuade more African Americans to enter the business.  Russell then asks what it takes to be qualified to run a dealership, and Jones suggests that the most important factors are training and having qualified employees to help operate the dealership.  \r\n	The group then goes on to discuss the issue of support from the auto companies, and how it affects their business.  Jones compliments Chrysler on their support; however Conyers suggests that manufacturers may not be doing enough to encourage black owned dealerships.  The group reflects on Ed Davis, the first black dealer for a Big Three automaker, and the progress that has been made during the past half a century.\r\n	Russell begins to take calls, and the first caller suggests that black dealerships may have difficulties because they are based in poorer, inner city neighborhoods.  The caller also recognizes the problem of credit in the inner city poor.  Farr agrees on the callerâ€™s points, and Harrell comments that auto dealers can potentially help people with credit problems.\r\n	The second caller addresses the view that women are not treated the same as men during an automobile purchase.  Jones comments that large parts of her business are female consumers, and that she cannot afford to treat them poorly.  Conyers comments on the change of culture in America, and advises females to not accept poor treatment.\r\nHarrell echoes those sentiments, saying that females or minorities should not tolerate false truths.  \r\n	The third caller inquires into the process of becoming an automobile salesperson, and both Farr and Conyers both implore listeners to reach out to dealerships if interested in employment in the auto dealership business.  \r\n	Another caller laments on the service of sales representatives after the car has been sold.  Farr denounces this treatment and stresses that his dealership depends on return customers.  \r\n	The group then discusses the myth that automobiles purchased from white dealerships are of higher quality.  Jones stresses that all dealerships receive the same cars from the companies and Conyers suggest that it might be a social problem.\r\n	Russell thanks the panel for joining him and then stresses the importance of the auto industry.  After suggesting viewers call the hotline telephone number, he reminds viewers about the North American Auto Show. \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-7','119','59','Darryl Wood is joined by civil rights activist and national talk show host, the Reverend Jesse Jackson.  Wood begins by addressing the issue of the current political situation, in particular recent speculation that Colin Powell might run for president.  Wood asks whether Jackson thinks that America is ready to elect a black president. Jackson is unsure: he highlights Powellâ€™s good qualities as a possible candidate, but notes that the question is of priorities and values, such as the problem of the urban crisis, which no one is addressing.  Jackson believes that significant issues must be addressed in the upcoming presidential race.  \r\n	Wood goes on to ask whether the lack of black mobilization to vote is influenced by the fact that certain issues such as the urban crisis are not generally addressed by politicians.  Jackson agrees, but he believes that mobilization without connections to public policy is not enough.  Jackson addresses his reputation for surrounding himself with a wide range of activists, such as Louis Farrakhan, and he says that one must be judged not by association, but by what they do themselves.  He hopes, through his coalitions, to push for an overall goal of fairness and equality.  \r\n	If alliances are formed, Wood asks, can they accomplish all that they hope to if they are extremely diverse, or should they be more focused on \'black issues\' and associate mainly with blacks.  Jackson says that racial justice and gender equality are black issues, but there are other issues, such as welfare, that were beneficial to whites first.  He says that none of these issues will be resolved until blacks and whites can come together, eliminate race designations to social problems, and fight as an alliance.  \r\n	They then go on to talk about who it is that champions the cause for unemployed blacks, and Jackson says that the leadership has to come from blacks, who must â€œurge for changeâ€ and â€œstrike the first blow.â€  However, a broader base of people must take action in order to implement true change, especially to the problem of racist jail policies.  Jackson says that it is necessary that good economic policies and commercial success can come to urban areas.  \r\n	Wood then asks what blacks must to in order to mobilize their communities.  Jackson believes that a specific plan of action must be developed, in which each person understands the goals for which they are working and what steps they must take to get there.  They move into talking about Jacksonâ€™s possible next run for the presidency, and Woods asks when he will announce his bid to run, which Jackson says that he is unsure of.   He is reluctant to run again and would rather that President Clinton honor his campaign priorities. If he does not address the urban problems, however, Jackson says that he will be forced to challenge Clinton.  However, he would rather support the President in his campaign, as long as he follows through on his campaign promises.  Jackson describes his possible run for president as an â€œopen question.â€  \r\n	Jackson finishes his interview, and then the program moves on to a discussion of the Jeffries Housing Project, part of the program Art in the Urban, run by Project REACH.  Deborah Franklin, one of the founders of this program, is interviewed. She says that the program developed out of a perception that the needs of black children were not being met.  She hopes to use art and cultural demonstrations and activities to bring self-esteem to the children of Jeffries residents.  She believes that giving these children self-esteem will enable them to reject antisocial behavior and pursue a better future.  Rene Lowe, another worker for REACH, is interviewed, as are residents such as Lois Williams.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-8','119','59','This show pays tribute to the works and teachings of Martin Luther King, Jr. It opens by profiling a conference held to teach teenagers how to use nonviolent methods to deal with their problems, which included a trip to the Martin Luther King Center for Nonviolent Social Change in Atlanta, Georgia. The students were touched by the trip, as many of them having never traveled outside of Detroit before.  At the center, they were taught the six principles of non-violence: 1) Non-violence is a way of life for courageous people, 2) Non-violence seeks to win friendship and understanding, 3) Non-violence seeks to defeat injustice, not people, 4) Non-violence holds that suffering can educate and transform, 5) Non-violence chooses love instead of hate, and 6) Non-violence believes that the universe is on the side of justice.  They then learned how to implement the principles they had learned through the six steps for non-violent social change: 1) Information gathering, 2) Education, 3), Personal commitment, 4) Negotiations, 5) Direct action, and 6) Reconciliation, and attended information and participation sessions where they talked about their experiences with violence and non-violence, and how to use their new tactics for non-violence.  They also got to mingle with and meet other black students from all over the country.  \r\n	The group also meets Coretta Scott King, who started the center and has continued to be involved with it.  She expresses that it is her commitment to Martin Luther Kingâ€™s dream that keeps her going and keeps her fighting for her principles, including the formation of a true community, the elimination of evils in society, and helping people to believe in themselves.  She wants this center to institutionalize Kingâ€™s teachings and message, and believes that it is important to create a program that works with all ages of people.  She says that her contribution would be to make sure that Kingâ€™s vision and dream of a â€œbeloved world communityâ€ would become a reality, and she believes that the King center is an answer to that.        \r\n	King goes on to talk about the struggles that the black community still faces today. She notes that, at the present time, there are fewer blatant signs in society of segregation, so many  young people donâ€™t always see obvious ways in which they can get involved.  She believes that this is one opportunity that the center can offer young people, along with hope and the opportunity for them to believe in themselves.  She also believes that multiculturalism is imperative for peace and for the formation of true community, where people can find common ground and learn to live with people of a variety of circumstances and characteristics.\r\n	She goes on to say that the highlight of her life was in 1964, when King received the Nobel Peace Prize for his work and for developing a method of struggle that could help liberate people.  This seemed to â€œaffirm all that had been done,â€ and was the greatest moment of fulfillment that she ever had.  \r\n	The show closes with a clip from Kingâ€™s famous â€œI Have a Dreamâ€ speech.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-9','119','59','This show is entitled â€œTo Be Woman, Gifted, and Black: From One Generation to Another,â€ and host Gene Elzy begins by saying that they will be talking with singer Lena Horne and writer/poet Nikki Giovanni, who have been touring together across the country.  Horne, who has also been an active member in the civil rights struggle, is the first interviewee.  \r\n	Elzy first poses the question as to whether the road to success for the black performer has changed over the years.  Horne believes so, and says that the present generation does not face the same stresses of her generation.  She does, however, believe that her generation was fortunate to have been able to listen to and draw from the black stars of earlier years.  He also asks her about what disciplines she learned as a young child that now carry her over into her present-day performing.  She states her belief that â€œthe show must go on,â€ and she was always taught to be professional and disciplined, no matter what.  \r\n	Horneâ€™s grandmother was a very good friend of Mary McCloud Bethoon, and Horne had the opportunity to meet her. Horne was enlisted by her in the National Council of Negro Women, and she was the main reason that Horne is a Delta.  Horne also talks about the strength of present-day black women, saying that they are as strong as past black women, but for different reasons.  \r\n	Horne then is asked to provide any thoughts she has for young entertainers who are going to have to â€œfight that fight.â€  She doesnâ€™t think theyâ€™ll have the same stresses, but she knows that itâ€™s rough economically at the present time for both whites and blacks, and she has learned to be more sympathetic to all sorts of people.  \r\n	Horne talks about her upcoming retirement from cabaret, and says that although she wonâ€™t be singing in that kind of setting anymore, she will continue to give concerts and do TV appearances and shows.  \r\n	The next interview is with Nikki Giovanni, starting with a discussion of her new book, â€œCotton Candy on a Rainy Day,â€ and whether it is different from her previous works or more personal and different.  She sees it as an outgrowth of her first book, and rather than being a departure, it is a natural maturation.  She stresses the importance of learning and growing from experiences.  She also talks about her decision to be a writer, and says that â€œthe form chooses the writer,â€ and every writer has his or her own discipline.  \r\n	She says that she would not be able to think of herself as a typical black woman, but what she shares with other black women is a strong curiosity and a desire to make things better.  She hopes that she can be helpful to black women in any way possible, because she believes that they are a great asset to the world.  She also believes that through her work, she will pave the way for other black poets to make their own mark on the world.  She sees it as a constant kind of progression, where children take up where parents left off and other citizens draw on peopleâ€™s examples.  \r\n	She also talks about how women are most certainly the backbone of families, because they are the ones who teach the children.  She supports men, but stresses that the family is â€œset by the woman.â€  She is then asked what she thinks the seventies brought and what she believes the eighties will hold for black men and women.  She thinks that the eighties will bring new definitions for life, men, women, and more, and give people new senses of what everything truly is.  Blacks will also be in the unique decision to create the definitions.  \r\n	Giovanni has been quoted as saying she was disappointed by the fact that the books published now hardly give any contribution to the black contributions of earlier times, especially the sixties.  She talks about how children believe that they are educated and are the way they are only because of the contributions of white people, and they donâ€™t realize and understand the contributions of blacks.  She states that there is â€œnothing unique in white history,â€ and the culture of America comes from the blacks.  She believes that blacks must reclaim who they are.  She believes that people who see themselves as educated really are not, and must draw on other medium, such as books, to become better educated.  Literature and reading is extremely important, and she talks about how she read to her unborn child while pregnant.  \r\n	Elzy finishes by asking her where she thinks her writing is going.  She is unsure, but sheâ€™s playing with the idea of trying to write a novel.  She is interested in exploring human beings, so sheâ€™ll write to accomplish this in any way she can.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-A','119','59','When this show aired in 1992, the underprivileged of Detroit were finding increased struggle in many aspects of life.  The show opens with the comments of Governor John Engler on this issue. He stresses that the state will work to improve the situation for the underprivileged through welfare reform, enterprise zones, and private control and ownership of public housing.  Following the clip, Russell states that this installment of the show will probe the issues of public housing.  City Councilman Keith Butler and Michigan State Housing Authority appointee and president of Habitat for Humanity Metro Detroit Kevin Fobbs join Russell.  Ruth Williams, a civic activist and resident of the Herman Gardens public housing project is on the phone, as well as Bob Armstrong, from Omaha, Nebraskaâ€™s Housing Authority.  \r\n	Russell starts by questioning Butler, who is a point person on the housing issue, asking him to characterize the housing situation in the city of Detroit, as well as prospects for the future.  Butler is a strong advocate for housing, mainly for people who canâ€™t afford high-income housing. He believes that the state has serious problems in this area, particularly in helping those who are struggling.  The city is demolishing housing that he believes can be refurbished and reused.  Fobbs gives his perspective on where they are in terms of housing in Detroit, saying that Habitat has built 72 units of housing, and if they follow this example, they could potentially rehab several hundred units of housing.  \r\n	Russell then goes back to Butler, who has placed blame on  administration mismanagement for much of the housing problem.  He asks how the city is destroying homes when he said they could be rehabilitated.  Butler says that the administration is not nearly as involved s they should be, allowing some housing to become uninhabitable and then demolishing it rather than seeking to fix the problems.  Fobbs then talks about how Habitat works and how the program fits into the overall scheme of public housing in Detroit.  He says that Habitat rehabilitates several thousand homes every year through volunteer work, and they work to keep families and neighborhoods together by building groups of housing units and giving them to those in need.  It is volunteer and private sector.  \r\n	They then discuss MSHDA, the Michigan State Housing Development Authority, and Russell provides a definition of the organization.  It sells tax-exempt interest bonds and notes and taxable bonds for its support and oversees subsidized rental housing and the Neighborhood Grant Program.  \r\n	Russell talks about the monies coming in to Detroit that are used to fund the housing system, and how these monies may or may not have gone through the proper channels.  This issue is being used as a â€œpolitical football,â€ and he questions Butler about his and his departmentâ€™s role in all this.  Butler says that the city refused to use the money properly that was allocated to it.  They then go on to talk with Bob Armstrong, who has been working for public housing in Omaha.  Armstrong says that Omaha attacked the issues facing public housing by putting together a long-range plan with all the organizations involved.  Very few cities want to put together such long-range plans, but these are the most successful ways to combat housing problems.  Ruth Williams then comes on the phone to give her perspective about what is going on at Herman Gardens and what she would like to see in the future.  She says that they have finally decided to open up units to be lived in, but these units have been vacant for a long time, and she thinks there should be turnover every thirty or forty days, which they are not doing.  She also says they donâ€™t have sufficient lighting, and conditions arenâ€™t good, with drugs rife in the housing development.  \r\n	They then take calls on the phone.  A man wants to know why the government causes there to be involvement in the landlordsâ€™ business.  Butler says that the Public Housing Authority separates the government from the housing issue, and he believes that they need to work to separate the authorities from the landlordsâ€™ business.  Fobbs states his belief in tenant management, and he thinks that the ultimate goal is to have tenant ownership and management.  He says the question of public housing is how quickly they can turn it over to the private sector (to get rid of public housing in the long-term).  The next person on the phone wants to know what plans or models the city of Detroit, in cooperation with the Federal Government, has to address this problem inside the city.  Butler says that an action team was sent to the administration, and theyâ€™re working to make sure that the monies to help fix this problem are distributed properly over time.  \r\n	Armstrong says that the first step to getting things done is to have everybody sit down together and develop a long-range plan.  He does not agree with the idea that public housing should at some point be abolished, but he agrees with having good management, whether it is tenant management or a different type.  He says that the goal of public housing should be to provide temporary housing for those who are struggling, but they should work to make sure that this is only temporary and not permanent housing for individuals.  \r\n	Russell asks whether the current setup of public housing discourages some of the good things they discussed, such as pride in oneâ€™s neighborhood and a lack of crime.  Butler says that the lack of empowerment and involvement of residents creates problems.  Ruth Williams agrees with him.  Another caller asks why recently vacated buildings, such as a local hospital, canâ€™t be utilized as housing with all their available space.  Apparently Councilman Kelley has been floating this idea to people, and they believe it is a good idea, although it has not been picked up yet.  \r\n	The show finishes with a segment on the North American Auto Show.  While only a few car models  are still made in Detroit, they still hope that citizens will support Detroitâ€™s economy when it comes to their decisions about purchasing cars.    \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-B','119','59','This interview focuses on the problems facing a new generation of urban youths, and Jackson begins by talking about what blacks must do to help turn things around.  First, they must say that things such as drugs, rape, and crime must be seen as morally wrong and a societal wrongdoing.  He says that men must also â€œbear the burden of their behavior,â€ as well as fight for  more jobs and better housing.  He believes that people need a greater sense of personal responsibility.\r\n	Gordon then asks Jackson what he sees as the reason for why things are so particularly bad now, when blacks have always faced oppression.  Jackson says that rural and urban crime are quite different, and also that behavior has become extremely centralized. Through the mass media, the same picture of an acceptable lifestyle is given to people all over.  He says that disc jockeys, program directors, athletes, and other mass must exercise some â€œsocial judgmentâ€ about what messages they are sending to youth.\r\n	They then take calls. The first caller, a high school instructor, wants to know how he can tell his students that education and religion are a better option than drugs and crime.  Jackson believes that he canâ€™t do it by himself, but he believes that the instructor can challenge those students one-on-one who approach him about such issues.  The next caller wants to know what can be done to reduce teenage unemployment.  Jackson talks about how a new Senate leadership was elected that is more focused on employment issues, and says that people who have the vote must exercise this power to push for more jobs and increased employment.  He believes that the youth are not taught how to use their vote.  The third caller asks Jackson what sorts of suggestions he has in terms of curbing teen violence in urban areas.  He replies that they must â€œcrowd against itâ€ and create a â€œclimate to make it intolerable,â€ as well as making sure that the law cracks down hard on people who carry weapons and instigate violence.  He also believes that the desire to cause violence is a socializing process that must be reversed through the work of citizens themselves.\r\n	Gordon asks Jackson what must be done in order to get the male role model back in the community.  Jackson says that mothers must not give up if the man is not around, and also men must be oriented towards their responsibility as fathers, and it must be seen as unacceptable that men donâ€™t provide for and care for their children.  \r\n	Another caller is taken, and they want to know whether he thinks South Africa had anything to do with the death of Samora Michelâ€™s.  Jackson believes that it definitely had a hand in this, which didnâ€™t contact the Mozambiquan government until nine hours after the plane crash, resulting in the death of many people.  He says that they also used beams to redirect the plane off course.  Also, the Defense Minister of South Africa threatened Michel two weeks before the plane went down.  \r\n	Gordon gets back to talking about the issue of youth, and the problem of drugs is mentioned, which Jackson sees as the number one threat that faces them.  He believes that they should not make the mistake of thinking that youth are the only ones involved in drugs.  Rather, the epidemic involves all kinds of people.  They should know where the drugs are coming from and protect their borders from the incoming drugs, they should institute better drug education, and they should also make sure that their mass educators promote the message that drugs are destructive and dangerous.  \r\n	Another call is taken from the phone lines, and this is a Detroit high school student who wants to know what they can do to keep drugs and weapons out of schools when there arenâ€™t that many armed guards at the schools.  Jackson says that first the student must themselves say no to drugs, and then they must be ready and willing to use whatever means is necessary to prevent such things from getting into the schools.  He supports the idea that schools should use means such as metal detectors in order to make educational institutions safe havens away from violence and drugs.  Jackson is a firm believer that society can afford to secure schools.  The last person who calls in wants to know what Jackson thinks will happen to the large bodies of people graduating from school who are illiterate.  Jackson thinks that they will struggle greatly unless there are adult literacy programs that can help them, and therefore young people must be urged to become literate.  \r\n	Gordon then asks whether the program Push Excel, which worked to bring together students, parents, teachers, and administrators, might be reinstated in order to help the educational system again.  Jackson believes that certain schools are promoting the good mentality of people being welcomed at and privileged to be at school, but this mentality must be spread and people must understand that they must live with the consequences of their own actions.\r\n	They close the show with Whitney Houstonâ€™s song, â€œThe Greatest Love of All.â€\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-C','119','59','Gordon starts by asking Jackson whether he sees himself running for president in the 1988 campaign. Jackson says that it is premature to approach this idea now.  He does have concerns for his family; he has received threats that if he runs they will be hurt. He is also unsure whether or not he would get an adequate amount of money for the campaign.  He also needs a good deal of support from citizens, and must be able to change the direction of politics.  Gordon also wants to know whether blacks are a viable alternative as candidates for high office, especially following the events and politics of 1986.  Jackson talks about the breakthroughs of â€™86, when four new black Representatives were elected, and when several whites were beaten out for certain government positions.  He believes that these elections proved that people with civil rights priorities could win in the deep South.   He also says that more people have gotten involved in the voting process, making it even more possible for blacks to be elected.\r\n	Gordon says that some Democrats feel that Jackson is too liberal, but also that he is trying to become more palatable to whites, and he asks Jackson for his response to these things.  Jackson first questions what group of people it is that sees him as too liberal, and demonstrates through his policies and actions that he has been pushing for moving in directions that are the best for the country.  He also looks at the makeup of the nation, where there is a strong imbalance in power and wealth.  Jackson then moves on to address the question of whether he is trying to become more palatable to whites, and he says that although many white politicians are working to implement policies that he has supported for many years, this does not necessarily mean that he is selling himself to them.  Rather, the nation is â€œcoming back toward reality.â€  \r\n	Gordon then asks whether Democrats are taking blacks for granted and also whether Jackson is disappointed in the number of blacks that are voting.  Jackson says that Democrats are taking blacks for granted, but they will be less able to in the future when the black vote becomes stronger.  He also addresses, however, that there is an â€œanesthetized conscienceâ€ in the country that promotes racist viewpoints and actions, and this needs to be addressed.  Jackson then says that, although many fewer blacks vote than who actually can, the fact that the number of blacks voting keeps increasing and that progress is being made, he cannot be disappointed in it.  \r\n	Gordon addresses the question of whether black America needs to stop helping the government as much and focus on their own problems.  Jackson believes that there are two sides to the issue, whereas many of black Americaâ€™s problems can be fixed by changing behaviors, such as refraining from using drugs and alcohol.  However, blacks also need things that only the government can provide, such as better housing and education.  Thus, they must be able to have influence in the political arena and be able to influence governmental policies.  \r\n	They then move on to talk about Jacksonâ€™s trip to Africa and how it influenced him.  Jackson believes that African Americans can never be a complete people until they connect with their motherland and go back to their roots, and he describes how he was touched by this history.  However, seeing the horrible conditions in some parts of the continent also hurt Jackson and moved him to look at the African countriesâ€™ struggle and comparing their strife to Americaâ€™s insensitivities to their plight.  Also, although some American companies have divested from South Africa, Jackson is not impressed with these actions, because they have still not shifted power into the hands of blacks, but rather put more power into the hands of fewer whites.  He also believes that companies in the Reagan era feel no pressure for affirmative action and to hire blacks, and therefore there has been a drop off in the hiring of black workers.  \r\n	In several of the books about Jacksonâ€™s run for president, they tend to describe him as a â€œcalculating opportunist,â€ and Gordon questions what Jackson feels about that.  Jackson says thatâ€™s simply their opinion, and he does not get brought down by it.  Jackson also talks about the present-day black agenda, which is to have blacks exercise their voting rights, resist Reaganâ€™s â€œhostile acts,â€ and run for political office.  He is staunchly against the Reagan administration, and knows that blacks are working hard to resist many of his policies.  \r\n	The show closes with Aretha Franklin singing, â€œLook to the Rainbow.â€\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-D','119','59','Darryl Wood interviews John Conyers about such questions as whether civil rights policies now overlook the needs of African-Americans and whether the greater focus on women and homosexuals dilutes the cause of blacks.  He asks him such questions as whether we really need to continue to fight for enforcement of civil rights, how we can look at changing peoplesâ€™ present-day perceptions, issues of concern about where the funding for civil rights is going, and how we can maintain progressive action for black Americans.  Conyers responds to such questions by conveying his belief that we must recognize that we are moving into an era of human rights rather than just civil rights, and that even though other aspects of the civil rights struggle are obscuring African-American causes, blacks still are predominant in most of the groups that are being fought for.  In addition, he discusses what we should be doing to maintain progressive action and how such controversial and confusing issues such as reparations should be approached.');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-E','119','59','This is the anniversary of the birth of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., and host Ed Gordon is joined by former civil rights activist and Georgia State congressman Julian Bond.  Bond is going to be on the upcoming PBS series â€œEyes on the Prize,â€ and Gordon starts by asking Bond what the series is about.  Bond says that itâ€™s about the American civil rights years and a look at the civil rights movement itself.  He thinks that it shows that there was a time in history when ordinary people created a movement that, in the space of 10 years, completely changed the face of the American South.  Bond and Gordon mention that many present-day young people donâ€™t know much about the history of the movement, and that even those who participated in it don\'t always know what happened outside their own area. This show aims to give people a clearer picture of the 10-year period they are focusing on.  \r\n	Some of the footage from Eyes on the Prize is then shown, focusing on the struggle for voting rights, looking at some of one of Martin Luther Kingâ€™s speeches, and examining the Selma, Alabama protests, civil unrest, and night march.  Gordon, following this clip, asks whether modern-day black Americans are too complacent, and Bond says that this isnâ€™t necessarily it, but rather that people are just uneducated.  Indeed, these events did not happen that long ago, but many are forgetting or simply unaware that they happened.  Bond also talks about how the show not only examines the 10 years and the changes that occurred, but also highlights the everyday people and â€œsmall figuresâ€ who made a difference in that struggle.  \r\n	Another clip from Eyes on the Prize is shown, in which Governor Wallace of Alabama and President Lyndon B. Johnsonâ€™s react to the Selma, Alabama demonstrations and Johnsonâ€™s decision to introduce a comprehensive voting rights bill.  \r\n	They then move on to look at modern-day civil rights.  Bond says that they are better off because the legal enforcement of segregation in the South is gone, but he believes that, in some ways, they are worse off, because the divide between blacks and whites sometimes seems even clearer.  Bond believes that, in order to change these things, blacks must utilize their political power to the greatest extent possible.  \r\n	Gordon then asks Bond what it was like to run for a congressional seat in Georgia, especially because of the race issue that was raised with his opponent, John Lewis, and how the election seemed to split the community into blacks and whites.  Bond says itâ€™s an example of a victory that the civil rights movement won for them, because a black man was able to run against another black man.  He says it was upset to see that Lewis, who had claimed to be his friend for many years, ended up not being so.  Gordon also asks whether itâ€™s viable to assume whether blacks could become President or Vice President in the near future, and Bond, who they had attempted to get to run for Vice President in 1968, believes that yes, one must assume this, or else it wouldnâ€™t be possible. \r\n	Gordon also asks why Bond chose to stay so long in state government rather than moving onto a larger stage.  Bond says that he had to wait for the right opportunity, which came along in 1986, and even though he lost, he is happy he ran.  He hopes to keep moving on and trying new things, and this pushes him forward.  They also go back to talking about how civil rights relates to modern-day life, and Bond discusses how it matters greatly who gets elected to be President in the next couple years.  \r\n	Gordon finishes by asking whether there is a need for a summit for black leaders to sit down and find a path to go down in the future.  Bond believes that this isnâ€™t necessary, and that they already know what they need to do.  They must strengthen their economic endeavors, educational institutions, and increase their political strength and influence.    \r\n	The show finishes with more footage from Eyes on the Prize and Martin Luther King, Jr.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-F','119','59','This show takes an in-depth look at  Louis Farrakhan and his policies.  It starts out, however, by providing some history with footage from a press conference in Detroit with Farrakhan, about how Islam has great roots in Detroit and about Muslim leader Elijah Mohammed.  He talks about the growth and progression of Islam and about how blacks suffer from self-hatred and inferiority, which results in  economic, political, and civic struggle.  He discusses the \'Stop the Killing\' program that is now extending into the Detroit area.  \r\n	Rasul Muhammad, the Nation of Islamâ€™s local leader, joins Gallant to discuss these issues and Louis Farrakhan himself.  Gallant starts by asking what the organization is doing in regards to the \'Stop the Killing\' program.  Muhammad talks about how Farrakhanâ€™s message spurs blacks to take action.  They are planning for Halfway Homes, where people can stay, get back on track, and work towards independence, which he believes is essential for blacks to progress.  They want to encourage people to keep their living areas and communities in good condition, and have been working to go in and clean up housing projects.  \r\n	Another clip is shown from the press conference, where Farrakhan defends himself in regards to statements that he had made, some of which were seen as anti-Semitic.  He says that his words were distorted because whites  fear that Farrakhan could mobilize blacks and get them to take action in the community.  He also believes that he has been labeled as hateful because blacks have been taught to love all people except themselves.  He says that his critical analyses of Jews are simply critical, not anti-Semitic, and he hates that people refer to him as the â€œnew black Hitler.â€  \r\n	Gallant asks whether Muhammadâ€™s organization still gets a lot of repercussions from Farrakhanâ€™s remarks.  Muhammad says that the repercussions come mainly from their own people who are ignorant of the facts.  The Nation of Islamâ€™s position is that because their people suffer extremely, especially in relation to recognition of oneâ€™s identity, separation is the answer until education takes place, and then the country can begin to interact with others.  They want a separate state geographically, as long as the white government continues as it is.  \r\n	A third clip is shown from the news conference, addressing the issue of whether American blacks are entitled to reparations, comparing their plight to that of the Japanese-Americans who did receive reparations.  Farrakhan demands that they receive some form of reparations from the government, and is frustrated with the current allocation of government money.  \r\n	Calls are then taken from viewers.  The first caller wants to hear Muhammadâ€™s views on the underlying problems in Iraq.  He believes that they have no need to be in Iraq fighting for causes and conditions that have nothing to do with their own needs and values.  He thinks that they sometimes get too involved in issues abroad and forget about their own issues, and believe that the Iraqis should be left to handle their own problems.  The next caller wants to know what Muhammad has to say about the seemingly anti-Semitic and anti-Christian views of the Islamic community.  He believes that if all people, no matter what their religion, practice the principles of god, then it is â€œonly the title that keeps them away from one another.â€  He is firm that there â€œis no anti-anything, as long as you are pro-god.â€  The third caller wants to know why Muhammad isnâ€™t very visible and active in the community.  He talks about how they have a few hundred active, working supporters in the community, and he says that he himself has been doing a lot of travel, so he hasnâ€™t been that visible.  But he hopes that they will soon be very visible in the community in the times to come.  The fourth caller wants to know how black people can understand the psychological damages from slavery that still affect them today.  Muhammad says that all community leaders should come together, and blacks must have self-sufficiency.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-10','119','59','Elzy begins by discussing Ossie Davis and Ruby Deeâ€™s fame as entertainers, both on screen and television, where they present their interpretation of drama, poetry, dance, and music.  Now, they have a new PBS television series called â€œOssie and Ruby,â€ where they â€œportray an anthology of the human spirit.â€  Ossie Davis is with Detroit Black Journal today to give an interview.\r\n	The interview starts with a discussion of what the series is about.  Ossie says that itâ€™s a continuation of what he and Ruby have been doing their entire careers, a show in which they hope to provide the world with a look at influential black culture, with looks at its poets, novelists, artists, and others who have made strong cultural contributions.  He says that people featured will be both known and, on occasion, unknown to the general public.  Ossie talks about how, although he is busy, he and Ruby find time to do this show because they truly love doing so and they care so much about it.  \r\n	He goes on to discuss how he and wife Ruby got into their careers, and talks about how, as struggling actors, they were desperate for a way to make money.  In looking around at their community, they saw that if they went around to where black people were located and performed works by people such as Langston Hughes and Phyllis Wheaton, they could get paid for this.  They found that if they â€œcultivated this audience,â€ their own people, they would always find work, and as they continued in their work, they branched out and found even more material to use.  Then, as curriculum for blacks was expanded and branched out at the university level, they found even more places where their work was needed (on campuses).  \r\n	Elzy poses the question to Davis, â€œCan anyone act?â€ and Davis responds that yes, anyone can, and goes on to elaborate.  He talks about as, throughout oneâ€™s life, as you are put in different situations, you have to assume different roles and act as different versions of oneself.  Your environment influences how you act, and Ossie believes that acting on-stage is essentially no different than the â€œactingâ€ that one does in everyday life to adapt to different situations.  He stresses, however, that although young people who wish to pursue acting should do so, they should first remain in school and learn to read, write, and use the English language well.  They cannot just go out and wait for the entertainment industry to pick them up.  Rather, they must prepare themselves and develop in their homes and at school before they pursue a career in the entertainment industry.  \r\n	Next, they show a clip of Ossie Davis and Ruby Deeâ€™s program.  In the clip, Davis highlights Louis Armstrong and his experiences working with him in film.  He discusses the sometimes heartbreaking nature of always having to â€œput on a faceâ€ and make everything funny, rather than exposing oneâ€™s true, often conflicted and unhappy, self.  He talks about how Armstrong and others must hide their manhood deep inside just to survive in the world that they live in.\r\n	Ossie says that the programs will start to air February 14th at 7:30, and he hopes the audience will participate and help continue the show on past its first 13 episodes (the season).   He also stresses the variety that will be present in the programs, each differing from the one before it and providing a variety of scenarios, performances, themes, emotions, etc.  They are also going to feature interviews with prominent people such as Sterling A. Brown.  \r\n	The show then takes a few questions from the audience.  The first woman asks Davis if he has any ideas as to how they can develop control by community participation in putting on black shows as they want them to be put on.  Davis talks about how the television industry is about to change immensely with the addition of satellites and cable.  He believes that smaller groups and stations will then have the chance to make themselves heard and do their own thing, but this means that blacks must immediately work to protect their stake in cable television, ensuring that they will be able to do what they hope to for their own people.  The next person asks why there arenâ€™t any black dance and theater workshops in Detroit, and if there are, wants to know whether there is the possibility of bringing any of the top black talents into Detroit.  Davis states that, as an outsider, he canâ€™t speak authoritatively on the subject of Detroit, but Elzy says that there are indeed workshops and programs in the area, and they both agree that there still are not enough, and one must work hard to search out what is available and let entertainers know that they want them to come.  Everyone must be vocal.  The third question comes from a male in the audience who is also an actor, and he wants to know how Davis manages to keep a sense of perspective and sense of humanity in an often cruel and ruthless business.  Short on time, Davis gives the brief answer that his humanity lies in the hands of all his brothers and sisters, and that when he â€œruns short,â€ he asks them to give it back.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-11','119','59','Gordon is joined by two Detroit School Board members, Clara Rutherford and Alonzo Bates, to talk about the recent criticism and scrutiny that has been directed towards and placed on the school board for its actions.  Gordon begins by reading a statement made by the Superintendent of Schools, saying that financial issues are the biggest problem for the school district.  He then asks Bates whether he thinks the board is spending too much money on travel and other perks.  He says no, and that board members do not create travel, and have rather tried to eliminate excessive amounts of it.  They do travel, but only to beneficial conferences and forums that can educate them and make them better board members.  Gordon goes through figures that highlight high spending on travel, especially in regards to spending money on first class travel.  Bates says that this cannot be considered excessive when one looks at the million dollars brought in by the board to the school system.  He also notes the high amount of international travel that was done, which could contribute to the $15,000 spent on travel in fiscal year 1986.\r\n	Gordon then addresses Rutherford, asking whether perhaps, because of the deficits the school system is facing, they should step back and amend some practices, such as traveling coach instead of first-class.  She does not attempt to defend traveling first class, and attempts to look at the fact that there is still eight million dollars in the budget, and the fact that there are many board members in other school districts who receive a large amount of that money and perks that those who are not on the Detroit School Board do not.  She also talks about ways in which they have worked against helping reverse the deficit, such as raising wages for workers.  Both Rutherford and Bates feel that the board is being picked on, and Bates says that their lack of perks as board members is racially motivated.  \r\n	Gordon then goes to the phone lines.  The first caller asks Bates how previous abuse of perks justifies present-day abuse of perks, and what the proven benefits are of the trips that are taken.  Bates responds that he did not create board travel, and he feels that Bates Academy, a school for intellectually gifted kids that he created, is a result of his travel, and he feels that both he and the board have grown over time.  The next caller says that he sends his caller to a Catholic school because he would never send him to a Detroit school, and that people are tired of board members saying that because white people did certain things, then they should be entitled to do them too.  Rutherford says that, in sending a child to a Catholic school, that in itself is following white people, but Gordon pushes her to address the overall issue of the large number of people who do not want to enroll their children in the Detroit Public School system.  Rutherford talks about the issue of shootings, and feels that the Detroit Public Schools are the â€œcourts of last resort.â€  She laments the fact that they are poorly funded and provided with poor resources, but are expected to provide private schools with support.  \r\n	Gordon moves on to address the issue of chauffeurs, and board members allegedly using them for personal reasons and on their own time.  He asks their position on the chauffeurs for the board members.  Rutherford says that these drivers are used professionally to pick up checks and other things, and says that she doesnâ€™t believe that they are being used for personal reasons.  She also says that she feels safer after getting a driver to go places, because she has not been attacked as she was during her travels alone before.  Bates then laments the fact that the Board of Education is a â€œdumping groundâ€ for peopleâ€™s problems and issues.\r\n	Another call is taken, and he wants to know whether they are getting off track with uses of and discussions of travels and chauffeurs, and whether they should rather be focusing on the students and improving the school system.  Rutherford talks about Town and Countryâ€™s list of the top high schools in the country, and she mentions one of their own schools that were listed.  She also mentions programs that are being used to aid struggling students who need a bit more assistance.  She believes that they have an excellent school system in many ways.  The next caller is a teacher at Jesu School, who comments that he voted for both of the board members, but he believes that they are no longer upholding their policies that they presented when they first ran, and that they should spell out what their policies are so that people can understand them and vote for them up or down.  \r\n	Gordon mentions the scandal and litigation surrounding the resignation of board member Harold Murdoch, who was accused of accepting payola, and asks what the role of the board is in terms of awarding contracts.  Bates lashes out at Fickelstein, who he believes is attacking Bates and the board in regards to their policies and actions.  Rutherford also mentions how 52 percent of the boards monies go to minority contractors, and this was the sole purpose of their program.\r\n	Detroit Free Press columnist Susan Watson then provides her commentary on the issue.  She says that someone should tell them that they are elected to work for the students and not for themselves, and should not spend a good deal of money on personal perks.  She says that she thinks they believe that â€œgetting elected to the School Board is the same as winning the state lottery; all your dreams come true.â€  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-12','119','59','There is the problem of young people bringing guns to school (esp. in response to death of student Chester Jackson, Jr. in a Detroit school).  Because of this tragic event, assemblies were held in several schools to get staff/students/parents together in discussion about this problem & how to enforce safety & security.  Questions raised were: What can parents do?  How can they get more involved?  The interviewees stress that they should talk to their children & prevent them from carrying weapons to school, and at the assembly they also had to sign the â€œParent Commitment Pledge.â€  In addition, the school will get more involved in getting those parents and students who werenâ€™t in attendance at the assemblies to help.  \r\nOther questions raised in the discussion had to do with policies regarding students with weapons.  Are sweeps and metal detectors constitutional?  Should separate facilities be arranged for â€œproblem studentsâ€ who have had to be removed from their schools?  Should any of these policies be changed?  These were the overall issues of discussion.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-13','119','59','The interviewer starts off by asking whether or not Jazz has ever been played before.  Sun Ra claims that everything came out of Egypt, including Jazz.  True Jazz is creativity, a gift from the â€œcreatorâ€.  Jazz has been diluted due to the integration of African culture into the American mainstream.  Without a cultural structure, the music is lost.  Sun-Ra voices his concerts about the selfish, materialistic nature of the black music industry.  Due to this search for wealth, black musicians have become detached from black race and culture, and therefore have eroded the ethnic structures.  \r\nCiting a book titled â€œFrom Man to Supermanâ€ by J.E. Rodgers, he claims that the black raceâ€™s lack of a philosophy compared to white cultureâ€™s embrace of Greek philosophical teachings is one of the problems today.  \r\nRa then discusses his trip to Egypt, and reflects on the acceptance of his name and beliefs in Egypt and Egyptian embassies and how it contrasts with treatment he receives in the United States.  All of the â€œanswersâ€ can be found in Egypt, and Ra claims visits from heads of states as a reflection of this.  \r\nRay asks about a natural law controlling the whole universe, and Ra explains the perspective of the â€œspace peopleâ€ concerning laws.  Human law, despite what society may believe, is no the law of the cosmos, and has no provisions for dealing with supernatural beings.  He claims the hostile nature of human law is why extraterrestrial beings are hesitant to visit Earth.  However, he goes on to discuss the â€œAngel Race,â€ a group of people from Nigeria, whom he learned about through a newsreel, and went to visit.  Ra claims to be a member of this â€œAngel Raceâ€ due to his lack of error and his obsession with precision and disciple.  \r\nRay steers the discussion towards Raâ€™s musical performances, and Ra claims to have learned about music directly from the â€œCreator.â€  He discusses a superior form of music, not of the body or the mind, but of the spirit.  This music can be used as a force of change throughout the world.  Ra claims that â€œtruthâ€ was lost with the crucifixion of Jesus Christ and all that is left is the â€œmyth.â€  \r\nRa discusses the problem of black education, and suggests that black people must be taught differently then white children, in the ancient Egyptian style with Hieroglyphics, myths and statues.  Ra explains that the color black is inherently evil, and goes on to embrace his evil nature, and suggests that separation from white culture would not be a bad thing.  \r\nRay again steers the conversation back towards music, asking him about his musical influences.  Fletcher Henderson is discussed as a main influence, mainly due to his discipline and the ability for his group to play as one.  Ray inquires about Raâ€™s groundbreaking use of electronic instruments, and Ra considers this a reflection of his ability to observe future technology, specifically the space age.  Ray then inquires as to where Ra sees music and the world in general ending up in the future.  Ra states that God is not on the side of the blacks, only the whites.  Black people should expect a new, different kind of savior.      \r\nRay asks Ra if musicians are free, and he reiterates that he is not concerned with freedom, and claims freedom is analogous to death.  He states that his concern is discipline, especially in regard to his musical compositions.  \r\nThe show closes with a Sun-Ra performance as the credits roll\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-14','119','59','Darryl Wood interviews the jazz musician Wynton Marsalis about his achievements, awards, accolades, etc.  Marsalis first addresses the question of how he has been able to handle all of the public response and hype surrounding his career, stating that he tries not to focus too much on the press and the media.  He emphasizes that one of the biggest changes that results from fame is a personâ€™s relationship with their peers.  Wood follows this by asking the question of how one should act as they rise to the top of jazz musicianship and become a star.  Marsalis believes that publicity isnâ€™t necessarily based on achievement, so the way a person acts outside of their musicianship is often focused on much more than their playing itself.  Therefore, there is no one certain way that a young musician can be told to act.\r\n	Wood goes on to ask the question of what Marsalis thinks his music achieves, both musically and socially.  Marsalis states that the main goal of his and his fellow musiciansâ€™ music is to encompass and convey the American experience, bringing all eras of people and music together.  He also stresses that music that he writes develops even more if he can become familiar with the players who will perform it first.  He often tailors his compositions and must have the players work together because each is different.  Woodâ€™s most difficult question for Marsalis has to do with what message he believes his own music is conveying to the public in this time.  Marsalis states that he tries to get across a sense of what he has struggled through in his life and the obstacles he has had to overcome.  The two also discuss the importance of preserving jazz music in order to preserve its messages of humanity, history, and personal experience, which is more important than simply oneâ€™s race, and relate this to Marsalisâ€™ inspiration for his composition Blood on the Fields.  They finish by discussing the â€œjazz geniuses,â€ such as Louis Armstrong and Coltrane.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-15','119','59','The episode begins with a montage of Cockerelâ€™s moments on Detroit Black Journal.  Gallant gives a short introduction, and then takes a look at his past via comments from contemporaries, such as Jim Ingram, Erma Henderson and Carl Edwards.  Gallant then introduces the guests, and asks Ravitz how the community will recover following Cockerelâ€™s death.  Gallant also discusses the uniqueness of the Marxist leanings of both Ravitz and Cockerel.  \r\n	Gallant then asks Archer his perspective on the possibility of Cockerel being a candidate for mayor.  Archer suggests that Cockerel may have been considering a run for mayor, however still held the mayor in high regard, and Jack Russell shares this opinion. Russell continues, stressing Cockerelâ€™s wisdom and forward thinking.\r\n	Gallant and Hamlin then discuss Cockerelâ€™s relationship with the auto industry.  Hamlin explains that Cockerels recognized ways to have an impact during a struggle, and could identify with the plight of the black autoworkers.  Gallant brings up criticisms of Cockerel, particularly that he â€œsold outâ€ as his career progressed.  However, Hamlin refutes this statement as irrational.    \r\n	Archer and Gallant discuss the assertion that Cockerel, and perhaps all black men are â€œcasualties of the system.â€  Archer considers this an accurate assessment, and suggests that there are two few black social leaders who are being stretched thin.  Russell also discusses the demands placed on Cockerel, despite his attempts to relax and be a healthy human being.  \r\n	Archer comments on Cockerelâ€™s ability to downplay race, and tackle general human problems, and promote ideas of brotherhood.  \r\n	Gallant discusses the difficult legal cases taken by both Cockerel and Ravitz.  Ravitz then discusses Ravitzâ€™s ability to speak to people from all walks of life gave him the ability to tackle cases dealing with political and social experiments.  \r\n	Hamlin interjects to comment again on the importance of struggle in Cockerelâ€™s life.  Hamlin then reflects on the struggles that he and Cockerel faced during the race struggles of the 1960â€™s.  \r\n	Gallant then opens the phone lines, and the first caller asks how the remaining black leaders in Detroit can fill Cockerelâ€™s leadership role.  Archer then comments on Cockerelâ€™s legacy and academic excellence.  Archer also lauds his decision to become a public servant rather than cashing in on his abilities.  Hamlin then discusses the role of black youth in light of Cockerelâ€™s death.\r\n	Gallant then asks Russell what he will miss most about Cockerel, and he suggests that some of the extraordinary advances that will be made in the 90â€™s can be attributed to Cockerel, and that he will always be remembered through these accomplishments.  \r\n	The episode closes with comments from Cockerelâ€™s son.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-16','119','59','Host Cliff Russell introduces the episode by discussing the difficulties black youth face in a college atmosphere.  Before the episode beings however, the episode takes a look back at a previous episode dealing with the civil unrest after the Rodney King verdict.  Russell then shifts the focus back to the youth, and introduces his guests.  These are Darryl Dawsey, who was a spokesperson for the students during the Wayne State University protests, Byron Williams, a spokesperson for the Michigan African Student Coalition, Tomeka Mingo, Ms. NAACP, and Dr. John Telfert, from MOSAIC. \r\n	Russel begins with Dawsey, asking him what was behind the Wayne State University protests.  Dawsey claims that Wayne State has not made many movements in a positive direction, and it has not been true to itâ€™s word and has not given out scholarships for African studies or implemented student recommended courses.  He also says that during his time at Wayne State, the university was an area under white supremacy, and this has lasted.  \r\n	Williams then discusses his experiences at Olivet College, and talks about how the black students had to take a back seat to the white students in regards to course implementation and fraternities.  They seemed to be â€œforgotten about,â€ and white studentsâ€™ interests were much more focused on.  Williams says that the universityâ€™s actions were made to seem like they were not racially motivated, so because of this there was no open hostility.    \r\n	Mingo then comments on both college and high school campuses and how a lot of young people are not aware of the racial problems that still remain in todayâ€™s society.  She says that through certain programs, young people can become aware of these problems and find non-violent ways to resist and make their voices heard.    \r\n	Russel then introduces Dr. John Telford, who starts out by talking about white academia.  He discusses how many institutions fail to recognize that they are still functioning under a racist system, and the leaders of these institutions need to be sensitized.  He says that there are many educational leaders who either sweep the problem under the rug, or simply donâ€™t realize the gravity of the problem.  He also stresses that it must be whites, who are the countryâ€™s power structure, to voice the problem and take the leadership.  \r\n	Russell then asks Dawsey what he sees as necessary to effect change.  He responds that students should step up the pressure on the administration, and also stresses that white students as well as blacks should be required to take Africana Studies, because whites are not the majority, and understanding African history and culture is necessary for coexistence and good relations between races.\r\n	Diana Craig, a correspondent for DBJ, went out to local campuses, and interviews with students reveal their viewpoints that different races donâ€™t understand each other and that races have been separated.  \r\n	DBJ then goes to the phones, and the first caller wants to know whether it was a good idea to walk out on Olivet College to make change in the system.  Williams says that it was unfair to them as students, because the administration didnâ€™t work to make things safe for them and upheld a hostile environment.  The next caller comments that there is a need for all cultures to be exposed to their cultural heritage early in life, and also wants to know what the panel thinks in the universityâ€™s role in exposing students to cultures prior to high school and college.  Telford says that itâ€™s essential that all students receive an education that covers the heritage of a wide variety of cultures in order to grow up accepting of all cultures.  Mingo comments that African American history classes are offered at her high school that students are required to take in order to graduate.  \r\n	A person from the audience comments that, when he was in college, he saw that black students who transferred from a predominately white college to a black college found that they were able to escape the racism and problems that they had faced.  He advocates that more young adults go to historically black colleges, because he says that at such institutions one receives more of a foundation, and one can then move on to universities that are whiter.  Dawsey disagrees a bit, and says that someone doesnâ€™t have to go to college to learn what it means to be black or white, but stresses that all people, respective of their choice of university, begin to discover their heritage and its importance early on.  \r\n	The next caller, a white college student, agrees with the fact that there is white racism occurring that restricts the opportunities for blacks, and asks for whites to be let in more to learn about black culture.  Williams comments that whites who want to help the black cause should try and change the viewpoints of their prejudiced friends and colleagues and make their viewpoints known.  \r\n	The program finishes by highlighting the Freedom Festival Fireworks, at which the theme will be â€œA Celebration of Freedom: Family Fun and the Fireworks.â€  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-17','119','59','The episode opens with statements from President Jimmy Carter announcing the strike settlement.  Carter also recognizes the difficulty of the job of a miner.  Next is a preview of a family, one who says that the miners have no choice but to stay out of the mines.\r\n	Host Ron Scott begins by announcing that negotiations between the United Mine Workers and representatives has been successful and a settlement has been reached.  Scott goes on to discuss some of the major details of the agreement, and then interviews Burdette Crowe, a miner, to get more info on the agreement.  Crowe however seems unfamiliar with the proposal, and does not feel comfortable commenting on specific proposals.  Scott then asks Crowe about the lack of Pension Funds in the provisional agreement, and Crowe voices his concerns and claims he will fight for pension funds in the future.  Scott also inquires about the Taft-Hartley act, which Crowe claims was not able to get miners to return to the coal mines.  Scott then thanks Crowe for joining the program.\r\nScott then turns to affiliate WWVU-TV for an interview with Len Gross, a representative of the coal industry.  Gross states that during the strike, 13 million tons of coal has been lost during the strike.  The program then shifts to Scottâ€™s interview with Charlestonâ€™s Mayor John Hutchinson.  Hutchinson downplays the negative effect of the strike of the economy of Charleston due to the diversified nature of the economy.  Hutchinson also comments on the waning influence of the United Mine Workers and the need for stability between the miners and the operators.  \r\n	Next, Scott interviews young coal miners Wayne Busby and Alec Meiklejohn.  Busby explains possible reasons behind the length of the strike, and reiterates his beliefs that the union will be able to hold out longer.  Meiklejohn comments on the lack of employment opportunities in the surrounding areas.  Busbyâ€™s wife, Kathy voices her concerns over the dangerous working environment of the mines.  She also states that she wouldnâ€™t want her son to work in the mine.  Another miner, Mike Meares, hopes that someday the mines will be run by the miners themselves, and would be able to make judgments and decisions of their own.  Meiklejohn goes on to thank the support of the Auto Workers in Detroit, and draws the connection between the plights of both unions.  \r\n	The episode then shifts to an interview with a retired miner, John Huddleston.  Scott and Huddleston discuss the lack of minerâ€™s pensions.  Huddleston also comments on the lack of unions when he began his mining career.  Huddlestonâ€™s wife Helen tells about her worries as a coal minerâ€™s wife, especially during strikes and labor disputes.  John says that he probably would still work in the mines if he could do it all over again, since he did not have the education required to obtain a better job.  \r\n	Scott then shares some statistics about the nation mortality rate in the mines.  He then joins Cecil Roberts, Pres. UMWA Dist. 17 in the mine, who discusses the contract negotiations in Washington and the dangers of working in the coal mines.  \r\n	The episode returns to the interview between Scott and Huddleston, and Huddleston reflects on his brotherâ€™s death in the mine.\r\n	Scott then closes out the episodes restating the dangers of the coal industry, and asks the viewer, â€œwhich side are you on?â€\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-18','119','59','On this show, Wood interviews Arthur Mitchell, a dancer who was a member of the New York City Ballet and is now a member and founder of the Dance Theatre of Harlem.  Mitchell starts out by discussing how he draws on the teachings that he has had from all sorts of people, both his leaders in the ballet world and civil rights activists such as Martin Luther King, and come to realize that what one truly needs to succeed are discipline and focus.\r\n	They then move on to talk about his life, starting with his young years struggling in Harlem, New York as the oldest of five kids.  He had to take over after his father left as the head of the family, and this forged a strong sense of responsibility and the desire to know the reasons for why things happen.  Wood then asks why Mitchell chose to pursue ballet instead of other much more popular sports.  Mitchell says his sister taught him to be a good social dancer, and then Mitchell tried out and made it into the High School of Performing Arts, and followed his dream from there.\r\n	Wood then approaches the issue that ballet would seem way to far out of reach for the disenfranchised black common man, and is curious as to how Mitchell approached this problem.  Mitchell talks about how he faced racism when he was continually turned down at auditions where he knew he was the best, and then tried to find something that he knew would give him the edge.  This, he decided, was classical technique, and he took up classical ballet at the age of 18.  Then, after three years at the School of American Ballet, Mitchell joined the company, and was inspired by Jackie Robinsonâ€™s breaking of barriers in baseball to hope to do the same in ballet.  \r\n	Wood then talks about how Mitchellâ€™s dance possesses the epitome of expressiveness, beauty, and technique.  Mitchell talks about how he believes dance is the first of the art forms because of its use of movement, which is the basis of all communication and behavior.  Wood moves on to talk about how when Mitchell was a principal dancer at the New York City ballet, and was the only black dancer with that kind of prestige at the time.  He asks him how he aspired to have that kind of prestige when no one else was doing it.  Mitchell talks about how oneâ€™s perspective changes, and one can only aspire for the â€œcommon denominator of excellence.â€  \r\n	Wood asks how Mitchell decided to, in 1968, leave his position as principal dancer and start the Dance Theatre of Harlem.  Mitchell describes his first motivation as being in 1966, when they had the First World Festival of the Negro and the Arts in Senegal.  He was asked by organizers in this event to start the first national Brazilian ballet company, and he also built an opera company.  Then, following Martin Luther Kingâ€™s death, he was motivated to take action, and he started in a basement teaching kids to dance.  This company grew extremely quickly, and in teaching kids from the streets and gang members ballet, he removed the stigma surrounding ballet and the fact that it wasnâ€™t â€œmanly.â€  Mitchell also found that, in making sure that his students were excelling scholastically as well, he was able to improve their performance in all aspects of their lives.  \r\n	Mitchell also describes how classical training is the highest level of technique possible, and how, even if one does not decide to pursue ballet, they will excel in any method of dance or athletics that they do pursue because of the training that theyâ€™ve had.  \r\n	Mitchell then goes on to talk about the residency program that he is working on for dance students in Detroit, and hopes that through this program he can enrich their lives with the arts, which he believes everyone should have in their lives.  He thinks that, by giving them the chance to participate in the arts, they can develop the skills that will help them succeed in other aspects of their lives.  Wood then asks why the arts are so financially undervalued in modern-day society.  Mitchell makes the point that we only think of the arts as pleasure and relaxation, so because of this viewpoint, it hasnâ€™t received the funding that it deserves.  He also makes the point that artistic expression can be made even more meaningful when one draws on the experiences they have had in other areas of their lives and applies them.  He dance can enhance oneâ€™s performance in things such as sports, by improving footwork and movement.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-19','119','59','Hunter-Gault first questions Tutu about the effect that demonstrations, such as the one happening that day at Shell Oil Company, have on South Africa.  He responds by saying that they have had a tremendous effect, mainly by boosting the morale of those who are fighting against apartheid.  He talks about the results of the bans placed on certain companies and people, mainly that it has opened up realities of the world, such as those of police brutality, to the fighters in the anti-apartheid movement, particularly younger people.  \r\n	Tutu then expresses his great appreciation and love for what America has been doing in the struggle against apartheid, both through its citizens and the President.  He highlights the importance of the sanctions that have been implemented, but Hunter-Gault brings up the fact that he has pushed for even more of these to be instated in a short amount of time.  He stresses that intervention of the international community through sanctions and in other ways is needed to prevent the crises that he sees arising in the future in South Africa if actions arenâ€™t taken.  He highlights the distrust had for government officials, such as Luttweiler, in regards to their so-called â€œempty promises,â€ and discusses how their failure to follow through on such promises has widened the gap between them and those fighting against apartheid.  \r\n	Hunter-Gault asks Tutu what it would take to have the anti-apartheid movement sit down with the government and negotiate.  He states that this could only happen if they made clear the intention to dismantle apartheid, removed political prisoners from detention, lifted the state of emergency and withdrew troops, and were determined to be involved in true negotiations.  The significant issue of violence is then addressed, and the question is raised as to how widespread the belief that it is the only alternative is.  It is clear that this belief is increasing, particularly amongst the younger generation\r\n	Questions are then taken from the audience and over the phone, involving issues such as why America should get involved in the problems of South Africa when it has enough race-relation problems of its own to figure out, how Americans can make a difference, the role that companies who claim to not support apartheid play in supporting society and community, the issue of divestment and sanctions, the political role South Africa will take following the dissolution of apartheid, and the role of Nelson Mandela in the anti-apartheid struggle.  In regards to this question, Tutu stresses the importance and faith that people place in Mandela, even though he is in jail, and how he is indispensable to the solution to the problems in South Africa.  \r\n	Tutu also stresses how he is not alone in his viewpoints and leadership, and how there are many others who are just as significant in the struggle, if not more, than he is.  Another issue is that of the different tribes in South Africa, and how they would be organized if apartheid was disbanded.  He stresses that people are mostly quite de-tribalized, and that it is the government of South Africa that has tried to enforce the tribal lines to promote and exacerbate the differences amongst people.  He also addresses the question of whether the courts and judicial system are merely â€œtools of the regime,â€ or whether they can be used to help in the anti-apartheid movement.  The problem in South Africa is that the Constitution is against blacks, because they are guaranteed very few rights under it, and so the judicial system must uphold this Constitution, making it difficult for them to be much of a help in the anti-apartheid struggle.  Comparisons are also drawn between the civil rights struggle in American and the anti-apartheid struggle in South Africa.  \r\n	Tutuâ€™s role as both a religious and a political leader is also addressed, and he discusses how preaching godâ€™s message and political messages to whites as well as black has been received.  He has a positive reaction, saying that he thinks whites are coming around to ideas of love and appreciation for their countrymen, both white and black.  He then talks about the role of South Africaâ€™s youth in the struggle and their bravery, often willing, with both good and bad results, to take more radical actions than older members of the struggle.  He subsequently discusses his support for what the ANC stands for, but his dislike for the means they use to get what they want, such as guerrilla tactics.  \r\n	Tutu finally discusses the issue of the white Africana, their resistance, and the role that they are playing in modern-day South Africa.  Also, he talks about the role that the Reagan Administration must play in regards to this issue and in helping South Africa through such things as divestment.  \r\n	Hunter-Gault finishes by questioning Tutu about what he feels is the most realistic scenario for South Africa.  He is quite optimistic, saying that if the correct policies are implemented, they could be free tomorrow.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-1A','119','59','Performance and â€œGrapevineâ€\r\nThe show opens with Wynn and Hal McKinney performing, â€œThe Freedom Jazz Dance.â€  Then, the â€œGrapevineâ€ portion of the show, which highlights the daily events, is broadcast.  On this dayâ€™s â€œGrapevine,â€ events mentioned include the Detroit Creative Musicianâ€™s Association performance of â€œBeyond That Jazz Concert Number 3,â€ the Annual Menâ€™s Day services, the Jolly Old Timerâ€™s Annual Charity Ball, a mass meeting to discuss community control of public schools, the Fred D. Lyles Social, and Womenâ€™s Day, featuring Dr. Paulina Campbell as speaker.  Another segment of the Grapevine highlights the â€œtogether sister of the week,â€ this week Sharyl McBig, a junior at Wayne State University.  The leader of this segment, Sandy, then highlights Murray Brooks, and Co., a firm in Detroit.  She continues with other events news, such as the weekly Funky! Soul Revue.  She also mentions CPTâ€™s â€œsalesman of the week,â€ Earl Grey.  Another focus of the Grapevine is fashion, and Sandy mentions performer Diane Carol and her ensembles.  \r\nInternational Gospel Choir\r\n	The show then goes on to highlight Afro-American music and jazz.  He introduces the International Gospel Choir from the International Gospel Center, which sings â€œHigher Groundâ€ and â€œGod Never Feels.â€  They are regulars on the Sunday International Gospel radio show.  Sandy then introduces the showâ€™s feature, â€œThe Making of a Rioter,â€ which is supplemented by footage of and information about the civil disturbances that had begun the night before and is continuing throughout Detroit.  \r\nTop Story\r\n	The segment highlights that Detroitâ€™s public schools are partly responsible for the â€œmakingâ€ of rioters.  Black children in the inner city are consistently deprived of good education, and these poor schools often produce students who believe that violence is the only way to incite change.  People from the show went out and interviewed inner-city students, particularly those from Northeastern, about their opinions on their schools, and they all believe that there is great room for and need for improvement.  It seems that racism, especially on the part of the teachers, is often the biggest problem.  The students also stress that the curriculum is not preparing them for any meaningful jobs following high school and/or college.   The Black Student Association has been formed by many students at Northeastern, and their goal is to improve the substandard education given at Northeastern and make the community more aware of the problems at the school.  \r\nPerformance #2 & News\r\n	To start the second half of the show, Bill Murphy performs.   Then, Abe Ulmer presents, â€œNews from Our Point of View.â€  He talks about issues such as: a Michigan civil rights panel charging police with discrimination involving alleged police assault of a protestor at a July rebellion, the New York City public school strike by teachers, the arrest of four inner-city firms for frauds, the suspension of police officers involved in an incident at the Veteranâ€™s Memorial, and another victory by Arthur Ashe, Jr. at the Davis Cup Inter-zone Championships.  \r\nEntertainment\r\n	The next part of the show features a presentation and performance by one of the worldâ€™s best mimics, George Kirby.  Following this, Kim Westin performs, â€œWhen Johnny Comes Marching Home.â€  Then, the show takes a look at the life of Harriet Tubman, a leading â€œconductorâ€ on the Underground Railroad through a dramatic stage presentation and portrayal of her.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-1B','119','59','Performance & â€œGrapevineâ€ Segment\r\nTo start off the show, Hal McKinney performs â€œCornerstone.â€  Then, the â€œGrapevineâ€ segment presents upcoming events, which include: Don Walden and his quintet will be performing, a social club gathering, the Cultural and Literary Club gathering and fashion show, an Art Istitute event, and fashions shown at the Veterans Memorial Building.  The â€œtogether sister of the weekâ€ is Rosalyn Russell, a medical secretary.  Former Supreme Lawrence Ballard is highlighted, as is another former Motown star Kim Westin.  To finish, Letâ€™s Face it, a book by Elsie Archer, is promoted.\r\nTop Story\r\n	Next, Part II of the The Olympic Revolt is shown, a program that focuses on the history and achievements of black athletes in competition, then is shown, highlighting the black boycott of the Olympic competitions.  Professor Harry Edwards, organizer of the boycott, insists that athletics can be used as a wedge to improve the second-class nature of blacks who dominate in track and field.  John Lewis, a winner of the 1928 Olympic relay team, gives CPTV his feelings about the boycott.  He says that he actually never had any racial troubles himself.  Lorenzo Wright, a former 400 m relay champion, gives his opinion, stating that itâ€™s quite a youthful movement, and Dr. William Watson, a former athlete who now works in athletics at Wayne State University, disapproves strongly of the boycott.  The show then highlights the performances of black athletes in Mexico City and their actions and the pressâ€™s response.  To finish the first half of the show, the Brothers of Soul perform.  \r\nNews\r\n	Then, current news stories from the black community are highlighted in â€œPeople and Places that Make up Our News.â€   Stories include: The Detroit Urban Leagueâ€™s release of information that  shows that some 20 public commissions have no black appointees, Congressman John Conyerâ€™s Jr.â€™s comments on black people sitting out the election,  the commission of a National Afro-American Police League, and a report on the African Conference on Black Writers.  They provide information about what was said by prominent people at the conference, including Stokely Carmichael.   He also gives a sports report, highlighting O.J. Simpsonâ€™s plays that kept Southern California undefeated after a win over Washington the previous week.  \r\nPerformance #2 & Special Guest\r\n	The next guest on the show, Wild Bill Davis, performs â€œQuiet Nights,â€ and then the nightâ€™s special guest, Martha Jean â€œThe Queen,â€ is brought on.  She works for the blue collar workers and laborers of the community, promoting their rights and â€œserving othersâ€ through her work and radio show.  She believes that money takes precedence in society over caring for fellow citizens and recognizing them.  She hopes, through her blue collar program, she and the groupâ€™s members can get people to use their minds and think.  She also has a talent in music, with a knack for picking number one songs, as she demonstrates in her disk jockey skills on her radio show.  She was also a recording artist.\r\nDramatic Performance\r\n	Following Martha Jeanâ€™s interview, the Inkster Community Choir performs, and then Kent Martin, director of the CPT Players, puts on a play featuring the character Jess B. Simple.  This finishes the show.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-1C','119','59','Ben Frasier begins by describing the aim of this installment of the show (to investigate the world of Detroitâ€™s black teens), and then moves on to pay tribute to the late Reverend C.L. Franklin, the father of Aretha Franklin.  They broadcast a special tribute video that shows footage from his funeral and provides commentary of other significant people of the times commenting on his life and actions, as a demonstration of the power of his sermons and his political and religious influence and his unique and special personality and importance to the community.  Some people who comment on his life include Claude Young of the SCLC, Martha Jean â€œThe Queenâ€ Steinberg, Reverend Marlon Terrell, Reverend S.L. Jones, Erma Franklin, Robin McCoy of the Michigan Chronicle, Reverend Cecil Franklin, and Fannie Tyler (Reverend C.L. Franklinâ€™s secretary).  They talk about his importance as a preacher, a leader, a father, and a husband, and his activity in spearheading such events as when Martin Luther King, Jr. gave his â€œI Have a Dreamâ€ speech.  They also talk about when he was shot and became severely debilitated.  \r\n	The show then moves on to investigate the lives of Detroitâ€™s black teenagers, looking at how many are hoping to better their communities and be part of a pursuit to improve their own and othersâ€™ lives even in the rough conditions that they often live amongst.  They highlight first the Royal Crusaders, a religious group that works to help those who are struggling.  They talk with some of the teens who are members of the group about the importance of the Royal Crusaders to them and their lives, as well as their parents.  The involved teens face opposition from some of their peers, but because of their belief in the organization, they continue with it despite this.  \r\n	They also look at how an androgynous look is considered cool amongst teens, mainly because of the popularity of androgynous-looking stars such as Michael Jackson, Boy George, and Prince.  Students discuss how popular androgyny is and why it is appealing, but some adults do worry about this trend, and psychiatrists and psychologists give their input about the issue, discussing how teens often adopt an androgynous look in order to help them discover who they are.  \r\n	Teen Profile, a radio and television series produced and run by teens through WGBR-TV, is then examined by the show.  Participants in the show are interviewed, as well as their parents, who believe that it provides a way for them to do things with their lives as they try and figure out where they want to go and what they want to do in their future.  The show provides ways to teenagers to be responsible, creative, hard workers, all while getting exposure.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-1D','119','59','The show starts out by showing a segment from â€œGunplay,â€ a documentary done by the show which took a look at the use of handguns and violence.  Gunplay features interviews with gunshot victims and their family members, as well as with other people, such as students, regarding the issue of why the use of guns has become much more widespread in recent times.  They discuss how accessible the weapons are, as well as the appeal of â€œeasy moneyâ€ associated with guns.  Many people believe that parents must be held partially responsible for their children obtaining weapons, and security measures must be increased.  \r\n	Following the clip, Gordon introduces his guests on the show: Hartford Smith, from the Wayne State School of Social Work, Commander James Younger, from the Detroit Police Departmentâ€™s Felony Prevention Unit, Emerald Crosby, the principal at Pershing High School, and a former gang member who wants to keep his true identity secret, who they refer to as â€œJoe.â€  Gordon begins by asking Joe how he felt when he saw a gunshot victim on the tape they just showed who lost the use of his legs.  Joe responds that he feels bad, and that the kind of crime involved in the shooting, where the victim was held up because he had nice sneakers that the person wanted, should be stopped.  They go on to talk about the prevalence of this type of crime, as well as other illegal activity, and Joe describes an issue where he was shot in front of his home.  Gordon then addresses the issue of how there are many young children involved in gang activity, and the two of them discuss the availability of handguns to all ages of people.  \r\n	Gordon then addresses Younger, who wants to know about some of the things that Joe did while he was involved in gang activity.  Joe describes how there are different kinds of gangs that serve different functions.  Younger then talks about the definition of gangs, and how the dictionary definition is quite different from citizensâ€™ perception.  Younger says the police classify youth gangs in terms of how theyâ€™re going to combat their activity.  \r\nSmith then comes into the discussion, talking about the social context in which gang problems grow.  He talks about the deterioration of community, especially in struggling urban areas.  He says that the conditions in these communities lead to youth searching for their own methods of survival, which can lead to gang violence.\r\nGordon then goes to the phone lines.  The first caller asks Younger what measures they are taking to keep weapons out of schools as well and off the streets.  Younger says the police department has been working with the Detroit School Board to conduct school sweeps, has intensified its street patrols, and has started more vigorous prosecution of individuals involved in weapons crimes.  He stresses the importance that citizens work to report crimes as well.  \r\nCrosby then comes into the discussion, and Gordon talks about how many weapons have been found at Pershing and other high schools during sweeps.  Crosby says that the school should be seen as an extension of what is happening in the neighborhoods, and believes that the violence problems associated with schools stems from community mentalities.  \r\nAnother call is taken.  He vouches for Joeâ€™s comments and says that everything he has been talking about is true.  Another caller asks what should be done about people who carry guns not with the goal of hurting others, but simply to protect themselves, and they go on to discuss the penalties associated with gun-carrying in Michigan.  \r\nSmith says that there is a general feeling of a lack of safety in communities, and this is the motivation for many people carrying weapons.  People also feel that police will not be able to get to places fast enough, and that is another contributor to the rapid increase in the amount of people possessing firearms.  \r\nCrosby then comes back into the discussion to talk about the environment in present-day public high schools.  He talks about how there are a lot of individuals compressed into a single school, and this generates a violent atmosphere.  He discusses the issue of the small number of supporters available to change this atmosphere for the better.  \r\nThe next caller addresses the case of the victim Shawn Norman, and says that he believes the police didnâ€™t do their job, because his attacker is still roaming free.  Gordon steers the discussion towards talking about whether there need to be changes in the judicial system.  Younger says that the community needs to take more action in influencing the practices of the judicial system.  The following caller asks Joe why there is always â€œblack on blackâ€ victimization, rather than going to other methods of crime that donâ€™t involve hurting individuals.  Crosby comments that he believes people do this because they think they can victimize certain individuals with a small amount of repercussions.  The following caller wants to know why parents canâ€™t be held responsible when their children commit crimes, and the issue is also raised about how she believes her environment has led her towards a future that doesnâ€™t involve crime, as opposed to Joeâ€™s environment.  Younger says there are certain circumstances where the parent can be held responsible.  He also talks about how certain crimes are perpetuated by the poor, but upper-class individuals can also contribute to crime as well, such as those involving the drug market.  \r\nThe next caller wants to know if including capital punishment in the judicial system would lead to a breakdown in crime.  Smith says that this has never been shown to be a deterrent to crime.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-1E','119','59','In recent times, there have been a resurgence of racist acts occurring, including movements from the Klu Klux Klan.  Now, there are meetings and coalitions forming to put an end to the violence.  The first person they talk to is Mrs. B. Tracy, director of the Eastside City Coalition, who a lecture called â€œUnity in the black community.â€  She says that their major purpose for the lecture and event was to do something for the black community, which is constantly being denied rights that they feel entitle to.  She hopes to make this affordable and available to black people, as well as to have a summer program for youth.  She states the importance of focusing on business and things that will empower and benefit the black community through the development of black entrepreneurship skills.  \r\n	Clements then asks how she thinks they will deal with black unity, the theme of the lecture.  Tracy says that, by bringing things to the community that blacks are drawn to attend, they are effectively dealing with the issue of black unity.  She also talks about how they are not funded and are trying to be self-sufficient before using grants.  They function off of individual donations and fund-raisers.  \r\n	Detroit Black Journal then speaks with Dick Gregory, the keynote speaker for the event, about his viewpoints on the recent racist, violent, and genocidal actions against blacks.  Clements quotes Gregory as saying that the Atlanta child murders had to do with fiendish experiments, and asks him to explain.  Gregory says that the facts that no one got away from the murder and that it occurred during the daytime are extremely suspicious, as well as the fact that the crime baffled all the police intelligence of the country.  This leads him to believe that groups such as the Klu Klux Klan could not have been involved, but in looking at patterns in the governmentâ€™s involvement in different things, itâ€™s indicative that they could have some involvement in the Atlanta murders.  Clements then addresses the fact that he was informed that the Atlanta governmental task force that was named to investigate this crime didnâ€™t go out and do field work, but rather stayed indoors and worked out of their offices, and Gregory expands upon this fact, saying that he talked to the mothers of the victims.  He also talks about the mutilations performed on the female and male victims, and says that, in looking at trends in these mutilations, he is led to believe that fiendish medical experiments are at the root of the murders.  He also talks about the actions of the police, such as those who buried a severely decomposed boy under a tree and told his mother to simply have a memorial service for him.  He also talks about the possibility that the government may have been involved in some way in these murders.  \r\n	Clements then talks about the fact that there is other terrorist activity going on around the country, and asks Gregory if he feels that the Atlanta tragedy was an isolated even or if it was somehow related to these other atrocities that are occurring.  Gregory feels that it is an isolated event, because itâ€™s happening in one community and happening to one group of black people.  Gregory then talks about black organizations, and discusses his belief that it is not a matter of a lack of black voice, but rather a lack of blacks putting their priorities on the right things.  \r\n	They then talk about the issue of the United Statesâ€™ involvement in South Africa.  Gregory says that it is a matter of profit for the countries that are involved, and he says that once they break this economic involvement, then they will break South Africa.  \r\n	Clements then talks about his observations of the Atlanta child murders, and talks about evidence from police, investigators, and coronersâ€™ actions that there is a conspiracy occurring.  Clements says that blacks must use the evidence they are presented with to make their own conclusions and protect themselves in any way they see fit and for any possible scenarios.  He says that in the upcoming years, they will see a continuing effort to unify the black community and form strong coalitions.  \r\n	The program finishes with a montage of photographs of the murdered children and funeral services, as well as video footage of other parents with their children.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-1F','119','59','Gallant is joined by City Council President Erma Henderson, who did not put her name on the Detroit ballot for the first time in 17 years.  Henderson starts out by discussing the importance of changes in the yearâ€™s ballot, as well as the significance of the elections themselves.  Gallant brings up the subject of Hendersonâ€™s mayoral run, in which she received much less support than she had always gotten for her runs for City Council.  Henderson says that she could not reach a lot of the people that she was able to reach before, largely because of a lack of funds, and because the press dominated the election and influenced public perceptions of it.  Henderson stresses the importance of people taking more of an active role in elections in order to prevent such influence by the press.  \r\n	They then show a tape of some highlights from Erma Hendersonâ€™s career.  The final clip features Henderson and mayor Coleman Young, and Gallant asks about their relationship, them having been long-time friends but her having run against him in the primary election for mayor.  Henderson says that theyâ€™ve known each other a long time, and that they attracted the same kind of constituency even though they had different points of view, which made her success in the election rather improbable.  She ran against him only in order to make the people aware of policies and political conditions, as well as to address issues that she cared about.    \r\n	They then discuss what Hendersonâ€™s plans will be after the year ends and her term as City Council President is over.  She says she has been invited to teach, as well as other things, but she wants to make sure that, whatever she does, that she loves it.  She also talks about her mentors that she met in her lifetime, including W.E.B. DuBois and Paul Robeson.\r\n	The show then goes to the phone lines.  The first caller wants to know whether Henderson is pleased with Ms. Mahateyâ€™s win over Gill Hill, and whether, as blacks, they lose something, since a black no longer fills the presidency position.  Henderson says that who the city has as a person, rather than their race, makes the most difference for Detroit and its future.  The next caller wants to know whether the mayor will be more responsive to neighborhood issues in light of the heat of the recent election, and what the secret is of her high energy.  Henderson believes that the yearâ€™s election will have an impact on the mayor, and says that she works to keep herself healthy in order to stay high-energy (she also owns and operates a health food store).  The following caller brings up figures such as Colin Powell and David Deacon, and asks whether Henderson thinks having such â€œblack faces in high placesâ€ will help the community.  Henderson emphasizes how people change once entering politics, and that electing blacks can help the black community, but individuals also must work to close the gap between politicians and their constituency, no matter what their race is.  The fourth caller wants to know whether, in the next four or five years, whether she thinks Tom Barrel has the potential to be Mayor.  Henderson says thatâ€™s really up to Mr. Barrel, but she does believe that he had the weakness of not being in public office before his run.  \r\n	They talk about Hendersonâ€™s proposal for more police on the street, and she thinks that but updating the work of the police force, it could drastically improve the community.  They then go back to the phone lines, and the next caller wants to know what the probability is for more females in Detroit politics.  Henderson comments on how the number of women is down, and there is only one black woman.  She says that people donâ€™t tend to treat women as seriously as they do males in politics.  \r\n	The show closes with some clips featuring highlights from Hendersonâ€™s career.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-20','119','59','Gordon is joined by Earl Graves, editor and publisher of Black Enterprise Magazine, and Dave Bing, president of Bing Steel.  Gordonâ€™s first question is for Graves, and he asks whether he thinks blacks have learned how to â€œleverage economic clout.â€  Graves says that he thinks so, and says that black organizations have taken it into their own hands to bring in more finances and grow.  Gordon also asks what more can be done to increase the political and social clout of the black community.  Graves says economic clout can only come from them making good decisions about what to do with their money.  This could include doing business with things such as hotel chains.  \r\n	Gordon asks how Bing saw his clout grow as a black businessman in the economic community, and how the black community could see theirs grow as relates to that kind of power.  Bing says that location and support from local corporations and the whole political process has fostered his companyâ€™s growth.  Gordon comments on Bingâ€™s observation that itâ€™s important that blacks find a niche, but also asks whether itâ€™s important that blacks expand themselves in the business world as well.  Bing says that this is indeed very important, and comments that, in going into the steel industry in Detroit, he set himself up to accrue a good deal of money that would then allow him to expand his enterprise into other areas.  \r\n	Graves says that itâ€™s important that blacks recognize that they are on the â€œthresholdâ€ of where business can go, and are â€œknocking at the door of opportunityâ€ in regards to expanding out and diversifying.  They need to look at the business opportunities that are available, as well as looking at the opportunities to set up their own brokerage and finance firms, because they need to have their own kind of economic clout.  \r\n	Gordon comments that government plays a large role in the business world, and asks what effect governmental restrictions, mandates, and actions are going to have on black business.  Graves says that opportunity cutbacks didnâ€™t set the black business community back too much, but they just realized that they were going to have to work harder to achieve their economic goals.  Bing has never done business with the federal government, and instead went directly to the private sector and the city of Detroit as he was starting out.  \r\n	Gordon then goes to the phone lines.  The first caller says that he was pleased to hear them mention the need for brokerage firms, but also says that, although such firms are needed, there is a low percentage of blacks who are investing in the stock market.  Graves says that his magazine will be having networking sessions across the country focusing on economic empowerment through personal financial planning, and says that the magazine has been working to get blacks to invest in the stock market.  The second caller wants to know how they can diversify business endeavors.  Bing says that getting out of the traditional business set takes both studying and exposure.  \r\n	Gordon then asks Graves if he is pleased about where black enterprise is in present-day corporate America.  Graves isnâ€™t that satisfied, because he sees companies that are doing better, but there are others that arenâ€™t doing well as far as black employment is concerned.  He says that the present-day problem is that opportunities for black movement in the corporate world are just not available as they should be.  \r\n	Gordon returns to the phones, and the next caller wants to know how they can get the message across to black businesses that there is too much money diffused out of communities.  Graves says that the media hypes up the idea that blacks are not supporting blacks, and that in reality this is no longer the case.  Graves also says that modern-day blacks have the right to demand from businesses that they provide a service in a first-class manner, especially since black businesses do so.  The next caller wants to know the panelâ€™s view on affirmative action, as well as whether Bing thinks he would be where he is without having been known as a great basketball player first.  Bing says that he had name recognition, which got him in the door, but it was essential that he perform in the business world and for his customers, or else his business would have sank.  He adds that he believes in affirmative action.  The following caller wants to know ways to find suitable working capital for young black businesses.  Graves says that this is the tough question that faces all businessmen, and that one first has to build up a personal income and look to institutions such as local banks, and then to larger institutions such as the AKAs.   \r\n	Gordon asks whether blacks need to have a better understanding of business.  Graves says that there is a need for a basic educational background, so that they can understand business and the marketplace and be able to communicate.  Financial planning is also extremely important as one plans for expenses involved in oneâ€™s future.\r\n	The next caller asks Graves what advice he can give to the black community as they see more Arabic businessmen moving in to the community, removing money, and beautifying their own communities.  Graves says itâ€™s not a matter of race and ethnicity, but rather one should look at the situation as they are there because they didnâ€™t take advantage of opportunities when they were available.  \r\n	Gordon turns again to Bing, and asks whether he believes that blacks are ready for the economic world and big business.  Bing says that there is a wealth of talent in the black community, and there are many people who would like to see a black company grow and succeed.  The next caller, Carl Gregory, a top economist in the country who wrote for Gravesâ€™ magazine, asks Graves whether there are any efforts going on nationally to bring together the fraternities, sororities, churches, and other black organizations to create a larger black venture capital company.  Graves says that they are having discussions with the different Greek organizations about how they leverage the power they have to use that clout to create business opportunities and generate capital.  \r\n	Gordon asks Graves to name one thing the black community could do to achieve economic parity, and Graves says that leveraging the economic and political clout they have requires exercising oneâ€™s voting power and recognizing that one holds power with the voting dollar.  Bing says that Detroit businessmen have been meeting to try and come up with ways to raise the economic clout in Detroit, and one group he is in, NABAS, is working together to try and understand the opportunities that are available.  \r\n	The show closes with Billy Paulâ€™s song â€œLet the Dollar Circulate.â€\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-21','119','59','The show opens with video highlights from Nelson Mandelaâ€™s stop in Detroit, Michigan, which include clips from Mandelaâ€™s speeches, travels, and the response of Detroitâ€™s auto workers to his visit.  The highlights also include a large concert attended by Mandela and his wife, at which choral groups and Stevie Wonder performed, and where he gave a rousing speech to many of Detroitâ€™s citizens.  \r\n	Gallant is then joined by two members of the steering committee for the Detroit stop-off on Mandelaâ€™s U.S. tour, Margaret Baylor and Paul Hubbard.  They are there to discuss the financial success of the event.  Gallant starts with Baylor, who talks about how Detroit made more than one million dollars from Mandelaâ€™s visit.  Hubbard says that this money will go to the ANC, as well as Trans-Africaâ€™s 510C3 organization, which will use it to help South Africaâ€™s homeless.  There are also other possibilities for where the rest of the money could go.  Baylor is the the president of the local chapter of Trans-Africa, which served as the local governing body for the Mandela Freedom Tour.  She says the money might also be used to repatriate South African exiles, and talks about how Trans-Africa has been working to collect books to be sent to South Africa, as well as working with the auto industry to have money from car sales to go to the Mandela Freedom Tour.  \r\n	Hubbard talks about the feedback he has gotten about the Mendelaâ€™s visit, all extremely positive.  His visit was seen as a â€œhealing factionâ€ between all facets of the city, during which Detroitâ€™s spirit was raised greatly and crime dropped.  Hubbard says the one thing that stands out in his mind about the visit is that everyone worked extremely well with each other on the project and made it a productive, smooth-running process.  They also got lots of cooperation from many different organizations.  Hubbard says her favorite moment from Mandelaâ€™s visit was when he thanked her at his press conference.  \r\n	The show breaks with more footage from one of Mandelaâ€™s speeches, and then returns with two journalists who got to follow Mandela during his travel across the country: Detroit Free Press columnist Susan Watson, and WDIV reporter and anchorman Emery King.  Watson first talks about the difficulty to be objective as a journalist when Mandelaâ€™s visit was so moving for all involved.  King says the first time he saw Mandela was in Toronto, and says that at that moment he was simply in awe of Mandela.  \r\n	They then show clips from each of Mandelaâ€™s stops, alternating with comments from the journalists, starting in Harlem, New York.  Watson says that at his speech there, people got a true sense of his strength, his mission, and his seriousness about what he wants for his country and the world.  Gallant talks about how Mandela voiced his support for leaders such as Castro, and says she was a bit surprised that he didnâ€™t receive a little more criticism for these views.  King responds by saying that Mandela diffused the issue himself, and didnâ€™t leave any room for criticism.  The second clip they look at is from Boston, where Winnie Mandela also spoke.  King says that this stop-off, where Mandela danced along with the crowd to the music that followed his speech, was his single favorite moment from the tour.  Watson also makes the point that Boston was much more like home than any of the other cities.  They also talk about the issue of not hearing much from Winnie Mandela, and Watson says that she thinks this was intentional, especially because she had been heard from so much before her husband was released, and also because she faced some troubles at home, such as the fact that a young man was killed by her body guards, and she had made some controversial statements.  Gallant also talks about how the audience was much more integrated, and King agrees that the audience was much whiter, but says that there were still racial problems going on in the city before his speech.  The third stop-off they discuss was Mandelaâ€™s trip to Washington, where, in an unusual turn, he surprisingly stood up to President Bush.  King says Washington was significant because he came there to take care of business.  They also talk about how they worked hard to keep from injecting the controversy from the Marion Barry problems into Mandelaâ€™s affairs.  \r\n	They then move on to talk about Mandelaâ€™s visit to Atlanta, which was so symbolic because it was the heart of the American Civil Rights Movement.  King describes this stop as the â€œleast frenetic,â€ and then they move on to show a clip and talk about Mandelaâ€™s stop in Miami.  This was a quick stop, and he faced a good deal of resistance to his visit, because he angered many Cuban-Americans with his statements of support for Fidel Castro.  They finally move on to Detroit, and they talk about the feeling of bonding and kinship that was present in Detroit.  King says that he was at the airport for Mandelaâ€™s arrival, as well as the rally at the Tigers Stadium, and says that this was the most powerful rally of all.  Gallant says that the one downside about Detroit was that there were certain politicians who were rubbed the wrong way because they werenâ€™t invited to certain things.  Watson says that this probably could have been avoided, but that it is politics, but that they can learn from this that they donâ€™t have time for in-fighting and should focus on the more pressing problems facing them.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-22','119','59','They begin by talking about Brownâ€™s early life, during which he worked extremely hard and only went as far as the seventh grade.  Brown says that his early life taught him about the importance of working hard and gave him an appreciation for struggling to get somewhere, and Scott asks him what he says to youngsters that donâ€™t know what that is like.  Brown says that he makes them aware of their ignorance of this, and that they should understand that it exists.  \r\n	They then go on to talk about â€œJames Brown: Will of Love,â€ a new TV show that the entertainer will be producing.  He discusses the importance of him being in charge of his own projects, rather than other people, and says that every artist should be able to project themselves.  However, present-day conditions have brought about conditions where many artists do not take charge of their own careers.  \r\n	Brown and Scott also discuss how, during the beginning of when Brown brought back disco, he bought up radio stations and played the music that he thought people should hear.  This was quite revolutionary at the time.  He says we should accept all people and appreciate humanity together.  Scott then follows this by asking him if different races are coming together or growing apart, and Brown says that the conditions are a repeat of the times of slavery and segregation, and they will get worse if people do not take action.  \r\n	They go back to talking about the television show, and Scott asks whether Brown believes ending up on television will compromise his career.  Brown says that he is worried to a certain extent, but says that he and everybody else just wants to do better in their lives.  He says he can only succeed as far as possible with his talent and seventh-grade education, and he will try to do so.  Brown also stresses the importance of â€œmind power,â€ and having a strong sense of self and god.  \r\n	The two of them also talk about the new movie that Brown made, which is a documentary as well as an entertainment piece.  Scott also asks how Brown managed to turn himself into such a great entertainer.  Brown says he took the opportunity he was given and made the most of it, and says that he owes it to all people to work hard and continue entertaining.  He says that his struggle to receive deserved recognition that he has not yet gotten, as well as the public, motivates him to keep going.  He also talks about how the black struggle is not over, and that they need to make use of their education and wealth to improve conditions for blacks.  \r\n	Brown finishes by saying that all people have given him a chance to live â€œfive times, and they didnâ€™t get a chance to live one time,â€ and he hopes that can then live even longer past him.  He thanks them sincerely.  \r\n	Scott then goes on to preview some of the upcoming events that will be occurring over the last six weeks of the season with American Black Journal.  Such things include the Grail Galaxy, a music group and the assassination of Malcolm X.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-23','119','59','The holiday show starts with the gospel group Witness singing â€œGo Tell it On the Mountain.â€  Then, host Trudy Gallant interview the group, made up of Yolanda Harris, Lisa Page, Tina Brooks, and Diane Campbell.  She first asks them how they came together, and they say Brooks expressed interest in getting into the music business, and they slowly came together to form a girl group.  They love to sing gospel, and says that they are singing what they are â€œtrying their best to live.â€  Gallant asks them what they say to people who are saying that gospel has become too contemporary.  They say they havenâ€™t had too much of a problem with that, but they believe that you have to reach people by whatever means possible without going outside oneâ€™s surroundings, and they tell people that whether itâ€™s contemporary music or not, itâ€™s the message that matters.  \r\n	Gallant goes on to talk about Witnessâ€™ â€œbig break,â€ which happened when they were an opening act and found out that there was a representative for a record label at the time.  They talk about their present activities, such as completion of their fourth album and making of videos.  They talk about how they have a basic producer, but they do some of their own writing.  Asked how they describe their style, they say itâ€™s contemporary gospel.  \r\n	Then, the next performer, Keith Staten, the lead singer from the group Commissioned, performs â€œDonâ€™t Walk Away From Love.â€  Following his solo performance, he performs along with Witness.  After the performances, Gallant interviews Staten.  Staten starts out by talking about how he wanted to go into this business since he was a young child.  Gallant asks how long it took for it to really happen for Staten, and he talks about how he started out singing in churches and then moved on to form Commissioned.  Following this group, he moved to a group called Blessed and then back to a larger Commissioned group.  Gallant asks why he decided to go solo, and he says he initially intended to simply enhance Commissioned through his solo career rather than simply do solo work for a living, but they ran across different issues and now heâ€™s enjoying the place heâ€™s in as a solo artist even though itâ€™s not how he initially intended it to be.  \r\n	They move on to talk about his new album, â€œFrom the Heart,â€ and Staten says that itâ€™s a contemporary album that will appeal to many different ages.  Gallant asks how he hopes his music will affect people, and Staten says that he hopes people feel something from his singing and that their lives are changed.  He hopes that his singing is a â€œjob and a ministry.â€  \r\n	The show then shows a few highlights from the Essence Magazine Awards at Radio City Music Hall, hosted by Bill Cosby.  This event honored black women in the performing arts.  At the end of the event, South Africaâ€™s Winnie Mandela received the Courageous Spirit Award.  \r\n	The show closes with a look at the people who make Detroit Black Journal possible throughout the year.\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-27','119','59','The show starts out by showing a segment from â€œGunplay,â€ a documentary done by the show which took a look at the use of handguns and violence.  Gunplay features interviews with gunshot victims and their family members, as well as with other people, such as students, regarding the issue of why the use of guns has become much more widespread in recent times.  They discuss how accessible the weapons are, as well as the appeal of â€œeasy moneyâ€ associated with guns.  Many people believe that parents must be held partially responsible for their children obtaining weapons, and security measures must be increased.  \r\n	Following the clip, Gordon introduces his guests on the show: Hartford Smith, from the Wayne State School of Social Work, Commander James Younger, from the Detroit Police Departmentâ€™s Felony Prevention Unit, Emerald Crosby, the principal at Pershing High School, and a former gang member who wants to keep his true identity secret, who they refer to as â€œJoe.â€  Gordon begins by asking Joe how he felt when he saw a gunshot victim on the tape they just showed who lost the use of his legs.  Joe responds that he feels bad, and that the kind of crime involved in the shooting, where the victim was held up because he had nice sneakers that the person wanted, should be stopped.  They go on to talk about the prevalence of this type of crime, as well as other illegal activity, and Joe describes an issue where he was shot in front of his home.  Gordon then addresses the issue of how there are many young children involved in gang activity, and the two of them discuss the availability of handguns to all ages of people.  \r\n	Gordon then addresses Younger, who wants to know about some of the things that Joe did while he was involved in gang activity.  Joe describes how there are different kinds of gangs that serve different functions.  Younger then talks about the definition of gangs, and how the dictionary definition is quite different from citizensâ€™ perception.  Younger says the police classify youth gangs in terms of how theyâ€™re going to combat their activity.  \r\nSmith then comes into the discussion, talking about the social context in which gang problems grow.  He talks about the deterioration of community, especially in struggling urban areas.  He says that the conditions in these communities lead to youth searching for their own methods of survival, which can lead to gang violence.\r\nGordon then goes to the phone lines.  The first caller asks Younger what measures they are taking to keep weapons out of schools as well and off the streets.  Younger says the police department has been working with the Detroit School Board to conduct school sweeps, has intensified its street patrols, and has started more vigorous prosecution of individuals involved in weapons crimes.  He stresses the importance that citizens work to report crimes as well.  \r\nCrosby then comes into the discussion, and Gordon talks about how many weapons have been found at Pershing and other high schools during sweeps.  Crosby says that the school should be seen as an extension of what is happening in the neighborhoods, and believes that the violence problems associated with schools stems from community mentalities.  \r\nAnother call is taken.  He vouches for Joeâ€™s comments and says that everything he has been talking about is true.  Another caller asks what should be done about people who carry guns not with the goal of hurting others, but simply to protect themselves, and they go on to discuss the penalties associated with gun-carrying in Michigan.  \r\nSmith says that there is a general feeling of a lack of safety in communities, and this is the motivation for many people carrying weapons.  People also feel that police will not be able to get to places fast enough, and that is another contributor to the rapid increase in the amount of people possessing firearms.  \r\nCrosby then comes back into the discussion to talk about the environment in present-day public high schools.  He talks about how there are a lot of individuals compressed into a single school, and this generates a violent atmosphere.  He discusses the issue of the small number of supporters available to change this atmosphere for the better.  \r\nThe next caller addresses the case of the victim Shawn Norman, and says that he believes the police didnâ€™t do their job, because his attacker is still roaming free.  Gordon steers the discussion towards talking about whether there need to be changes in the judicial system.  Younger says that the community needs to take more action in influencing the practices of the judicial system.  The following caller asks Joe why there is always â€œblack on blackâ€ victimization, rather than going to other methods of crime that donâ€™t involve hurting individuals.  Crosby comments that he believes people do this because they think they can victimize certain individuals with a small amount of repercussions.  The following caller wants to know why parents canâ€™t be held responsible when their children commit crimes, and the issue is also raised about how she believes her environment has led her towards a future that doesnâ€™t involve crime, as opposed to Joeâ€™s environment.  Younger says there are certain circumstances where the parent can be held responsible.  He also talks about how certain crimes are perpetuated by the poor, but upper-class individuals can also contribute to crime as well, such as those involving the drug market.  \r\nThe next caller wants to know if including capital punishment in the judicial system would lead to a breakdown in crime.  Smith says that this has never been shown to be a deterrent to crime.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-29','119','59','The episode opens with statements from President Jimmy Carter announcing the strike settlement.  Carter also recognizes the difficulty of the job of a miner.  Next is a preview of a family, one who says that the miners have no choice but to stay out of the mines.\r\n	Host Ron Scott begins by announcing that negotiations between the United Mine Workers and representatives has been successful and a settlement has been reached.  Scott goes on to discuss some of the major details of the agreement, and then interviews Burdette Crowe, a miner, to get more info on the agreement.  Crowe however seems unfamiliar with the proposal, and does not feel comfortable commenting on specific proposals.  Scott then asks Crowe about the lack of Pension Funds in the provisional agreement, and Crowe voices his concerns and claims he will fight for pension funds in the future.  Scott also inquires about the Taft-Hartley act, which Crowe claims was not able to get miners to return to the coal mines.  Scott then thanks Crowe for joining the program.\r\nScott then turns to affiliate WWVU-TV for an interview with Len Gross, a representative of the coal industry.  Gross states that during the strike, 13 million tons of coal has been lost during the strike.  The program then shifts to Scottâ€™s interview with Charlestonâ€™s Mayor John Hutchinson.  Hutchinson downplays the negative effect of the strike of the economy of Charleston due to the diversified nature of the economy.  Hutchinson also comments on the waning influence of the United Mine Workers and the need for stability between the miners and the operators.  \r\n	Next, Scott interviews young coal miners Wayne Busby and Alec Meiklejohn.  Busby explains possible reasons behind the length of the strike, and reiterates his beliefs that the union will be able to hold out longer.  Meiklejohn comments on the lack of employment opportunities in the surrounding areas.  Busbyâ€™s wife, Kathy voices her concerns over the dangerous working environment of the mines.  She also states that she wouldnâ€™t want her son to work in the mine.  Another miner, Mike Meares, hopes that someday the mines will be run by the miners themselves, and would be able to make judgments and decisions of their own.  Meiklejohn goes on to thank the support of the Auto Workers in Detroit, and draws the connection between the plights of both unions.  \r\n	The episode then shifts to an interview with a retired miner, John Huddleston.  Scott and Huddleston discuss the lack of minerâ€™s pensions.  Huddleston also comments on the lack of unions when he began his mining career.  Huddlestonâ€™s wife Helen tells about her worries as a coal minerâ€™s wife, especially during strikes and labor disputes.  John says that he probably would still work in the mines if he could do it all over again, since he did not have the education required to obtain a better job.  \r\n	Scott then shares some statistics about the nation mortality rate in the mines.  He then joins Cecil Roberts, Pres. UMWA Dist. 17 in the mine, who discusses the contract negotiations in Washington and the dangers of working in the coal mines.  \r\n	The episode returns to the interview between Scott and Huddleston, and Huddleston reflects on his brotherâ€™s death in the mine.\r\n	Scott then closes out the episodes restating the dangers of the coal industry, and asks the viewer, â€œwhich side are you on?â€\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-2A','119','59','Performance and â€œGrapevineâ€\r\nThe show opens with Wynn and Hal McKinney performing, â€œThe Freedom Jazz Dance.â€  Then, the â€œGrapevineâ€ portion of the show, which highlights the daily events, is broadcast.  On this dayâ€™s â€œGrapevine,â€ events mentioned include the Detroit Creative Musicianâ€™s Association performance of â€œBeyond That Jazz Concert Number 3,â€ the Annual Menâ€™s Day services, the Jolly Old Timerâ€™s Annual Charity Ball, a mass meeting to discuss community control of public schools, the Fred D. Lyles Social, and Womenâ€™s Day, featuring Dr. Paulina Campbell as speaker.  Another segment of the Grapevine highlights the â€œtogether sister of the week,â€ this week Sharyl McBig, a junior at Wayne State University.  The leader of this segment, Sandy, then highlights Murray Brooks, and Co., a firm in Detroit.  She continues with other events news, such as the weekly Funky! Soul Revue.  She also mentions CPTâ€™s â€œsalesman of the week,â€ Earl Grey.  Another focus of the Grapevine is fashion, and Sandy mentions performer Diane Carol and her ensembles.  \r\nInternational Gospel Choir\r\n	The show then goes on to highlight Afro-American music and jazz.  He introduces the International Gospel Choir from the International Gospel Center, which sings â€œHigher Groundâ€ and â€œGod Never Feels.â€  They are regulars on the Sunday International Gospel radio show.  Sandy then introduces the showâ€™s feature, â€œThe Making of a Rioter,â€ which is supplemented by footage of and information about the civil disturbances that had begun the night before and is continuing throughout Detroit.  \r\nTop Story\r\n	The segment highlights that Detroitâ€™s public schools are partly responsible for the â€œmakingâ€ of rioters.  Black children in the inner city are consistently deprived of good education, and these poor schools often produce students who believe that violence is the only way to incite change.  People from the show went out and interviewed inner-city students, particularly those from Northeastern, about their opinions on their schools, and they all believe that there is great room for and need for improvement.  It seems that racism, especially on the part of the teachers, is often the biggest problem.  The students also stress that the curriculum is not preparing them for any meaningful jobs following high school and/or college.   The Black Student Association has been formed by many students at Northeastern, and their goal is to improve the substandard education given at Northeastern and make the community more aware of the problems at the school.  \r\nPerformance #2 & News\r\n	To start the second half of the show, Bill Murphy performs.   Then, Abe Ulmer presents, â€œNews from Our Point of View.â€  He talks about issues such as: a Michigan civil rights panel charging police with discrimination involving alleged police assault of a protestor at a July rebellion, the New York City public school strike by teachers, the arrest of four inner-city firms for frauds, the suspension of police officers involved in an incident at the Veteranâ€™s Memorial, and another victory by Arthur Ashe, Jr. at the Davis Cup Inter-zone Championships.  \r\nEntertainment\r\n	The next part of the show features a presentation and performance by one of the worldâ€™s best mimics, George Kirby.  Following this, Kim Westin performs, â€œWhen Johnny Comes Marching Home.â€  Then, the show takes a look at the life of Harriet Tubman, a leading â€œconductorâ€ on the Underground Railroad through a dramatic stage presentation and portrayal of her.  \r\n');
