insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-2C','119','59','Darryl Wood is joined by scholar, author, and lecturer Dr. Cornell West, who is there to discuss his new book.  West has been called many things, including an \"endangered species,\" and Wood begins by asking his guest what he thinks that means.  West replies that it could mean any black man with self-love and self-respect in modern-day life is a dying species, or that people who are seriously connected to a political struggle are a dying breed.  West has been quoted as saying that \"our capitalist civilization is killing our minds, bodies, and souls in the name of the American Dream.\" Wood asks him to explain this comment.  West believes that the system allowed the market to \"run amok\" in the past, which created a market culture and market mentality.  He says that historically, people are bombarded with this market culture. When things that are not involved in the market, such as parenting, take on this mentality, the result is \"gangsterized\" culture and politics.  \r\n	Wood then asks whether, as people move through capitalist society, West\'s goal is to create a more \"humane form\" of a capitalist society, or whether it is to change capitalist mentality to something else.  West says that it is both short-term and long-term: it is partly about keeping poor working people alive and active, and also providing access to politics and opportunities.  He fears that radical Democratic policies are waning, and that they have been left with a global capitalism.  He says that there have to be countervailing forces against the market mentality and global capitalism, and that this would involve democratization.   \r\n	Wood moves on to discuss the new movement, or \"obsidian society,\" in which West finds himself partnering to create.  West describes such as society as a foundation that would generate funds to reinvest in the black community, mainly in black young people.  He says is it would give out genius awards to inner-city youth, funding their outstanding intellectual, academic, and artistic pursuits, and he describes it as a kind of \"philanthropic endeavor\" that involves a \"re-channeling of resources into communities that are in need of investment.\"  He also says that it would involve black celebrities using their public stature to make a difference in society, and Wood asks him what he thinks could make this possible.  West gives the names of some black celebrities, such as Harry Belafonte, who have used their leverage to promote strong movements within the black community.    \r\n	Wood then addresses the issue that blacks are always seen as acting as a group, and questions whether they need to get out of their situation and support new economies and institutions that West proposes.  West says that transforming the larger society would have to involve multi-racial coalition and alliance, but these would be stronger if black solidarity was stronger, and he doesn\'t think there is a way around this solidarity.  Woods expands on this idea of multi-racialism to say that other races\' concerns all tend to get lumped in with black concerns and the black community.  He asked whether, with the net effect of diluting black solution, a coalition can truly be put together with that dynamic existing.  West says that blacks signify a certain kind of suffering that has been experienced in America, and there is no way they can separate any form of suffering from any other forms.  Their challenge is to make sure that their mission and message is not diluted, but they must also keep it broad enough that it encompasses all forms of suffering so that they don\'t get the worst of mainstream society.  He says that the black freedom struggle has never been solely about black interests, and that it\'s in the interests of all peoples\' freedom and equality.  \r\n	Wood moves on to discussing West\'s latest book, Restoring Hope: Conversations on the Future of Black America, which has a lot to do with internal qualities, such as integrity and sacrifice.  He asks what the place is of all these qualities in restoring hope, and West says that they serve to remind us of all those who came before and transmit to present-day blacks the terms of struggle and to focus on the terms of sacrifice and institution-building that came before them.  West describes how they are living in a large generation gap, where people are so shaped by market culture that their relation to their past is increasingly distant.  \r\n	West discusses the principles and ideas of Harry Belafonte at length in his book, and Wood asks West whether this was his favorite interview in the making of the book.  West says that his interview was mind-blowing, because he provides so much insight and information on so many ideas and topics.  He is also a strong believer in Belafonte\'s vision and message.  Wood also talks about West\'s interview with Charlayne Hunter-Gault, who talks about having to \"insulate herself\" in society and pass hope on to others.  West talks about having to be able to push aside the oppressive views and natures of society and having to have self-respect and dignity in order to remain strong and influential.  \r\n	Wood then jumps to the end of the book, where Maya Angelou equates hope with love, and he asks who West thinks will help black America love itself again.  West believes that it\'s the artists, the great singers, painters, writers, etc., that can help spread the message of the importance of self-love and hope.  \r\n\r\n');
