insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-2F','119','59','This show pays tribute to the works and teachings of Martin Luther King, Jr. It opens by profiling a conference held to teach teenagers how to use nonviolent methods to deal with their problems, which included a trip to the Martin Luther King Center for Nonviolent Social Change in Atlanta, Georgia. The students were touched by the trip, as many of them having never traveled outside of Detroit before.  At the center, they were taught the six principles of non-violence: 1) Non-violence is a way of life for courageous people, 2) Non-violence seeks to win friendship and understanding, 3) Non-violence seeks to defeat injustice, not people, 4) Non-violence holds that suffering can educate and transform, 5) Non-violence chooses love instead of hate, and 6) Non-violence believes that the universe is on the side of justice.  They then learned how to implement the principles they had learned through the six steps for non-violent social change: 1) Information gathering, 2) Education, 3), Personal commitment, 4) Negotiations, 5) Direct action, and 6) Reconciliation, and attended information and participation sessions where they talked about their experiences with violence and non-violence, and how to use their new tactics for non-violence.  They also got to mingle with and meet other black students from all over the country.  \r\n	The group also meets Coretta Scott King, who started the center and has continued to be involved with it.  She expresses that it is her commitment to Martin Luther Kingâ€™s dream that keeps her going and keeps her fighting for her principles, including the formation of a true community, the elimination of evils in society, and helping people to believe in themselves.  She wants this center to institutionalize Kingâ€™s teachings and message, and believes that it is important to create a program that works with all ages of people.  She says that her contribution would be to make sure that Kingâ€™s vision and dream of a â€œbeloved world communityâ€ would become a reality, and she believes that the King center is an answer to that.        \r\n	King goes on to talk about the struggles that the black community still faces today. She notes that, at the present time, there are fewer blatant signs in society of segregation, so many  young people donâ€™t always see obvious ways in which they can get involved.  She believes that this is one opportunity that the center can offer young people, along with hope and the opportunity for them to believe in themselves.  She also believes that multiculturalism is imperative for peace and for the formation of true community, where people can find common ground and learn to live with people of a variety of circumstances and characteristics.\r\n	She goes on to say that the highlight of her life was in 1964, when King received the Nobel Peace Prize for his work and for developing a method of struggle that could help liberate people.  This seemed to â€œaffirm all that had been done,â€ and was the greatest moment of fulfillment that she ever had.  \r\n	The show closes with a clip from Kingâ€™s famous â€œI Have a Dreamâ€ speech.\r\n');
