insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-32','119','59','Host Cliff Russell introduces the episode by discussing the difficulties black youth face in a college atmosphere.  Before the episode beings however, the episode takes a look back at a previous episode dealing with the civil unrest after the Rodney King verdict.  Russell then shifts the focus back to the youth, and introduces his guests.  These are Darryl Dawsey, who was a spokesperson for the students during the Wayne State University protests, Byron Williams, a spokesperson for the Michigan African Student Coalition, Tomeka Mingo, Ms. NAACP, and Dr. John Telfert, from MOSAIC. \r\n	Russel begins with Dawsey, asking him what was behind the Wayne State University protests.  Dawsey claims that Wayne State has not made many movements in a positive direction, and it has not been true to itâ€™s word and has not given out scholarships for African studies or implemented student recommended courses.  He also says that during his time at Wayne State, the university was an area under white supremacy, and this has lasted.  \r\n	Williams then discusses his experiences at Olivet College, and talks about how the black students had to take a back seat to the white students in regards to course implementation and fraternities.  They seemed to be â€œforgotten about,â€ and white studentsâ€™ interests were much more focused on.  Williams says that the universityâ€™s actions were made to seem like they were not racially motivated, so because of this there was no open hostility.    \r\n	Mingo then comments on both college and high school campuses and how a lot of young people are not aware of the racial problems that still remain in todayâ€™s society.  She says that through certain programs, young people can become aware of these problems and find non-violent ways to resist and make their voices heard.    \r\n	Russel then introduces Dr. John Telford, who starts out by talking about white academia.  He discusses how many institutions fail to recognize that they are still functioning under a racist system, and the leaders of these institutions need to be sensitized.  He says that there are many educational leaders who either sweep the problem under the rug, or simply donâ€™t realize the gravity of the problem.  He also stresses that it must be whites, who are the countryâ€™s power structure, to voice the problem and take the leadership.  \r\n	Russell then asks Dawsey what he sees as necessary to effect change.  He responds that students should step up the pressure on the administration, and also stresses that white students as well as blacks should be required to take Africana Studies, because whites are not the majority, and understanding African history and culture is necessary for coexistence and good relations between races.\r\n	Diana Craig, a correspondent for DBJ, went out to local campuses, and interviews with students reveal their viewpoints that different races donâ€™t understand each other and that races have been separated.  \r\n	DBJ then goes to the phones, and the first caller wants to know whether it was a good idea to walk out on Olivet College to make change in the system.  Williams says that it was unfair to them as students, because the administration didnâ€™t work to make things safe for them and upheld a hostile environment.  The next caller comments that there is a need for all cultures to be exposed to their cultural heritage early in life, and also wants to know what the panel thinks in the universityâ€™s role in exposing students to cultures prior to high school and college.  Telford says that itâ€™s essential that all students receive an education that covers the heritage of a wide variety of cultures in order to grow up accepting of all cultures.  Mingo comments that African American history classes are offered at her high school that students are required to take in order to graduate.  \r\n	A person from the audience comments that, when he was in college, he saw that black students who transferred from a predominately white college to a black college found that they were able to escape the racism and problems that they had faced.  He advocates that more young adults go to historically black colleges, because he says that at such institutions one receives more of a foundation, and one can then move on to universities that are whiter.  Dawsey disagrees a bit, and says that someone doesnâ€™t have to go to college to learn what it means to be black or white, but stresses that all people, respective of their choice of university, begin to discover their heritage and its importance early on.  \r\n	The next caller, a white college student, agrees with the fact that there is white racism occurring that restricts the opportunities for blacks, and asks for whites to be let in more to learn about black culture.  Williams comments that whites who want to help the black cause should try and change the viewpoints of their prejudiced friends and colleagues and make their viewpoints known.  \r\n	The program finishes by highlighting the Freedom Festival Fireworks, at which the theme will be â€œA Celebration of Freedom: Family Fun and the Fireworks.â€  \r\n');
