insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-35','119','59','Gordon is joined by two Detroit School Board members, Clara Rutherford and Alonzo Bates, to talk about the recent criticism and scrutiny that has been directed towards and placed on the school board for its actions.  Gordon begins by reading a statement made by the Superintendent of Schools, saying that financial issues are the biggest problem for the school district.  He then asks Bates whether he thinks the board is spending too much money on travel and other perks.  He says no, and that board members do not create travel, and have rather tried to eliminate excessive amounts of it.  They do travel, but only to beneficial conferences and forums that can educate them and make them better board members.  Gordon goes through figures that highlight high spending on travel, especially in regards to spending money on first class travel.  Bates says that this cannot be considered excessive when one looks at the million dollars brought in by the board to the school system.  He also notes the high amount of international travel that was done, which could contribute to the $15,000 spent on travel in fiscal year 1986.\r\n	Gordon then addresses Rutherford, asking whether perhaps, because of the deficits the school system is facing, they should step back and amend some practices, such as traveling coach instead of first-class.  She does not attempt to defend traveling first class, and attempts to look at the fact that there is still eight million dollars in the budget, and the fact that there are many board members in other school districts who receive a large amount of that money and perks that those who are not on the Detroit School Board do not.  She also talks about ways in which they have worked against helping reverse the deficit, such as raising wages for workers.  Both Rutherford and Bates feel that the board is being picked on, and Bates says that their lack of perks as board members is racially motivated.  \r\n	Gordon then goes to the phone lines.  The first caller asks Bates how previous abuse of perks justifies present-day abuse of perks, and what the proven benefits are of the trips that are taken.  Bates responds that he did not create board travel, and he feels that Bates Academy, a school for intellectually gifted kids that he created, is a result of his travel, and he feels that both he and the board have grown over time.  The next caller says that he sends his caller to a Catholic school because he would never send him to a Detroit school, and that people are tired of board members saying that because white people did certain things, then they should be entitled to do them too.  Rutherford says that, in sending a child to a Catholic school, that in itself is following white people, but Gordon pushes her to address the overall issue of the large number of people who do not want to enroll their children in the Detroit Public School system.  Rutherford talks about the issue of shootings, and feels that the Detroit Public Schools are the â€œcourts of last resort.â€  She laments the fact that they are poorly funded and provided with poor resources, but are expected to provide private schools with support.  \r\n	Gordon moves on to address the issue of chauffeurs, and board members allegedly using them for personal reasons and on their own time.  He asks their position on the chauffeurs for the board members.  Rutherford says that these drivers are used professionally to pick up checks and other things, and says that she doesnâ€™t believe that they are being used for personal reasons.  She also says that she feels safer after getting a driver to go places, because she has not been attacked as she was during her travels alone before.  Bates then laments the fact that the Board of Education is a â€œdumping groundâ€ for peopleâ€™s problems and issues.\r\n	Another call is taken, and he wants to know whether they are getting off track with uses of and discussions of travels and chauffeurs, and whether they should rather be focusing on the students and improving the school system.  Rutherford talks about Town and Countryâ€™s list of the top high schools in the country, and she mentions one of their own schools that were listed.  She also mentions programs that are being used to aid struggling students who need a bit more assistance.  She believes that they have an excellent school system in many ways.  The next caller is a teacher at Jesu School, who comments that he voted for both of the board members, but he believes that they are no longer upholding their policies that they presented when they first ran, and that they should spell out what their policies are so that people can understand them and vote for them up or down.  \r\n	Gordon mentions the scandal and litigation surrounding the resignation of board member Harold Murdoch, who was accused of accepting payola, and asks what the role of the board is in terms of awarding contracts.  Bates lashes out at Fickelstein, who he believes is attacking Bates and the board in regards to their policies and actions.  Rutherford also mentions how 52 percent of the boards monies go to minority contractors, and this was the sole purpose of their program.\r\n	Detroit Free Press columnist Susan Watson then provides her commentary on the issue.  She says that someone should tell them that they are elected to work for the students and not for themselves, and should not spend a good deal of money on personal perks.  She says that she thinks they believe that â€œgetting elected to the School Board is the same as winning the state lottery; all your dreams come true.â€  \r\n');
