insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-3B','119','59','Cliff Russell sits down with leading Metro-Detroit black auto dealership owners and discusses their perspectives on minorities and the automobile industry.\r\n\r\nSummary: The episode opens with a remote report from Diana Craig discussing the upcoming plans for the Big Three for the automotive year.  \r\nCliff Russell begins by expressing the difficulties of owing a car dealership in Detroit, and introduces his four guests: Mel Farr, Charles Harrell, Theresa Jones and Nathan Conyers.\r\nRussell begins by expressing amazement that he is joined by four black car dealers who are still in business, however Farr downplays this notion, saying that the worst has passed economically.  Conyers claims that 16 black owned dealerships in the State of Michigan is significant, and predicts that the number is bound to go up.  \r\n	Russell asks the group what it will take to increase the number of African Americans in the car dealership business, and Harrell says that the success of current black dealers will persuade more African Americans to enter the business.  Russell then asks what it takes to be qualified to run a dealership, and Jones suggests that the most important factors are training and having qualified employees to help operate the dealership.  \r\n	The group then goes on to discuss the issue of support from the auto companies, and how it affects their business.  Jones compliments Chrysler on their support; however Conyers suggests that manufacturers may not be doing enough to encourage black owned dealerships.  The group reflects on Ed Davis, the first black dealer for a Big Three automaker, and the progress that has been made during the past half a century.\r\n	Russell begins to take calls, and the first caller suggests that black dealerships may have difficulties because they are based in poorer, inner city neighborhoods.  The caller also recognizes the problem of credit in the inner city poor.  Farr agrees on the callerâ€™s points, and Harrell comments that auto dealers can potentially help people with credit problems.\r\n	The second caller addresses the view that women are not treated the same as men during an automobile purchase.  Jones comments that large parts of her business are female consumers, and that she cannot afford to treat them poorly.  Conyers comments on the change of culture in America, and advises females to not accept poor treatment.\r\nHarrell echoes those sentiments, saying that females or minorities should not tolerate false truths.  \r\n	The third caller inquires into the process of becoming an automobile salesperson, and both Farr and Conyers both implore listeners to reach out to dealerships if interested in employment in the auto dealership business.  \r\n	Another caller laments on the service of sales representatives after the car has been sold.  Farr denounces this treatment and stresses that his dealership depends on return customers.  \r\n	The group then discusses the myth that automobiles purchased from white dealerships are of higher quality.  Jones stresses that all dealerships receive the same cars from the companies and Conyers suggest that it might be a social problem.\r\n	Russell thanks the panel for joining him and then stresses the importance of the auto industry.  After suggesting viewers call the hotline telephone number, he reminds viewers about the North American Auto Show. \r\n');
