rable,â€ as well as making sure that the law cracks down hard on people who carry weapons and instigate violence.  He also believes that the desire to cause violence is a socializing process that must be reversed through the work of citizens themselves.\r\n	Gordon asks Jackson what must be done in order to get the male role model back in the community.  Jackson says that mothers must not give up if the man is not around, and also men must be oriented towards their responsibility as fathers, and it must be seen as unacceptable that men donâ€™t provide for and care for their children.  \r\n	Another caller is taken, and they want to know whether he thinks South Africa had anything to do with the death of Samora Michelâ€™s.  Jackson believes that it definitely had a hand in this, which didnâ€™t contact the Mozambiquan government until nine hours after the plane crash, resulting in the death of many people.  He says that they also used beams to redirect the plane off course.  Also, the Defense Minister of South Africa threatened Michel two weeks before the plane went down.  \r\n	Gordon gets back to talking about the issue of youth, and the problem of drugs is mentioned, which Jackson sees as the number one threat that faces them.  He believes that they should not make the mistake of thinking that youth are the only ones involved in drugs.  Rather, the epidemic involves all kinds of people.  They should know where the drugs are coming from and protect their borders from the incoming drugs, they should institute better drug education, and they should also make sure that their mass educators promote the message that drugs are destructive and dangerous.  \r\n	Another call is taken from the phone lines, and this is a Detroit high school student who wants to know what they can do to keep drugs and weapons out of schools when there arenâ€™t that many armed guards at the schools.  Jackson says that first the student must themselves say no to drugs, and then they must be ready and willing to use whatever means is necessary to prevent such things from getting into the schools.  He supports the idea that schools should use means such as metal detectors in order to make educational institutions safe havens away from violence and drugs.  Jackson is a firm believer that society can afford to secure schools.  The last person who calls in wants to know what Jackson thinks will happen to the large bodies of people graduating from school who are illiterate.  Jackson thinks that they will struggle greatly unless there are adult literacy programs that can help them, and therefore young people must be urged to become literate.  \r\n	Gordon then asks whether the program Push Excel, which worked to bring together students, parents, teachers, and administrators, might be reinstated in order to help the educational system again.  Jackson believes that certain schools are promoting the good mentality of people being welcomed at and privileged to be at school, but this mentality must be spread and people must understand that they must live with the consequences of their own actions.\r\n	They close the show with Whitney Houstonâ€™s song, â€œThe Greatest Love of All.â€\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-4C','119','59','Darryl Wood is joined by civil rights activist and national talk show host, the Reverend Jesse Jackson.  Wood begins by addressing the issue of the current political situation, in particular recent speculation that Colin Powell might run for president.  Wood asks whether Jackson thinks that America is ready to elect a black president. Jackson is unsure: he highlights Powellâ€™s good qualities as a possible candidate, but notes that the question is of priorities and values, such as the problem of the urban crisis, which no one is addressing.  Jackson believes that significant issues must be addressed in the upcoming presidential race.  \r\n	Wood goes on to ask whether the lack of black mobilization to vote is influenced by the fact that certain issues such as the urban crisis are not generally addressed by politicians.  Jackson agrees, but he believes that mobilization without connections to public policy is not enough.  Jackson addresses his reputation for surrounding himself with a wide range of activists, such as Louis Farrakhan, and he says that one must be judged not by association, but by what they do themselves.  He hopes, through his coalitions, to push for an overall goal of fairness and equality.  \r\n	If alliances are formed, Wood asks, can they accomplish all that they hope to if they are extremely diverse, or should they be more focused on \'black issues\' and associate mainly with blacks.  Jackson says that racial justice and gender equality are black issues, but there are other issues, such as welfare, that were beneficial to whites first.  He says that none of these issues will be resolved until blacks and whites can come together, eliminate race designations to social problems, and fight as an alliance.  \r\n	They then go on to talk about who it is that champions the cause for unemployed blacks, and Jackson says that the leadership has to come from blacks, who must â€œurge for changeâ€ and â€œstrike the first blow.â€  However, a broader base of people must take action in order to implement true change, especially to the problem of racist jail policies.  Jackson says that it is necessary that good economic policies and commercial success can come to urban areas.  \r\n	Wood then asks what blacks must to in order to mobilize their communities.  Jackson believes that a specific plan of action must be developed, in which each person understands the goals for which they are working and what steps they must take to get there.  They move into talking about Jacksonâ€™s possible next run for the presidency, and Woods asks when he will announce his bid to run, which Jackson says that he is unsure of.   He is reluctant to run again and would rather that President Clinton honor his campaign priorities. If he does not address the urban problems, however, Jackson says that he will be forced to challenge Clinton.  However, he would rather support the President in his campaign, as long as he follows through on his campaign promises.  Jackson describes his possible run for president as an â€œopen question.â€  \r\n	Jackson finishes his interview, and then the program moves on to a discussion of the Jeffries Housing Project, part of the program Art in the Urban, run by Project REACH.  Deborah Franklin, one of the founders of this program, is interviewed. She says that the program developed out of a perception that the needs of black children were not being met.  She hopes to use art and cultural demonstrations and activities to bring self-esteem to the children of Jeffries residents.  She believes that giving these children self-esteem will enable them to reject antisocial behavior and pursue a better future.  Rene Lowe, another worker for REACH, is interviewed, as are residents such as Lois Williams.  \r\n');
