insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-5A','119','59','The show starts out by showing a segment from â€œGunplay,â€ a documentary done by the show which took a look at the use of handguns and violence.  Gunplay features interviews with gunshot victims and their family members, as well as with other people, such as students, regarding the issue of why the use of guns has become much more widespread in recent times.  They discuss how accessible the weapons are, as well as the appeal of â€œeasy moneyâ€ associated with guns.  Many people believe that parents must be held partially responsible for their children obtaining weapons, and security measures must be increased.  \r\n	Following the clip, Gordon introduces his guests on the show: Hartford Smith, from the Wayne State School of Social Work, Commander James Younger, from the Detroit Police Departmentâ€™s Felony Prevention Unit, Emerald Crosby, the principal at Pershing High School, and a former gang member who wants to keep his true identity secret, who they refer to as â€œJoe.â€  Gordon begins by asking Joe how he felt when he saw a gunshot victim on the tape they just showed who lost the use of his legs.  Joe responds that he feels bad, and that the kind of crime involved in the shooting, where the victim was held up because he had nice sneakers that the person wanted, should be stopped.  They go on to talk about the prevalence of this type of crime, as well as other illegal activity, and Joe describes an issue where he was shot in front of his home.  Gordon then addresses the issue of how there are many young children involved in gang activity, and the two of them discuss the availability of handguns to all ages of people.  \r\n	Gordon then addresses Younger, who wants to know about some of the things that Joe did while he was involved in gang activity.  Joe describes how there are different kinds of gangs that serve different functions.  Younger then talks about the definition of gangs, and how the dictionary definition is quite different from citizensâ€™ perception.  Younger says the police classify youth gangs in terms of how theyâ€™re going to combat their activity.  \r\nSmith then comes into the discussion, talking about the social context in which gang problems grow.  He talks about the deterioration of community, especially in struggling urban areas.  He says that the conditions in these communities lead to youth searching for their own methods of survival, which can lead to gang violence.\r\nGordon then goes to the phone lines.  The first caller asks Younger what measures they are taking to keep weapons out of schools as well and off the streets.  Younger says the police department has been working with the Detroit School Board to conduct school sweeps, has intensified its street patrols, and has started more vigorous prosecution of individuals involved in weapons crimes.  He stresses the importance that citizens work to report crimes as well.  \r\nCrosby then comes into the discussion, and Gordon talks about how many weapons have been found at Pershing and other high schools during sweeps.  Crosby says that the school should be seen as an extension of what is happening in the neighborhoods, and believes that the violence problems associated with schools stems from community mentalities.  \r\nAnother call is taken.  He vouches for Joeâ€™s comments and says that everything he has been talking about is true.  Another caller asks what should be done about people who carry guns not with the goal of hurting others, but simply to protect themselves, and they go on to discuss the penalties associated with gun-carrying in Michigan.  \r\nSmith says that there is a general feeling of a lack of safety in communities, and this is the motivation for many people carrying weapons.  People also feel that police will not be able to get to places fast enough, and that is another contributor to the rapid increase in the amount of people possessing firearms.  \r\nCrosby then comes back into the discussion to talk about the environment in present-day public high schools.  He talks about how there are a lot of individuals compressed into a single school, and this generates a violent atmosphere.  He discusses the issue of the small number of supporters available to change this atmosphere for the better.  \r\nThe next caller addresses the case of the victim Shawn Norman, and says that he believes the police didnâ€™t do their job, because his attacker is still roaming free.  Gordon steers the discussion towards talking about whether there need to be changes in the judicial system.  Younger says that the community needs to take more action in influencing the practices of the judicial system.  The following caller asks Joe why there is always â€œblack on blackâ€ victimization, rather than going to other methods of crime that donâ€™t involve hurting individuals.  Crosby comments that he believes people do this because they think they can victimize certain individuals with a small amount of repercussions.  The following caller wants to know why parents canâ€™t be held responsible when their children commit crimes, and the issue is also raised about how she believes her environment has led her towards a future that doesnâ€™t involve crime, as opposed to Joeâ€™s environment.  Younger says there are certain circumstances where the parent can be held responsible.  He also talks about how certain crimes are perpetuated by the poor, but upper-class individuals can also contribute to crime as well, such as those involving the drug market.  \r\nThe next caller wants to know if including capital punishment in the judicial system would lead to a breakdown in crime.  Smith says that this has never been shown to be a deterrent to crime.  \r\n');
