insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-5C','119','59','The holiday show starts with the gospel group Witness singing â€œGo Tell it On the Mountain.â€  Then, host Trudy Gallant interview the group, made up of Yolanda Harris, Lisa Page, Tina Brooks, and Diane Campbell.  She first asks them how they came together, and they say Brooks expressed interest in getting into the music business, and they slowly came together to form a girl group.  They love to sing gospel, and says that they are singing what they are â€œtrying their best to live.â€  Gallant asks them what they say to people who are saying that gospel has become too contemporary.  They say they havenâ€™t had too much of a problem with that, but they believe that you have to reach people by whatever means possible without going outside oneâ€™s surroundings, and they tell people that whether itâ€™s contemporary music or not, itâ€™s the message that matters.  \r\n	Gallant goes on to talk about Witnessâ€™ â€œbig break,â€ which happened when they were an opening act and found out that there was a representative for a record label at the time.  They talk about their present activities, such as completion of their fourth album and making of videos.  They talk about how they have a basic producer, but they do some of their own writing.  Asked how they describe their style, they say itâ€™s contemporary gospel.  \r\n	Then, the next performer, Keith Staten, the lead singer from the group Commissioned, performs â€œDonâ€™t Walk Away From Love.â€  Following his solo performance, he performs along with Witness.  After the performances, Gallant interviews Staten.  Staten starts out by talking about how he wanted to go into this business since he was a young child.  Gallant asks how long it took for it to really happen for Staten, and he talks about how he started out singing in churches and then moved on to form Commissioned.  Following this group, he moved to a group called Blessed and then back to a larger Commissioned group.  Gallant asks why he decided to go solo, and he says he initially intended to simply enhance Commissioned through his solo career rather than simply do solo work for a living, but they ran across different issues and now heâ€™s enjoying the place heâ€™s in as a solo artist even though itâ€™s not how he initially intended it to be.  \r\n	They move on to talk about his new album, â€œFrom the Heart,â€ and Staten says that itâ€™s a contemporary album that will appeal to many different ages.  Gallant asks how he hopes his music will affect people, and Staten says that he hopes people feel something from his singing and that their lives are changed.  He hopes that his singing is a â€œjob and a ministry.â€  \r\n	The show then shows a few highlights from the Essence Magazine Awards at Radio City Music Hall, hosted by Bill Cosby.  This event honored black women in the performing arts.  At the end of the event, South Africaâ€™s Winnie Mandela received the Courageous Spirit Award.  \r\n	The show closes with a look at the people who make Detroit Black Journal possible throughout the year.\r\n');
