insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-5E','119','59','This show takes an in-depth look at  Louis Farrakhan and his policies.  It starts out, however, by providing some history with footage from a press conference in Detroit with Farrakhan, about how Islam has great roots in Detroit and about Muslim leader Elijah Mohammed.  He talks about the growth and progression of Islam and about how blacks suffer from self-hatred and inferiority, which results in  economic, political, and civic struggle.  He discusses the \'Stop the Killing\' program that is now extending into the Detroit area.  \r\n	Rasul Muhammad, the Nation of Islamâ€™s local leader, joins Gallant to discuss these issues and Louis Farrakhan himself.  Gallant starts by asking what the organization is doing in regards to the \'Stop the Killing\' program.  Muhammad talks about how Farrakhanâ€™s message spurs blacks to take action.  They are planning for Halfway Homes, where people can stay, get back on track, and work towards independence, which he believes is essential for blacks to progress.  They want to encourage people to keep their living areas and communities in good condition, and have been working to go in and clean up housing projects.  \r\n	Another clip is shown from the press conference, where Farrakhan defends himself in regards to statements that he had made, some of which were seen as anti-Semitic.  He says that his words were distorted because whites  fear that Farrakhan could mobilize blacks and get them to take action in the community.  He also believes that he has been labeled as hateful because blacks have been taught to love all people except themselves.  He says that his critical analyses of Jews are simply critical, not anti-Semitic, and he hates that people refer to him as the â€œnew black Hitler.â€  \r\n	Gallant asks whether Muhammadâ€™s organization still gets a lot of repercussions from Farrakhanâ€™s remarks.  Muhammad says that the repercussions come mainly from their own people who are ignorant of the facts.  The Nation of Islamâ€™s position is that because their people suffer extremely, especially in relation to recognition of oneâ€™s identity, separation is the answer until education takes place, and then the country can begin to interact with others.  They want a separate state geographically, as long as the white government continues as it is.  \r\n	A third clip is shown from the news conference, addressing the issue of whether American blacks are entitled to reparations, comparing their plight to that of the Japanese-Americans who did receive reparations.  Farrakhan demands that they receive some form of reparations from the government, and is frustrated with the current allocation of government money.  \r\n	Calls are then taken from viewers.  The first caller wants to hear Muhammadâ€™s views on the underlying problems in Iraq.  He believes that they have no need to be in Iraq fighting for causes and conditions that have nothing to do with their own needs and values.  He thinks that they sometimes get too involved in issues abroad and forget about their own issues, and believe that the Iraqis should be left to handle their own problems.  The next caller wants to know what Muhammad has to say about the seemingly anti-Semitic and anti-Christian views of the Islamic community.  He believes that if all people, no matter what their religion, practice the principles of god, then it is â€œonly the title that keeps them away from one another.â€  He is firm that there â€œis no anti-anything, as long as you are pro-god.â€  The third caller wants to know why Muhammad isnâ€™t very visible and active in the community.  He talks about how they have a few hundred active, working supporters in the community, and he says that he himself has been doing a lot of travel, so he hasnâ€™t been that visible.  But he hopes that they will soon be very visible in the community in the times to come.  The fourth caller wants to know how black people can understand the psychological damages from slavery that still affect them today.  Muhammad says that all community leaders should come together, and blacks must have self-sufficiency.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-5F','119','59','Performance and â€œGrapevineâ€\r\nThe show opens with Wynn and Hal McKinney performing, â€œThe Freedom Jazz Dance.â€  Then, the â€œGrapevineâ€ portion of the show, which highlights the daily events, is broadcast.  On this dayâ€™s â€œGrapevine,â€ events mentioned include the Detroit Creative Musicianâ€™s Association performance of â€œBeyond That Jazz Concert Number 3,â€ the Annual Menâ€™s Day services, the Jolly Old Timerâ€™s Annual Charity Ball, a mass meeting to discuss community control of public schools, the Fred D. Lyles Social, and Womenâ€™s Day, featuring Dr. Paulina Campbell as speaker.  Another segment of the Grapevine highlights the â€œtogether sister of the week,â€ this week Sharyl McBig, a junior at Wayne State University.  The leader of this segment, Sandy, then highlights Murray Brooks, and Co., a firm in Detroit.  She continues with other events news, such as the weekly Funky! Soul Revue.  She also mentions CPTâ€™s â€œsalesman of the week,â€ Earl Grey.  Another focus of the Grapevine is fashion, and Sandy mentions performer Diane Carol and her ensembles.  \r\nInternational Gospel Choir\r\n	The show then goes on to highlight Afro-American music and jazz.  He introduces the International Gospel Choir from the International Gospel Center, which sings â€œHigher Groundâ€ and â€œGod Never Feels.â€  They are regulars on the Sunday International Gospel radio show.  Sandy then introduces the showâ€™s feature, â€œThe Making of a Rioter,â€ which is supplemented by footage of and information about the civil disturbances that had begun the night before and is continuing throughout Detroit.  \r\nTop Story\r\n	The segment highlights that Detroitâ€™s public schools are partly responsible for the â€œmakingâ€ of rioters.  Black children in the inner city are consistently deprived of good education, and these poor schools often produce students who believe that violence is the only way to incite change.  People from the show went out and interviewed inner-city students, particularly those from Northeastern, about their opinions on their schools, and they all believe that there is great room for and need for improvement.  It seems that racism, especially on the part of the teachers, is often the biggest problem.  The students also stress that the curriculum is not preparing them for any meaningful jobs following high school and/or college.   The Black Student Association has been formed by many students at Northeastern, and their goal is to improve the substandard education given at Northeastern and make the community more aware of the problems at the school.  \r\nPerformance #2 & News\r\n	To start the second half of the show, Bill Murphy performs.   Then, Abe Ulmer presents, â€œNews from Our Point of View.â€  He talks about issues such as: a Michigan civil rights panel charging police with discrimination involving alleged police assault of a protestor at a July rebellion, the New York City public school strike by teachers, the arrest of four inner-city firms for frauds, the suspension of police officers involved in an incident at the Veteranâ€™s Memorial, and another victory by Arthur Ashe, Jr. at the Davis Cup Inter-zone Championships.  \r\nEntertainment\r\n	The next part of the show features a presentation and performance by one of the worldâ€™s best mimics, George Kirby.  Following this, Kim Westin performs, â€œWhen Johnny Comes Marching Home.â€  Then, the show takes a look at the life of Harriet Tubman, a leading â€œconductorâ€ on the Underground Railroad through a dramatic stage presentation and portrayal of her.  \r\n');
