insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-65','119','59','This interview focuses on the problems facing a new generation of urban youths, and Jackson begins by talking about what blacks must do to help turn things around.  First, they must say that things such as drugs, rape, and crime must be seen as morally wrong and a societal wrongdoing.  He says that men must also â€œbear the burden of their behavior,â€ as well as fight for  more jobs and better housing.  He believes that people need a greater sense of personal responsibility.\r\n	Gordon then asks Jackson what he sees as the reason for why things are so particularly bad now, when blacks have always faced oppression.  Jackson says that rural and urban crime are quite different, and also that behavior has become extremely centralized. Through the mass media, the same picture of an acceptable lifestyle is given to people all over.  He says that disc jockeys, program directors, athletes, and other mass must exercise some â€œsocial judgmentâ€ about what messages they are sending to youth.\r\n	They then take calls. The first caller, a high school instructor, wants to know how he can tell his students that education and religion are a better option than drugs and crime.  Jackson believes that he canâ€™t do it by himself, but he believes that the instructor can challenge those students one-on-one who approach him about such issues.  The next caller wants to know what can be done to reduce teenage unemployment.  Jackson talks about how a new Senate leadership was elected that is more focused on employment issues, and says that people who have the vote must exercise this power to push for more jobs and increased employment.  He believes that the youth are not taught how to use their vote.  The third caller asks Jackson what sorts of suggestions he has in terms of curbing teen violence in urban areas.  He replies that they must â€œcrowd against itâ€ and create a â€œclimate to make it intolerable,â€ as well as making sure that the law cracks down hard on people who carry weapons and instigate violence.  He also believes that the desire to cause violence is a socializing process that must be reversed through the work of citizens themselves.\r\n	Gordon asks Jackson what must be done in order to get the male role model back in the community.  Jackson says that mothers must not give up if the man is not around, and also men must be oriented towards their responsibility as fathers, and it must be seen as unacceptable that men donâ€™t provide for and care for their children.  \r\n	Another caller is taken, and they want to know whether he thinks South Africa had anything to do with the death of Samora Michelâ€™s.  Jackson believes that it definitely had a hand in this, which didnâ€™t contact the Mozambiquan government until nine hours after the plane crash, resulting in the death of many people.  He says that they also used beams to redirect the plane off course.  Also, the Defense Minister of South Africa threatened Michel two weeks before the plane went down.  \r\n	Gordon gets back to talking about the issue of youth, and the problem of drugs is mentioned, which Jackson sees as the number one threat that faces them.  He believes that they should not make the mistake of thinking that youth are the only ones involved in drugs.  Rather, the epidemic involves all kinds of people.  They should know where the drugs are coming from and protect their borders from the incoming drugs, they should institute better drug education, and they should also make sure that their mass educators promote the message that drugs are destructive and dangerous.  \r\n	Another call is taken from the phone lines, and this is a Detroit high school student who wants to know what they can do to keep drugs and weapons out of schools when there arenâ€™t that many armed guards at the schools.  Jackson says that first the student must themselves say no to drugs, and then they must be ready and willing to use whatever means is necessary to prevent such things from getting into the schools.  He supports the idea that schools should use means such as metal detectors in order to make educational institutions safe havens away from violence and drugs.  Jackson is a firm believer that society can afford to secure schools.  The last person who calls in wants to know what Jackson thinks will happen to the large bodies of people graduating from school who are illiterate.  Jackson thinks that they will struggle greatly unless there are adult literacy programs that can help them, and therefore young people must be urged to become literate.  \r\n	Gordon then asks whether the program Push Excel, which worked to bring together students, parents, teachers, and administrators, might be reinstated in order to help the educational system again.  Jackson believes that certain schools are promoting the good mentality of people being welcomed at and privileged to be at school, but this mentality must be spread and people must understand that they must live with the consequences of their own actions.\r\n	They close the show with Whitney Houstonâ€™s song, â€œThe Greatest Love of All.â€\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-66','119','59','This show is entitled â€œTo Be Woman, Gifted, and Black: From One Generation to Another,â€ and host Gene Elzy begins by saying that they will be talking with singer Lena Horne and writer/poet Nikki Giovanni, who have been touring together across the country.  Horne, who has also been an active member in the civil rights struggle, is the first interviewee.  \r\n	Elzy first poses the question as to whether the road to success for the black performer has changed over the years.  Horne believes so, and says that the present generation does not face the same stresses of her generation.  She does, however, believe that her generation was fortunate to have been able to listen to and draw from the black stars of earlier years.  He also asks her about what disciplines she learned as a young child that now carry her over into her present-day performing.  She states her belief that â€œthe show must go on,â€ and she was always taught to be professional and disciplined, no matter what.  \r\n	Horneâ€™s grandmother was a very good friend of Mary McCloud Bethoon, and Horne had the opportunity to meet her. Horne was enlisted by her in the National Council of Negro Women, and she was the main reason that Horne is a Delta.  Horne also talks about the strength of present-day black women, saying that they are as strong as past black women, but for different reasons.  \r\n	Horne then is asked to provide any thoughts she has for young entertainers who are going to have to â€œfight that fight.â€  She doesnâ€™t think theyâ€™ll have the same stresses, but she knows that itâ€™s rough economically at the present time for both whites and blacks, and she has learned to be more sympathetic to all sorts of people.  \r\n	Horne talks about her upcoming retirement from cabaret, and says that although she wonâ€™t be singing in that kind of setting anymore, she will continue to give concerts and do TV appearances and shows.  \r\n	The next interview is with Nikki Giovanni, starting with a discussion of her new book, â€œCotton Candy on a Rainy Day,â€ and whether it is different from her previous works or more personal and different.  She sees it as an outgrowth of her first book, and rather than being a departure, it is a natural maturation.  She stresses the importance of learning and growing from experiences.  She also talks about her decision to be a writer, and says that â€œthe form chooses the writer,â€ and every writer has his or her own discipline.  \r\n	She says that she would not be able to think of herself as a typical black woman, but what she shares with other black women is a strong curiosity and a desire to make things better.  She hopes that she can be helpful to black women in any way possible, because she believes that they are a great asset to the world.  She also believes that through her work, she will pave the way for other black poets to make their own mark on the world.  She sees it as a constant kind of progression, where children take up where parents left off and other citizens draw on peopleâ€™s examples.  \r\n	She also talks about how women are most certainly the backbone of families, because they are the ones who teach the children.  She supports men, but stresses that the family is â€œset by the woman.â€  She is then asked what she thinks the seventies brought and what she believes the eighties will hold for black men and women.  She thinks that the eighties will bring new definitions for life, men, women, and more, and give people new senses of what everything truly is.  Blacks will also be in the unique decision to create the definitions.  \r\n	Giovanni has been quoted as saying she was disappointed by the fact that the books published now hardly give any contribution to the black contributions of earlier times, especially the sixties.  She talks about how children believe that they are educated and are the way they are only because of the contributions of white people, and they donâ€™t realize and understand the contributions of blacks.  She states that there is â€œnothing unique in white history,â€ and the culture of America comes from the blacks.  She believes that blacks must reclaim who they are.  She believes that people who see themselves as educated really are not, and must draw on other medium, such as books, to become better educated.  Literature and reading is extremely important, and she talks about how she read to her unborn child while pregnant.  \r\n	Elzy finishes by asking her where she thinks her writing is going.  She is unsure, but sheâ€™s playing with the idea of trying to write a novel.  She is interested in exploring human beings, so sheâ€™ll write to accomplish this in any way she can.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-67','119','59','The episode opens with statements from President Jimmy Carter announcing the strike settlement.  Carter also recognizes the difficulty of the job of a miner.  Next is a preview of a family, one who says that the miners have no choice but to stay out of the mines.\r\n	Host Ron Scott begins by announcing that negotiations between the United Mine Workers and representatives has been successful and a settlement has been reached.  Scott goes on to discuss some of the major details of the agreement, and then interviews Burdette Crowe, a miner, to get more info on the agreement.  Crowe however seems unfamiliar with the proposal, and does not feel comfortable commenting on specific proposals.  Scott then asks Crowe about the lack of Pension Funds in the provisional agreement, and Crowe voices his concerns and claims he will fight for pension funds in the future.  Scott also inquires about the Taft-Hartley act, which Crowe claims was not able to get miners to return to the coal mines.  Scott then thanks Crowe for joining the program.\r\nScott then turns to affiliate WWVU-TV for an interview with Len Gross, a representative of the coal industry.  Gross states that during the strike, 13 million tons of coal has been lost during the strike.  The program then shifts to Scottâ€™s interview with Charlestonâ€™s Mayor John Hutchinson.  Hutchinson downplays the negative effect of the strike of the economy of Charleston due to the diversified nature of the economy.  Hutchinson also comments on the waning influence of the United Mine Workers and the need for stability between the miners and the operators.  \r\n	Next, Scott interviews young coal miners Wayne Busby and Alec Meiklejohn.  Busby explains possible reasons behind the length of the strike, and reiterates his beliefs that the union will be able to hold out longer.  Meiklejohn comments on the lack of employment opportunities in the surrounding areas.  Busbyâ€™s wife, Kathy voices her concerns over the dangerous working environment of the mines.  She also states that she wouldnâ€™t want her son to work in the mine.  Another miner, Mike Meares, hopes that someday the mines will be run by the miners themselves, and would be able to make judgments and decisions of their own.  Meiklejohn goes on to thank the support of the Auto Workers in Detroit, and draws the connection between the plights of both unions.  \r\n	The episode then shifts to an interview with a retired miner, John Huddleston.  Scott and Huddleston discuss the lack of minerâ€™s pensions.  Huddleston also comments on the lack of unions when he began his mining career.  Huddlestonâ€™s wife Helen tells about her worries as a coal minerâ€™s wife, especially during strikes and labor disputes.  John says that he probably would still work in the mines if he could do it all over again, since he did not have the education required to obtain a better job.  \r\n	Scott then shares some statistics about the nation mortality rate in the mines.  He then joins Cecil Roberts, Pres. UMWA Dist. 17 in the mine, who discusses the contract negotiations in Washington and the dangers of working in the coal mines.  \r\n	The episode returns to the interview between Scott and Huddleston, and Huddleston reflects on his brotherâ€™s death in the mine.\r\n	Scott then closes out the episodes restating the dangers of the coal industry, and asks the viewer, â€œwhich side are you on?â€\r\n');
