insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-6C','119','59','The interviewer starts off by asking whether or not Jazz has ever been played before.  Sun Ra claims that everything came out of Egypt, including Jazz.  True Jazz is creativity, a gift from the â€œcreatorâ€.  Jazz has been diluted due to the integration of African culture into the American mainstream.  Without a cultural structure, the music is lost.  Sun-Ra voices his concerts about the selfish, materialistic nature of the black music industry.  Due to this search for wealth, black musicians have become detached from black race and culture, and therefore have eroded the ethnic structures.  \r\nCiting a book titled â€œFrom Man to Supermanâ€ by J.E. Rodgers, he claims that the black raceâ€™s lack of a philosophy compared to white cultureâ€™s embrace of Greek philosophical teachings is one of the problems today.  \r\nRa then discusses his trip to Egypt, and reflects on the acceptance of his name and beliefs in Egypt and Egyptian embassies and how it contrasts with treatment he receives in the United States.  All of the â€œanswersâ€ can be found in Egypt, and Ra claims visits from heads of states as a reflection of this.  \r\nRay asks about a natural law controlling the whole universe, and Ra explains the perspective of the â€œspace peopleâ€ concerning laws.  Human law, despite what society may believe, is no the law of the cosmos, and has no provisions for dealing with supernatural beings.  He claims the hostile nature of human law is why extraterrestrial beings are hesitant to visit Earth.  However, he goes on to discuss the â€œAngel Race,â€ a group of people from Nigeria, whom he learned about through a newsreel, and went to visit.  Ra claims to be a member of this â€œAngel Raceâ€ due to his lack of error and his obsession with precision and disciple.  \r\nRay steers the discussion towards Raâ€™s musical performances, and Ra claims to have learned about music directly from the â€œCreator.â€  He discusses a superior form of music, not of the body or the mind, but of the spirit.  This music can be used as a force of change throughout the world.  Ra claims that â€œtruthâ€ was lost with the crucifixion of Jesus Christ and all that is left is the â€œmyth.â€  \r\nRa discusses the problem of black education, and suggests that black people must be taught differently then white children, in the ancient Egyptian style with Hieroglyphics, myths and statues.  Ra explains that the color black is inherently evil, and goes on to embrace his evil nature, and suggests that separation from white culture would not be a bad thing.  \r\nRay again steers the conversation back towards music, asking him about his musical influences.  Fletcher Henderson is discussed as a main influence, mainly due to his discipline and the ability for his group to play as one.  Ray inquires about Raâ€™s groundbreaking use of electronic instruments, and Ra considers this a reflection of his ability to observe future technology, specifically the space age.  Ray then inquires as to where Ra sees music and the world in general ending up in the future.  Ra states that God is not on the side of the blacks, only the whites.  Black people should expect a new, different kind of savior.      \r\nRay asks Ra if musicians are free, and he reiterates that he is not concerned with freedom, and claims freedom is analogous to death.  He states that his concern is discipline, especially in regard to his musical compositions.  \r\nThe show closes with a Sun-Ra performance as the credits roll\r\n');
