insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-6E','119','59','The episode begins with a montage of Cockerelâ€™s moments on Detroit Black Journal.  Gallant gives a short introduction, and then takes a look at his past via comments from contemporaries, such as Jim Ingram, Erma Henderson and Carl Edwards.  Gallant then introduces the guests, and asks Ravitz how the community will recover following Cockerelâ€™s death.  Gallant also discusses the uniqueness of the Marxist leanings of both Ravitz and Cockerel.  \r\n	Gallant then asks Archer his perspective on the possibility of Cockerel being a candidate for mayor.  Archer suggests that Cockerel may have been considering a run for mayor, however still held the mayor in high regard, and Jack Russell shares this opinion. Russell continues, stressing Cockerelâ€™s wisdom and forward thinking.\r\n	Gallant and Hamlin then discuss Cockerelâ€™s relationship with the auto industry.  Hamlin explains that Cockerels recognized ways to have an impact during a struggle, and could identify with the plight of the black autoworkers.  Gallant brings up criticisms of Cockerel, particularly that he â€œsold outâ€ as his career progressed.  However, Hamlin refutes this statement as irrational.    \r\n	Archer and Gallant discuss the assertion that Cockerel, and perhaps all black men are â€œcasualties of the system.â€  Archer considers this an accurate assessment, and suggests that there are two few black social leaders who are being stretched thin.  Russell also discusses the demands placed on Cockerel, despite his attempts to relax and be a healthy human being.  \r\n	Archer comments on Cockerelâ€™s ability to downplay race, and tackle general human problems, and promote ideas of brotherhood.  \r\n	Gallant discusses the difficult legal cases taken by both Cockerel and Ravitz.  Ravitz then discusses Ravitzâ€™s ability to speak to people from all walks of life gave him the ability to tackle cases dealing with political and social experiments.  \r\n	Hamlin interjects to comment again on the importance of struggle in Cockerelâ€™s life.  Hamlin then reflects on the struggles that he and Cockerel faced during the race struggles of the 1960â€™s.  \r\n	Gallant then opens the phone lines, and the first caller asks how the remaining black leaders in Detroit can fill Cockerelâ€™s leadership role.  Archer then comments on Cockerelâ€™s legacy and academic excellence.  Archer also lauds his decision to become a public servant rather than cashing in on his abilities.  Hamlin then discusses the role of black youth in light of Cockerelâ€™s death.\r\n	Gallant then asks Russell what he will miss most about Cockerel, and he suggests that some of the extraordinary advances that will be made in the 90â€™s can be attributed to Cockerel, and that he will always be remembered through these accomplishments.  \r\n	The episode closes with comments from Cockerelâ€™s son.\r\n');
