insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-70','119','59','Darryl Wood is joined by Motown Records founder Berry Gordy, and they start out talking about Gordy\'s autobiography \"To Be Loved,\" with Wood asking why it took so long for him to share anything about Motown in intimate detail.  Gordy says that he wants to share his experience with young people who share his life of struggle, and show them how he managed to build such a company and show them that it is possible.  He wants people to understand clearly how a company such as Motown was developed, mainly through competition, and he doesn\'t want inner-city young people to give up their dream, so he wants them to understand the work that was put into building up the organization.  Gordy also wrote the book to discuss the history and the legacy of Motown, and wants to make sure that people understand that the book was written for a variety of reasons.\r\n	Wood then addresses how it didn\'t always look to Gordy like he would \"make it,\" and how he faced adversity and doubt at a young age when he was starting out.  Gordy was a songwriter and a dreamer, so he was often looked at as though he wasn\'t doing much with his life.  Starting out, Gordy\'s family gave him a loan to cut a record and get the organization going. They treated it as a professional loan, and Gordy signed a contract and promised to pay it back.  This led to Gordy having to pay good attention to the financial aspects of the label, which contributed to his strong work ethic and sense of responsibility.  His sister was in charge of watching his money as it grew, and then Motown developed into a family affair, because they had such a strong involvement in it.  \r\n	Wood then talks about how Gordy addresses extremely personal issues in his book and opens up old wounds for the world to see, and he asks Gordy why he chose to do that.  Gordy responds by saying that he has to take full responsibility for his life, and that many of his personal experiences are shared by other citizens and people who are reading the book.  He wants to make clear that he is proud that he was a normal person who was forced to overcome his own problems.  He believes that, on a basic level, everyone is the same and wants the same things, and everyone should share the ideas that they come up with.  He believes that people do not fulfill their potential because they are afraid to speak their mind and just want to be safe.  \r\n	Wood talks about the chronological nature of the book, following from the start of the Gordy clan all the way up through to Barry\'s life at present.  One of the points in this chronology is when Gordy was forced to work for his father, even though he hated it, because his father wanted him to learn the principles of a good day\'s work.  Gordy\'s relationship with his father also taught him that finding god doesn\'t necessarily come from going to church, but rather from one\'s actions.  This gave Gordy the belief that one can never be truly happy unless they are proud of themselves.  He also believes that communication and spreading of one\'s learning is extremely important.  \r\n');
