y of his personal experiences are shared by other citizens and people who are reading the book.  He wants to make clear that he is proud that he was a normal person who was forced to overcome his own problems.  He believes that, on a basic level, everyone is the same and wants the same things, and everyone should share the ideas that they come up with.  He believes that people do not fulfill their potential because they are afraid to speak their mind and just want to be safe.  \r\n	Wood talks about the chronological nature of the book, following from the start of the Gordy clan all the way up through to Barry\'s life at present.  One of the points in this chronology is when Gordy was forced to work for his father, even though he hated it, because his father wanted him to learn the principles of a good day\'s work.  Gordy\'s relationship with his father also taught him that finding god doesn\'t necessarily come from going to church, but rather from one\'s actions.  This gave Gordy the belief that one can never be truly happy unless they are proud of themselves.  He also believes that communication and spreading of one\'s learning is extremely important.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-73','119','59','This is the anniversary of the birth of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., and host Ed Gordon is joined by former civil rights activist and Georgia State congressman Julian Bond.  Bond is going to be on the upcoming PBS series â€œEyes on the Prize,â€ and Gordon starts by asking Bond what the series is about.  Bond says that itâ€™s about the American civil rights years and a look at the civil rights movement itself.  He thinks that it shows that there was a time in history when ordinary people created a movement that, in the space of 10 years, completely changed the face of the American South.  Bond and Gordon mention that many present-day young people donâ€™t know much about the history of the movement, and that even those who participated in it don\'t always know what happened outside their own area. This show aims to give people a clearer picture of the 10-year period they are focusing on.  \r\n	Some of the footage from Eyes on the Prize is then shown, focusing on the struggle for voting rights, looking at some of one of Martin Luther Kingâ€™s speeches, and examining the Selma, Alabama protests, civil unrest, and night march.  Gordon, following this clip, asks whether modern-day black Americans are too complacent, and Bond says that this isnâ€™t necessarily it, but rather that people are just uneducated.  Indeed, these events did not happen that long ago, but many are forgetting or simply unaware that they happened.  Bond also talks about how the show not only examines the 10 years and the changes that occurred, but also highlights the everyday people and â€œsmall figuresâ€ who made a difference in that struggle.  \r\n	Another clip from Eyes on the Prize is shown, in which Governor Wallace of Alabama and President Lyndon B. Johnsonâ€™s react to the Selma, Alabama demonstrations and Johnsonâ€™s decision to introduce a comprehensive voting rights bill.  \r\n	They then move on to look at modern-day civil rights.  Bond says that they are better off because the legal enforcement of segregation in the South is gone, but he believes that, in some ways, they are worse off, because the divide between blacks and whites sometimes seems even clearer.  Bond believes that, in order to change these things, blacks must utilize their political power to the greatest extent possible.  \r\n	Gordon then asks Bond what it was like to run for a congressional seat in Georgia, especially because of the race issue that was raised with his opponent, John Lewis, and how the election seemed to split the community into blacks and whites.  Bond says itâ€™s an example of a victory that the civil rights movement won for them, because a black man was able to run against another black man.  He says it was upset to see that Lewis, who had claimed to be his friend for many years, ended up not being so.  Gordon also asks whether itâ€™s viable to assume whether blacks could become President or Vice President in the near future, and Bond, who they had attempted to get to run for Vice President in 1968, believes that yes, one must assume this, or else it wouldnâ€™t be possible. \r\n	Gordon also asks why Bond chose to stay so long in state government rather than moving onto a larger stage.  Bond says that he had to wait for the right opportunity, which came along in 1986, and even though he lost, he is happy he ran.  He hopes to keep moving on and trying new things, and this pushes him forward.  They also go back to talking about how civil rights relates to modern-day life, and Bond discusses how it matters greatly who gets elected to be President in the next couple years.  \r\n	Gordon finishes by asking whether there is a need for a summit for black leaders to sit down and find a path to go down in the future.  Bond believes that this isnâ€™t necessary, and that they already know what they need to do.  They must strengthen their economic endeavors, educational institutions, and increase their political strength and influence.    \r\n	The show finishes with more footage from Eyes on the Prize and Martin Luther King, Jr.\r\n');
