insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-76','119','59','In recent times, there have been a resurgence of racist acts occurring, including movements from the Klu Klux Klan.  Now, there are meetings and coalitions forming to put an end to the violence.  The first person they talk to is Mrs. B. Tracy, director of the Eastside City Coalition, who a lecture called â€œUnity in the black community.â€  She says that their major purpose for the lecture and event was to do something for the black community, which is constantly being denied rights that they feel entitle to.  She hopes to make this affordable and available to black people, as well as to have a summer program for youth.  She states the importance of focusing on business and things that will empower and benefit the black community through the development of black entrepreneurship skills.  \r\n	Clements then asks how she thinks they will deal with black unity, the theme of the lecture.  Tracy says that, by bringing things to the community that blacks are drawn to attend, they are effectively dealing with the issue of black unity.  She also talks about how they are not funded and are trying to be self-sufficient before using grants.  They function off of individual donations and fund-raisers.  \r\n	Detroit Black Journal then speaks with Dick Gregory, the keynote speaker for the event, about his viewpoints on the recent racist, violent, and genocidal actions against blacks.  Clements quotes Gregory as saying that the Atlanta child murders had to do with fiendish experiments, and asks him to explain.  Gregory says that the facts that no one got away from the murder and that it occurred during the daytime are extremely suspicious, as well as the fact that the crime baffled all the police intelligence of the country.  This leads him to believe that groups such as the Klu Klux Klan could not have been involved, but in looking at patterns in the governmentâ€™s involvement in different things, itâ€™s indicative that they could have some involvement in the Atlanta murders.  Clements then addresses the fact that he was informed that the Atlanta governmental task force that was named to investigate this crime didnâ€™t go out and do field work, but rather stayed indoors and worked out of their offices, and Gregory expands upon this fact, saying that he talked to the mothers of the victims.  He also talks about the mutilations performed on the female and male victims, and says that, in looking at trends in these mutilations, he is led to believe that fiendish medical experiments are at the root of the murders.  He also talks about the actions of the police, such as those who buried a severely decomposed boy under a tree and told his mother to simply have a memorial service for him.  He also talks about the possibility that the government may have been involved in some way in these murders.  \r\n	Clements then talks about the fact that there is other terrorist activity going on around the country, and asks Gregory if he feels that the Atlanta tragedy was an isolated even or if it was somehow related to these other atrocities that are occurring.  Gregory feels that it is an isolated event, because itâ€™s happening in one community and happening to one group of black people.  Gregory then talks about black organizations, and discusses his belief that it is not a matter of a lack of black voice, but rather a lack of blacks putting their priorities on the right things.  \r\n	They then talk about the issue of the United Statesâ€™ involvement in South Africa.  Gregory says that it is a matter of profit for the countries that are involved, and he says that once they break this economic involvement, then they will break South Africa.  \r\n	Clements then talks about his observations of the Atlanta child murders, and talks about evidence from police, investigators, and coronersâ€™ actions that there is a conspiracy occurring.  Clements says that blacks must use the evidence they are presented with to make their own conclusions and protect themselves in any way they see fit and for any possible scenarios.  He says that in the upcoming years, they will see a continuing effort to unify the black community and form strong coalitions.  \r\n	The program finishes with a montage of photographs of the murdered children and funeral services, as well as video footage of other parents with their children.  \r\n');
