insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-7A','119','59','Darryl Wood is joined by civil rights activist and national talk show host, the Reverend Jesse Jackson.  Wood begins by addressing the issue of the current political situation, in particular recent speculation that Colin Powell might run for president.  Wood asks whether Jackson thinks that America is ready to elect a black president. Jackson is unsure: he highlights Powellâ€™s good qualities as a possible candidate, but notes that the question is of priorities and values, such as the problem of the urban crisis, which no one is addressing.  Jackson believes that significant issues must be addressed in the upcoming presidential race.  \r\n	Wood goes on to ask whether the lack of black mobilization to vote is influenced by the fact that certain issues such as the urban crisis are not generally addressed by politicians.  Jackson agrees, but he believes that mobilization without connections to public policy is not enough.  Jackson addresses his reputation for surrounding himself with a wide range of activists, such as Louis Farrakhan, and he says that one must be judged not by association, but by what they do themselves.  He hopes, through his coalitions, to push for an overall goal of fairness and equality.  \r\n	If alliances are formed, Wood asks, can they accomplish all that they hope to if they are extremely diverse, or should they be more focused on \'black issues\' and associate mainly with blacks.  Jackson says that racial justice and gender equality are black issues, but there are other issues, such as welfare, that were beneficial to whites first.  He says that none of these issues will be resolved until blacks and whites can come together, eliminate race designations to social problems, and fight as an alliance.  \r\n	They then go on to talk about who it is that champions the cause for unemployed blacks, and Jackson says that the leadership has to come from blacks, who must â€œurge for changeâ€ and â€œstrike the first blow.â€  However, a broader base of people must take action in order to implement true change, especially to the problem of racist jail policies.  Jackson says that it is necessary that good economic policies and commercial success can come to urban areas.  \r\n	Wood then asks what blacks must to in order to mobilize their communities.  Jackson believes that a specific plan of action must be developed, in which each person understands the goals for which they are working and what steps they must take to get there.  They move into talking about Jacksonâ€™s possible next run for the presidency, and Woods asks when he will announce his bid to run, which Jackson says that he is unsure of.   He is reluctant to run again and would rather that President Clinton honor his campaign priorities. If he does not address the urban problems, however, Jackson says that he will be forced to challenge Clinton.  However, he would rather support the President in his campaign, as long as he follows through on his campaign promises.  Jackson describes his possible run for president as an â€œopen question.â€  \r\n	Jackson finishes his interview, and then the program moves on to a discussion of the Jeffries Housing Project, part of the program Art in the Urban, run by Project REACH.  Deborah Franklin, one of the founders of this program, is interviewed. She says that the program developed out of a perception that the needs of black children were not being met.  She hopes to use art and cultural demonstrations and activities to bring self-esteem to the children of Jeffries residents.  She believes that giving these children self-esteem will enable them to reject antisocial behavior and pursue a better future.  Rene Lowe, another worker for REACH, is interviewed, as are residents such as Lois Williams.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-7B','119','59','This show takes an in-depth look at  Louis Farrakhan and his policies.  It starts out, however, by providing some history with footage from a press conference in Detroit with Farrakhan, about how Islam has great roots in Detroit and about Muslim leader Elijah Mohammed.  He talks about the growth and progression of Islam and about how blacks suffer from self-hatred and inferiority, which results in  economic, political, and civic struggle.  He discusses the \'Stop the Killing\' program that is now extending into the Detroit area.  \r\n	Rasul Muhammad, the Nation of Islamâ€™s local leader, joins Gallant to discuss these issues and Louis Farrakhan himself.  Gallant starts by asking what the organization is doing in regards to the \'Stop the Killing\' program.  Muhammad talks about how Farrakhanâ€™s message spurs blacks to take action.  They are planning for Halfway Homes, where people can stay, get back on track, and work towards independence, which he believes is essential for blacks to progress.  They want to encourage people to keep their living areas and communities in good condition, and have been working to go in and clean up housing projects.  \r\n	Another clip is shown from the press conference, where Farrakhan defends himself in regards to statements that he had made, some of which were seen as anti-Semitic.  He says that his words were distorted because whites  fear that Farrakhan could mobilize blacks and get them to take action in the community.  He also believes that he has been labeled as hateful because blacks have been taught to love all people except themselves.  He says that his critical analyses of Jews are simply critical, not anti-Semitic, and he hates that people refer to him as the â€œnew black Hitler.â€  \r\n	Gallant asks whether Muhammadâ€™s organization still gets a lot of repercussions from Farrakhanâ€™s remarks.  Muhammad says that the repercussions come mainly from their own people who are ignorant of the facts.  The Nation of Islamâ€™s position is that because their people suffer extremely, especially in relation to recognition of oneâ€™s identity, separation is the answer until education takes place, and then the country can begin to interact with others.  They want a separate state geographically, as long as the white government continues as it is.  \r\n	A third clip is shown from the news conference, addressing the issue of whether American blacks are entitled to reparations, comparing their plight to that of the Japanese-Americans who did receive reparations.  Farrakhan demands that they receive some form of reparations from the government, and is frustrated with the current allocation of government money.  \r\n	Calls are then taken from viewers.  The first caller wants to hear Muhammadâ€™s views on the underlying problems in Iraq.  He believes that they have no need to be in Iraq fighting for causes and conditions that have nothing to do with their own needs and values.  He thinks that they sometimes get too involved in issues abroad and forget about their own issues, and believe that the Iraqis should be left to handle their own problems.  The next caller wants to know what Muhammad has to say about the seemingly anti-Semitic and anti-Christian views of the Islamic community.  He believes that if all people, no matter what their religion, practice the principles of god, then it is â€œonly the title that keeps them away from one another.â€  He is firm that there â€œis no anti-anything, as long as you are pro-god.â€  The third caller wants to know why Muhammad isnâ€™t very visible and active in the community.  He talks about how they have a few hundred active, working supporters in the community, and he says that he himself has been doing a lot of travel, so he hasnâ€™t been that visible.  But he hopes that they will soon be very visible in the community in the times to come.  The fourth caller wants to know how black people can understand the psychological damages from slavery that still affect them today.  Muhammad says that all community leaders should come together, and blacks must have self-sufficiency.  \r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-7C','119','59','Gordon is joined by Earl Graves, editor and publisher of Black Enterprise Magazine, and Dave Bing, president of Bing Steel.  Gordonâ€™s first question is for Graves, and he asks whether he thinks blacks have learned how to â€œleverage economic clout.â€  Graves says that he thinks so, and says that black organizations have taken it into their own hands to bring in more finances and grow.  Gordon also asks what more can be done to increase the political and social clout of the black community.  Graves says economic clout can only come from them making good decisions about what to do with their money.  This could include doing business with things such as hotel chains.  \r\n	Gordon asks how Bing saw his clout grow as a black businessman in the economic community, and how the black community could see theirs grow as relates to that kind of power.  Bing says that location and support from local corporations and the whole political process has fostered his companyâ€™s growth.  Gordon comments on Bingâ€™s observation that itâ€™s important that blacks find a niche, but also asks whether itâ€™s important that blacks expand themselves in the business world as well.  Bing says that this is indeed very important, and comments that, in going into the steel industry in Detroit, he set himself up to accrue a good deal of money that would then allow him to expand his enterprise into other areas.  \r\n	Graves says that itâ€™s important that blacks recognize that they are on the â€œthresholdâ€ of where business can go, and are â€œknocking at the door of opportunityâ€ in regards to expanding out and diversifying.  They need to look at the business opportunities that are available, as well as looking at the opportunities to set up their own brokerage and finance firms, because they need to have their own kind of economic clout.  \r\n	Gordon comments that government plays a large role in the business world, and asks what effect governmental restrictions, mandates, and actions are going to have on black business.  Graves says that opportunity cutbacks didnâ€™t set the black business community back too much, but they just realized that they were going to have to work harder to achieve their economic goals.  Bing has never done business with the federal government, and instead went directly to the private sector and the city of Detroit as he was starting out.  \r\n	Gordon then goes to the phone lines.  The first caller says that he was pleased to hear them mention the need for brokerage firms, but also says that, although such firms are needed, there is a low percentage of blacks who are investing in the stock market.  Graves says that his magazine will be having networking sessions across the country focusing on economic empowerment through personal financial planning, and says that the magazine has been working to get blacks to invest in the stock market.  The second caller wants to know how they can diversify business endeavors.  Bing says that getting out of the traditional business set takes both studying and exposure.  \r\n	Gordon then asks Graves if he is pleased about where black enterprise is in present-day corporate America.  Graves isnâ€™t that satisfied, because he sees companies that are doing better, but there are others that arenâ€™t doing well as far as black employment is concerned.  He says that the present-day problem is that opportunities for black movement in the corporate world are just not available as they should be.  \r\n	Gordon returns to the phones, and the next caller wants to know how they can get the message across to black businesses that there is too much money diffused out of communities.  Graves says that the media hypes up the idea that blacks are not supporting blacks, and that in reality this is no longer the case.  Graves also says that modern-day blacks have the right to demand from businesses that they provide a service in a first-class manner, especially since black businesses do so.  The next caller wants to know the panelâ€™s view on affirmative action, as well as whether Bing thinks he would be where he is without having been known as a great basketball player first.  Bing says that he had name recognition, which got him in the door, but it was essential that he perform in the business world and for his customers, or else his business would have sank.  He adds that he believes in affirmative action.  The following caller wants to know ways to find suitable working capital for young black businesses.  Graves says that this is the tough question that faces all businessmen, and that one first has to build up a personal income and look to institutions such as local banks, and then to larger institutions such as the AKAs.   \r\n	Gordon asks whether blacks need to have a better understanding of business.  Graves says that there is a need for a basic educational background, so that they can understand business and the marketplace and be able to communicate.  Financial planning is also extremely important as one plans for expenses involved in oneâ€™s future.\r\n	The next caller asks Graves what advice he can give to the black community as they see more Arabic businessmen moving in to the community, removing money, and beautifying their own communities.  Graves says itâ€™s not a matter of race and ethnicity, but rather one should look at the situation as they are there because they didnâ€™t take advantage of opportunities when they were available.  \r\n	Gordon turns again to Bing, and asks whether he believes that blacks are ready for the economic world and big business.  Bing says that there is a wealth of talent in the black community, and there are many people who would like to see a black company grow and succeed.  The next caller, Carl Gregory, a top economist in the country who wrote for Gravesâ€™ magazine, asks Graves whether there are any efforts going on nationally to bring together the fraternities, sororities, churches, and other black organizations to create a larger black venture capital company.  Graves says that they are having discussions with the different Greek organizations about how they leverage the power they have to use that clout to create business opportunities and generate capital.  \r\n	Gordon asks Graves to name one thing the black community could do to achieve economic parity, and Graves says that leveraging the economic and political clout they have requires exercising oneâ€™s voting power and recognizing that one holds power with the voting dollar.  Bing says that Detroit businessmen have been meeting to try and come up with ways to raise the economic clout in Detroit, and one group he is in, NABAS, is working together to try and understand the opportunities that are available.  \r\n	The show closes with Billy Paulâ€™s song â€œLet the Dollar Circulate.â€\r\n');
