insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-7F','119','59','On this show, Wood interviews Arthur Mitchell, a dancer who was a member of the New York City Ballet and is now a member and founder of the Dance Theatre of Harlem.  Mitchell starts out by discussing how he draws on the teachings that he has had from all sorts of people, both his leaders in the ballet world and civil rights activists such as Martin Luther King, and come to realize that what one truly needs to succeed are discipline and focus.\r\n	They then move on to talk about his life, starting with his young years struggling in Harlem, New York as the oldest of five kids.  He had to take over after his father left as the head of the family, and this forged a strong sense of responsibility and the desire to know the reasons for why things happen.  Wood then asks why Mitchell chose to pursue ballet instead of other much more popular sports.  Mitchell says his sister taught him to be a good social dancer, and then Mitchell tried out and made it into the High School of Performing Arts, and followed his dream from there.\r\n	Wood then approaches the issue that ballet would seem way to far out of reach for the disenfranchised black common man, and is curious as to how Mitchell approached this problem.  Mitchell talks about how he faced racism when he was continually turned down at auditions where he knew he was the best, and then tried to find something that he knew would give him the edge.  This, he decided, was classical technique, and he took up classical ballet at the age of 18.  Then, after three years at the School of American Ballet, Mitchell joined the company, and was inspired by Jackie Robinsonâ€™s breaking of barriers in baseball to hope to do the same in ballet.  \r\n	Wood then talks about how Mitchellâ€™s dance possesses the epitome of expressiveness, beauty, and technique.  Mitchell talks about how he believes dance is the first of the art forms because of its use of movement, which is the basis of all communication and behavior.  Wood moves on to talk about how when Mitchell was a principal dancer at the New York City ballet, and was the only black dancer with that kind of prestige at the time.  He asks him how he aspired to have that kind of prestige when no one else was doing it.  Mitchell talks about how oneâ€™s perspective changes, and one can only aspire for the â€œcommon denominator of excellence.â€  \r\n	Wood asks how Mitchell decided to, in 1968, leave his position as principal dancer and start the Dance Theatre of Harlem.  Mitchell describes his first motivation as being in 1966, when they had the First World Festival of the Negro and the Arts in Senegal.  He was asked by organizers in this event to start the first national Brazilian ballet company, and he also built an opera company.  Then, following Martin Luther Kingâ€™s death, he was motivated to take action, and he started in a basement teaching kids to dance.  This company grew extremely quickly, and in teaching kids from the streets and gang members ballet, he removed the stigma surrounding ballet and the fact that it wasnâ€™t â€œmanly.â€  Mitchell also found that, in making sure that his students were excelling scholastically as well, he was able to improve their performance in all aspects of their lives.  \r\n	Mitchell also describes how classical training is the highest level of technique possible, and how, even if one does not decide to pursue ballet, they will excel in any method of dance or athletics that they do pursue because of the training that theyâ€™ve had.  \r\n	Mitchell then goes on to talk about the residency program that he is working on for dance students in Detroit, and hopes that through this program he can enrich their lives with the arts, which he believes everyone should have in their lives.  He thinks that, by giving them the chance to participate in the arts, they can develop the skills that will help them succeed in other aspects of their lives.  Wood then asks why the arts are so financially undervalued in modern-day society.  Mitchell makes the point that we only think of the arts as pleasure and relaxation, so because of this viewpoint, it hasnâ€™t received the funding that it deserves.  He also makes the point that artistic expression can be made even more meaningful when one draws on the experiences they have had in other areas of their lives and applies them.  He dance can enhance oneâ€™s performance in things such as sports, by improving footwork and movement.  \r\n');
