insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-82','119','59','Gallant is joined by City Council President Erma Henderson, who did not put her name on the Detroit ballot for the first time in 17 years.  Henderson starts out by discussing the importance of changes in the yearâ€™s ballot, as well as the significance of the elections themselves.  Gallant brings up the subject of Hendersonâ€™s mayoral run, in which she received much less support than she had always gotten for her runs for City Council.  Henderson says that she could not reach a lot of the people that she was able to reach before, largely because of a lack of funds, and because the press dominated the election and influenced public perceptions of it.  Henderson stresses the importance of people taking more of an active role in elections in order to prevent such influence by the press.  \r\n	They then show a tape of some highlights from Erma Hendersonâ€™s career.  The final clip features Henderson and mayor Coleman Young, and Gallant asks about their relationship, them having been long-time friends but her having run against him in the primary election for mayor.  Henderson says that theyâ€™ve known each other a long time, and that they attracted the same kind of constituency even though they had different points of view, which made her success in the election rather improbable.  She ran against him only in order to make the people aware of policies and political conditions, as well as to address issues that she cared about.    \r\n	They then discuss what Hendersonâ€™s plans will be after the year ends and her term as City Council President is over.  She says she has been invited to teach, as well as other things, but she wants to make sure that, whatever she does, that she loves it.  She also talks about her mentors that she met in her lifetime, including W.E.B. DuBois and Paul Robeson.\r\n	The show then goes to the phone lines.  The first caller wants to know whether Henderson is pleased with Ms. Mahateyâ€™s win over Gill Hill, and whether, as blacks, they lose something, since a black no longer fills the presidency position.  Henderson says that who the city has as a person, rather than their race, makes the most difference for Detroit and its future.  The next caller wants to know whether the mayor will be more responsive to neighborhood issues in light of the heat of the recent election, and what the secret is of her high energy.  Henderson believes that the yearâ€™s election will have an impact on the mayor, and says that she works to keep herself healthy in order to stay high-energy (she also owns and operates a health food store).  The following caller brings up figures such as Colin Powell and David Deacon, and asks whether Henderson thinks having such â€œblack faces in high placesâ€ will help the community.  Henderson emphasizes how people change once entering politics, and that electing blacks can help the black community, but individuals also must work to close the gap between politicians and their constituency, no matter what their race is.  The fourth caller wants to know whether, in the next four or five years, whether she thinks Tom Barrel has the potential to be Mayor.  Henderson says thatâ€™s really up to Mr. Barrel, but she does believe that he had the weakness of not being in public office before his run.  \r\n	They talk about Hendersonâ€™s proposal for more police on the street, and she thinks that but updating the work of the police force, it could drastically improve the community.  They then go back to the phone lines, and the next caller wants to know what the probability is for more females in Detroit politics.  Henderson comments on how the number of women is down, and there is only one black woman.  She says that people donâ€™t tend to treat women as seriously as they do males in politics.  \r\n	The show closes with some clips featuring highlights from Hendersonâ€™s career.\r\n');
