insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-8F','119','59','Performance & â€œGrapevineâ€ Segment\r\nTo start off the show, Hal McKinney performs â€œCornerstone.â€  Then, the â€œGrapevineâ€ segment presents upcoming events, which include: Don Walden and his quintet will be performing, a social club gathering, the Cultural and Literary Club gathering and fashion show, an Art Istitute event, and fashions shown at the Veterans Memorial Building.  The â€œtogether sister of the weekâ€ is Rosalyn Russell, a medical secretary.  Former Supreme Lawrence Ballard is highlighted, as is another former Motown star Kim Westin.  To finish, Letâ€™s Face it, a book by Elsie Archer, is promoted.\r\nTop Story\r\n	Next, Part II of the The Olympic Revolt is shown, a program that focuses on the history and achievements of black athletes in competition, then is shown, highlighting the black boycott of the Olympic competitions.  Professor Harry Edwards, organizer of the boycott, insists that athletics can be used as a wedge to improve the second-class nature of blacks who dominate in track and field.  John Lewis, a winner of the 1928 Olympic relay team, gives CPTV his feelings about the boycott.  He says that he actually never had any racial troubles himself.  Lorenzo Wright, a former 400 m relay champion, gives his opinion, stating that itâ€™s quite a youthful movement, and Dr. William Watson, a former athlete who now works in athletics at Wayne State University, disapproves strongly of the boycott.  The show then highlights the performances of black athletes in Mexico City and their actions and the pressâ€™s response.  To finish the first half of the show, the Brothers of Soul perform.  \r\nNews\r\n	Then, current news stories from the black community are highlighted in â€œPeople and Places that Make up Our News.â€   Stories include: The Detroit Urban Leagueâ€™s release of information that  shows that some 20 public commissions have no black appointees, Congressman John Conyerâ€™s Jr.â€™s comments on black people sitting out the election,  the commission of a National Afro-American Police League, and a report on the African Conference on Black Writers.  They provide information about what was said by prominent people at the conference, including Stokely Carmichael.   He also gives a sports report, highlighting O.J. Simpsonâ€™s plays that kept Southern California undefeated after a win over Washington the previous week.  \r\nPerformance #2 & Special Guest\r\n	The next guest on the show, Wild Bill Davis, performs â€œQuiet Nights,â€ and then the nightâ€™s special guest, Martha Jean â€œThe Queen,â€ is brought on.  She works for the blue collar workers and laborers of the community, promoting their rights and â€œserving othersâ€ through her work and radio show.  She believes that money takes precedence in society over caring for fellow citizens and recognizing them.  She hopes, through her blue collar program, she and the groupâ€™s members can get people to use their minds and think.  She also has a talent in music, with a knack for picking number one songs, as she demonstrates in her disk jockey skills on her radio show.  She was also a recording artist.\r\nDramatic Performance\r\n	Following Martha Jeanâ€™s interview, the Inkster Community Choir performs, and then Kent Martin, director of the CPT Players, puts on a play featuring the character Jess B. Simple.  This finishes the show.  \r\n');
