insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-95','119','59','Darryl Wood interviews the jazz musician Wynton Marsalis about his achievements, awards, accolades, etc.  Marsalis first addresses the question of how he has been able to handle all of the public response and hype surrounding his career, stating that he tries not to focus too much on the press and the media.  He emphasizes that one of the biggest changes that results from fame is a personâ€™s relationship with their peers.  Wood follows this by asking the question of how one should act as they rise to the top of jazz musicianship and become a star.  Marsalis believes that publicity isnâ€™t necessarily based on achievement, so the way a person acts outside of their musicianship is often focused on much more than their playing itself.  Therefore, there is no one certain way that a young musician can be told to act.\r\n	Wood goes on to ask the question of what Marsalis thinks his music achieves, both musically and socially.  Marsalis states that the main goal of his and his fellow musiciansâ€™ music is to encompass and convey the American experience, bringing all eras of people and music together.  He also stresses that music that he writes develops even more if he can become familiar with the players who will perform it first.  He often tailors his compositions and must have the players work together because each is different.  Woodâ€™s most difficult question for Marsalis has to do with what message he believes his own music is conveying to the public in this time.  Marsalis states that he tries to get across a sense of what he has struggled through in his life and the obstacles he has had to overcome.  The two also discuss the importance of preserving jazz music in order to preserve its messages of humanity, history, and personal experience, which is more important than simply oneâ€™s race, and relate this to Marsalisâ€™ inspiration for his composition Blood on the Fields.  They finish by discussing the â€œjazz geniuses,â€ such as Louis Armstrong and Coltrane.  \r\n');
