insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-97','119','59','Song, dance, and clothing were used by African slaves to convey messages, and the song and dance of present-day African-Americans is very similar.  The dancing, storytelling, and music of the Inshangi family is used to show how such traditions of Africans can be conveyed to present-day African Americans.  Lessons taught in this performance include the importance of watching what you say.  Dancing and humor is used to convey important traditions and messages.  After the performance, Russell states the three things that prevail throughout: family, hospitality, and worship.\r\nThey also talk with Katherine Blackwell about present-day children, and she emphasizes the notion that children all over the world are the same and are affected in similar ways by storytelling.  Blackwell works with African-American schoolchildren to connect them to their African roots and get them to be more informed about their ancestry.  The episode finishes with Russell emphasizing the importance of the exchange between African-Americans and indigenous Africans, and that these exchanges will unify both groups.\r\n');
