insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-99','119','59','Gordon starts by asking Jackson whether he sees himself running for president in the 1988 campaign. Jackson says that it is premature to approach this idea now.  He does have concerns for his family; he has received threats that if he runs they will be hurt. He is also unsure whether or not he would get an adequate amount of money for the campaign.  He also needs a good deal of support from citizens, and must be able to change the direction of politics.  Gordon also wants to know whether blacks are a viable alternative as candidates for high office, especially following the events and politics of 1986.  Jackson talks about the breakthroughs of â€™86, when four new black Representatives were elected, and when several whites were beaten out for certain government positions.  He believes that these elections proved that people with civil rights priorities could win in the deep South.   He also says that more people have gotten involved in the voting process, making it even more possible for blacks to be elected.\r\n	Gordon says that some Democrats feel that Jackson is too liberal, but also that he is trying to become more palatable to whites, and he asks Jackson for his response to these things.  Jackson first questions what group of people it is that sees him as too liberal, and demonstrates through his policies and actions that he has been pushing for moving in directions that are the best for the country.  He also looks at the makeup of the nation, where there is a strong imbalance in power and wealth.  Jackson then moves on to address the question of whether he is trying to become more palatable to whites, and he says that although many white politicians are working to implement policies that he has supported for many years, this does not necessarily mean that he is selling himself to them.  Rather, the nation is â€œcoming back toward reality.â€  \r\n	Gordon then asks whether Democrats are taking blacks for granted and also whether Jackson is disappointed in the number of blacks that are voting.  Jackson says that Democrats are taking blacks for granted, but they will be less able to in the future when the black vote becomes stronger.  He also addresses, however, that there is an â€œanesthetized conscienceâ€ in the country that promotes racist viewpoints and actions, and this needs to be addressed.  Jackson then says that, although many fewer blacks vote than who actually can, the fact that the number of blacks voting keeps increasing and that progress is being made, he cannot be disappointed in it.  \r\n	Gordon addresses the question of whether black America needs to stop helping the government as much and focus on their own problems.  Jackson believes that there are two sides to the issue, whereas many of black Americaâ€™s problems can be fixed by changing behaviors, such as refraining from using drugs and alcohol.  However, blacks also need things that only the government can provide, such as better housing and education.  Thus, they must be able to have influence in the political arena and be able to influence governmental policies.  \r\n	They then move on to talk about Jacksonâ€™s trip to Africa and how it influenced him.  Jackson believes that African Americans can never be a complete people until they connect with their motherland and go back to their roots, and he describes how he was touched by this history.  However, seeing the horrible conditions in some parts of the continent also hurt Jackson and moved him to look at the African countriesâ€™ struggle and comparing their strife to Americaâ€™s insensitivities to their plight.  Also, although some American companies have divested from South Africa, Jackson is not impressed with these actions, because they have still not shifted power into the hands of blacks, but rather put more power into the hands of fewer whites.  He also believes that companies in the Reagan era feel no pressure for affirmative action and to hire blacks, and therefore there has been a drop off in the hiring of black workers.  \r\n	In several of the books about Jacksonâ€™s run for president, they tend to describe him as a â€œcalculating opportunist,â€ and Gordon questions what Jackson feels about that.  Jackson says thatâ€™s simply their opinion, and he does not get brought down by it.  Jackson also talks about the present-day black agenda, which is to have blacks exercise their voting rights, resist Reaganâ€™s â€œhostile acts,â€ and run for political office.  He is staunchly against the Reagan administration, and knows that blacks are working hard to resist many of his policies.  \r\n	The show closes with Aretha Franklin singing, â€œLook to the Rainbow.â€\r\n');
insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-9A','119','59','Hunter-Gault first questions Tutu about the effect that demonstrations, such as the one happening that day at Shell Oil Company, have on South Africa.  He responds by saying that they have had a tremendous effect, mainly by boosting the morale of those who are fighting against apartheid.  He talks about the results of the bans placed on certain companies and people, mainly that it has opened up realities of the world, such as those of police brutality, to the fighters in the anti-apartheid movement, particularly younger people.  \r\n	Tutu then expresses his great appreciation and love for what America has been doing in the struggle against apartheid, both through its citizens and the President.  He highlights the importance of the sanctions that have been implemented, but Hunter-Gault brings up the fact that he has pushed for even more of these to be instated in a short amount of time.  He stresses that intervention of the international community through sanctions and in other ways is needed to prevent the crises that he sees arising in the future in South Africa if actions arenâ€™t taken.  He highlights the distrust had for government officials, such as Luttweiler, in regards to their so-called â€œempty promises,â€ and discusses how their failure to follow through on such promises has widened the gap between them and those fighting against apartheid.  \r\n	Hunter-Gault asks Tutu what it would take to have the anti-apartheid movement sit down with the government and negotiate.  He states that this could only happen if they made clear the intention to dismantle apartheid, removed political prisoners from detention, lifted the state of emergency and withdrew troops, and were determined to be involved in true negotiations.  The significant issue of violence is then addressed, and the question is raised as to how widespread the belief that it is the only alternative is.  It is clear that this belief is increasing, particularly amongst the younger generation\r\n	Questions are then taken from the audience and over the phone, involving issues such as why America should get involved in the problems of South Africa when it has enough race-relation problems of its own to figure out, how Americans can make a difference, the role that companies who claim to not support apartheid play in supporting society and community, the issue of divestment and sanctions, the political role South Africa will take following the dissolution of apartheid, and the role of Nelson Mandela in the anti-apartheid struggle.  In regards to this question, Tutu stresses the importance and faith that people place in Mandela, even though he is in jail, and how he is indispensable to the solution to the problems in South Africa.  \r\n	Tutu also stresses how he is not alone in his viewpoints and leadership, and how there are many others who are just as significant in the struggle, if not more, than he is.  Another issue is that of the different tribes in South Africa, and how they would be organized if apartheid was disbanded.  He stresses that people are mostly quite de-tribalized, and that it is the government of South Africa that has tried to enforce the tribal lines to promote and exacerbate the differences amongst people.  He also addresses the question of whether the courts and judicial system are merely â€œtools of the regime,â€ or whether they can be used to help in the anti-apartheid movement.  The problem in South Africa is that the Constitution is against blacks, because they are guaranteed very few rights under it, and so the judicial system must uphold this Constitution, making it difficult for them to be much of a help in the anti-apartheid struggle.  Comparisons are also drawn between the civil rights struggle in American and the anti-apartheid struggle in South Africa.  \r\n	Tutuâ€™s role as both a religious and a political leader is also addressed, and he discusses how preaching godâ€™s message and political messages to whites as well as black has been received.  He has a positive reaction, saying that he thinks whites are coming around to ideas of love and appreciation for their countrymen, both white and black.  He then talks about the role of South Africaâ€™s youth in the struggle and their bravery, often willing, with both good and bad results, to take more radical actions than older members of the struggle.  He subsequently discusses his support for what the ANC stands for, but his dislike for the means they use to get what they want, such as guerrilla tactics.  \r\n	Tutu finally discusses the issue of the white Africana, their resistance, and the role that they are playing in modern-day South Africa.  Also, he talks about the role that the Reagan Administration must play in regards to this issue and in helping South Africa through such things as divestment.  \r\n	Hunter-Gault finishes by questioning Tutu about what he feels is the most realistic scenario for South Africa.  He is quite optimistic, saying that if the correct policies are implemented, they could be free tomorrow.  \r\n');
