insert into `p18Data` (`id`, `cid`, `schemeid`, `value`) values('12-3B-9C','119','59','The show opens with video highlights from Nelson Mandelaâ€™s stop in Detroit, Michigan, which include clips from Mandelaâ€™s speeches, travels, and the response of Detroitâ€™s auto workers to his visit.  The highlights also include a large concert attended by Mandela and his wife, at which choral groups and Stevie Wonder performed, and where he gave a rousing speech to many of Detroitâ€™s citizens.  \r\n	Gallant is then joined by two members of the steering committee for the Detroit stop-off on Mandelaâ€™s U.S. tour, Margaret Baylor and Paul Hubbard.  They are there to discuss the financial success of the event.  Gallant starts with Baylor, who talks about how Detroit made more than one million dollars from Mandelaâ€™s visit.  Hubbard says that this money will go to the ANC, as well as Trans-Africaâ€™s 510C3 organization, which will use it to help South Africaâ€™s homeless.  There are also other possibilities for where the rest of the money could go.  Baylor is the the president of the local chapter of Trans-Africa, which served as the local governing body for the Mandela Freedom Tour.  She says the money might also be used to repatriate South African exiles, and talks about how Trans-Africa has been working to collect books to be sent to South Africa, as well as working with the auto industry to have money from car sales to go to the Mandela Freedom Tour.  \r\n	Hubbard talks about the feedback he has gotten about the Mendelaâ€™s visit, all extremely positive.  His visit was seen as a â€œhealing factionâ€ between all facets of the city, during which Detroitâ€™s spirit was raised greatly and crime dropped.  Hubbard says the one thing that stands out in his mind about the visit is that everyone worked extremely well with each other on the project and made it a productive, smooth-running process.  They also got lots of cooperation from many different organizations.  Hubbard says her favorite moment from Mandelaâ€™s visit was when he thanked her at his press conference.  \r\n	The show breaks with more footage from one of Mandelaâ€™s speeches, and then returns with two journalists who got to follow Mandela during his travel across the country: Detroit Free Press columnist Susan Watson, and WDIV reporter and anchorman Emery King.  Watson first talks about the difficulty to be objective as a journalist when Mandelaâ€™s visit was so moving for all involved.  King says the first time he saw Mandela was in Toronto, and says that at that moment he was simply in awe of Mandela.  \r\n	They then show clips from each of Mandelaâ€™s stops, alternating with comments from the journalists, starting in Harlem, New York.  Watson says that at his speech there, people got a true sense of his strength, his mission, and his seriousness about what he wants for his country and the world.  Gallant talks about how Mandela voiced his support for leaders such as Castro, and says she was a bit surprised that he didnâ€™t receive a little more criticism for these views.  King responds by saying that Mandela diffused the issue himself, and didnâ€™t leave any room for criticism.  The second clip they look at is from Boston, where Winnie Mandela also spoke.  King says that this stop-off, where Mandela danced along with the crowd to the music that followed his speech, was his single favorite moment from the tour.  Watson also makes the point that Boston was much more like home than any of the other cities.  They also talk about the issue of not hearing much from Winnie Mandela, and Watson says that she thinks this was intentional, especially because she had been heard from so much before her husband was released, and also because she faced some troubles at home, such as the fact that a young man was killed by her body guards, and she had made some controversial statements.  Gallant also talks about how the audience was much more integrated, and King agrees that the audience was much whiter, but says that there were still racial problems going on in the city before his speech.  The third stop-off they discuss was Mandelaâ€™s trip to Washington, where, in an unusual turn, he surprisingly stood up to President Bush.  King says Washington was significant because he came there to take care of business.  They also talk about how they worked hard to keep from injecting the controversy from the Marion Barry problems into Mandelaâ€™s affairs.  \r\n	They then move on to talk about Mandelaâ€™s visit to Atlanta, which was so symbolic because it was the heart of the American Civil Rights Movement.  King describes this stop as the â€œleast frenetic,â€ and then they move on to show a clip and talk about Mandelaâ€™s stop in Miami.  This was a quick stop, and he faced a good deal of resistance to his visit, because he angered many Cuban-Americans with his statements of support for Fidel Castro.  They finally move on to Detroit, and they talk about the feeling of bonding and kinship that was present in Detroit.  King says that he was at the airport for Mandelaâ€™s arrival, as well as the rally at the Tigers Stadium, and says that this was the most powerful rally of all.  Gallant says that the one downside about Detroit was that there were certain politicians who were rubbed the wrong way because they werenâ€™t invited to certain things.  Watson says that this probably could have been avoided, but that it is politics, but that they can learn from this that they donâ€™t have time for in-fighting and should focus on the more pressing problems facing them.  \r\n');
